(149, 'Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert', 1, 'indie-singer-aw-shines-at-living-room-concert', '', 'Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert', 'Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert', 'Indie singer-songwriter A.W. blew the crowd away Monday at a living room show at Outpost Club\'s East Williamsburg House.', '<p>Indie singer-songwriter A.W. blew the crowd away Monday at a living room show at Outpost Club\'s East Williamsburg House.</p>', '<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">by Lauren Vega</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/listentoaw/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Indie singer-songwriter A.W.</a> was writing songs about their queerness before they had even realized they&rsquo;re queer. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&ldquo;I wrote this a couple years before I came out to myself; I was just like hoping someone would hear it and be like, &lsquo;Yo, are you gay?&rsquo;&rdquo; they said of 2009&rsquo;s &ldquo;Fingers Crossed.&rdquo; &ldquo;I was too vague with my metaphors, though.&rdquo; </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A.W., who came out as non-binary last summer and uses they/them pronouns, told Monday night\'s crowd at Outpost Club&rsquo;s East Williamsburg House&nbsp;how their journey as a trans person has impacted their music -- and in more ways than one. They&rsquo;ve had to adjust their older songs to account for how their voice has deepened, and changing their name has meant having to work hard to keep old fans aware that they&rsquo;re still active on the indie scene. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Most of their music feels almost universally relatable: Themes of lost love, anxiety and starting over mingle with songs about accepting yourself and living your truth to paint a complex portrait of the artist who wrote them. A.W. certainly doesn&rsquo;t shy away from writing about queerness; it just feels like a common thread woven throughout their body of work rather than the main focus. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&ldquo;It&rsquo;s about gay stuff in that it&rsquo;s about human stuff,&rdquo; they said about &ldquo;The Same,&rdquo; from their 2015 album </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">New Love. </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The song is one of those universally relatable ones that has complex layers; most of us have felt lonely and sad at some point in our lives, but as A.W. tells their story of finding their truth and starting to transition, the words take on new meaning: </span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&ldquo;Does anybody wonder how it ever got this bad?</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\"Does anybody wish that they could change the way they are?</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">...</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\"We all got feelings that we can\'t explain</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\"We\'re all a little bit the same.&rdquo;</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/44243097_2295228283834958_6606981056526548992_n.jpg\" alt=\"Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://open.spotify.com/artist/5UYzEUYfzFL4lzleHOXGjp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">A.W.&rsquo;s sound</a> typically leans more toward indie pop, but for the living room show -- part of the Alone Not Lonely U.S. tour -- they went for a more mellow vibe. It was a &ldquo;Monday night feelings fest,&rdquo; they said, but the mood in the crowded room was still jovial as the artist joked about the time a guy they had a crush on showed them the </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Buffy the Vampire Slayer </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">episode in which (spoiler alert) her mom dies, and they went home and wept -- but ultimately &ldquo;it&rsquo;s fine, because I&rsquo;m gay.&rdquo; </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Or the time they were on their way to New York City for the first time on tour and had no idea what to expect, leading them to think the lights of a random New Jersey town were the lights of New York City. That experience led them to write &ldquo;Ghost Stories,&rdquo; a contemplative ballad about the promise of the future and the shadows of our past:</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&ldquo;We got lost in New York, but the view from the bridge</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\"It was beautiful that night, all those lights, those lights.&rdquo;</span></em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If anyone would be able to capture how limitless it feels to see New York City for the first time, it&rsquo;s A.W.; they hail from Georgia but lived in Brooklyn for a few years after college. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&ldquo;I love Brooklyn,&rdquo; they said. &ldquo;This is a beautiful, magical place.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/44264709_2269185819975845_2173294176655900672_n_1.jpg\" alt=\"Indie singer A.W. shines at living room concert (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<h5>Photos: Lindsay Turberville</h5>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '44291742_186932575518008_4600589785734578176_n.jpg', 1, '2018-10-17 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(147, '#MemberMonday: Garazi Prieto', 1, 'membermonday-garazi-prieto', '', '#MemberMonday: Garazi Prieto', '#MemberMonday: Garazi Prieto', 'Meet an Outpost Club member who has been working with DoubleTake Dance in New York City: Garazi Prieto. ', '<p>This week at Outpost, we\'re profiling Garazi Prieto, an promising dancer who is on her second tour of New York and has her final performance here this week. Here\'s what she had to say about dancing and the Outpost Club experience.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>This week at Outpost, we\'re profiling Garazi Prieto, an promising dancer who is on her second tour of New York and has her final performance here this week. Here\'s what she had to say about dancing and the Outpost Club experience.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"#MemberMonday: Garazi Prieto (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/Garazi%20Prieto%20Member%20Monday.png\" alt=\"#MemberMonday: Garazi Prieto (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h3>Tell us a little about yourself&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m from Basque Country and am 25 years old. I also came to New York last year to live in Outpost. The first time I came to New York it was for like two weeks to do some dance training. Vanessa Martinez De Ba&ntilde;os and Ashley Carter with DoubleTake Dance have known me since I was 18 and have seen me grow up as a dancer, and they invited me to come. That&rsquo;s why I&rsquo;m back again this year. I don&rsquo;t know if I&rsquo;ll be back next year, but I hope I can come soon.</p>\r\n<p>Aside from dancing, I like to draw and go to movies. I like the designer world -- making clothes. I studied that for two years and I&rsquo;d like to keep doing that along with dancing.</p>\r\n<h3>How did you get into dance? Why do you love dancing?</h3>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve been dancing almost my whole life. At 9 I started doing rhythmic gymnastics, and then I changed to ballet at 15 because I was seeing that my career as a gymnast was ending and I wanted to keep being involved in that art. The most inspiring thing for me was ballet dance. From ballet I started going to new classes: contemporary, jazz and hip-hop.</p>\r\n<p>I love dance because think it&rsquo;s my way of living. I just feel free when I&rsquo;m moving. It&rsquo;s a way to express the things that I cannot speak.</p>\r\n<h3>Tell us about your performance this week</h3>\r\n<p>When I came here this performance was already planned, but we also did the StylePointe show in September with the company I&rsquo;m working with. This piece is called &ldquo;passage and perceptions.&rdquo; We&rsquo;ve been rehearsing for weeks.</p>\r\n<p>For me it&rsquo;s a new piece, but they&rsquo;ve already done it before. I really like the view it gives of the timing of our lives. This will be performed in Dixon Place at 7:30 p.m. It&rsquo;s Oct. 16.</p>\r\n<h3>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory? What will you miss when you\'re gone?</h3>\r\n<p>KNICKERBOCKER. It&rsquo;s my family here. We had something special between us and we created a friendship that is not so common. The moments when we were at home and watching TV on the couch all together or going out to Carmelo&rsquo;s, I will never forget.</p>\r\n<h6><em>Photos: Lauren Vega</em></h6>', 'membermonday-garazi-prieto.JPG', 1, '2018-10-15 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(151, '12 Halloween Events to Check Out in New York City', 1, '12-halloween-events-to-check-out-in-new-york-city', '', '12 Halloween Events to Check Out in New York City', '12 Halloween Events to Check Out in New York City', 'Halloween is nearly here, so get into costume and get ready for the Outpost Club’s Halloween party on Oct. 31 and check out these other awesome Halloween events in New York City.', '<p>Halloween is nearly here, so get into costume and get ready for the Outpost Club&rsquo;s Halloween party on Oct. 31 and check out these other awesome Halloween events in New York City.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Halloween is nearly here, so get into costume and get ready for the Outpost Club&rsquo;s Halloween party on Oct. 31 starting at 8 p.m. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We&rsquo;ll have a pumpkin-carving station for those of you who want to take a (literal) stab at one of our favorite spooky traditions, and a costume contest -- so get ready to strut your stuff! We&rsquo;ll bring the snacks if you BYOB. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">RSVP on Facebook</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Want to know what else New York has in store for the rest of the month? Check out these Halloween events: </span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Nightmare Machine</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Explore the nine-room Nightmare Machine experience by the makers of Dream Machine throughout October. The rooms are built to be Instagrammable and the creators say Nightmare Machine is &ldquo;not a haunted house, but inspired by them.&rdquo;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>A Haunting at Hendrick&rsquo;s</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Costumes are required at the Halloween cocktail party being held at the 298-year-old Hendrick I. Lott House. Cocktails and hors d\'oeuvres will be served and proceeds from the $75 ticket price benefit the Hendrick I. Lott House. </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 20, 7 p.m. - 10 p.m. | 1940 E. 36th Street, Marine Park</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Michael Alan Alien&rsquo;s Dark Side of the Moon</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This glow-in-the-dark Halloween special performance art piece will mix sound, color and light for a psychedelic experience in the artist&rsquo;s private studio. Admission is $20. </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 20, 8 p.m. - midnight | 566 Johnson Ave., Bushwick</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Zombie Prom</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Work your best zombie look out on the dance floor at House of Yes. Free drinks will be awarded for standout zombie costumes, and you&rsquo;ll even get to elect a zombie prom king and queen. No cover. </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 24, 10 p.m. - 4 a.m. | 2 Wyckoff Ave., Bushwick</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>The Library After Hours: Halloween Masquerade</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Get your literary costume judged by Tim Gunn and enjoy frightful films, drinks, dancing, a display of the spookiest items from library&rsquo;s vast collections. A $15 ticket gets you guaranteed entry from 7-8PM and 10-percent off at the bar. </span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 26, 7 p.m. | Stephen A. Schwarzman Building, Fifth Avenue at 42nd Street, Midtown</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Threes Brewing Halloween Bash</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Take advantage of food and drink specials, along with tarot readings, a DJ, a costume contest and more. This event is very near our&nbsp;Downtown Brooklyn House </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 27, 7 p.m. - late</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> | </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">333 Douglass St., Boerum Hill</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>World of Whimsy Halloween Party </strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There will be burlesque performances, contortionist dancers and fire breathing by The Hive Fire -- along with small bites and themed signature cocktails -- at the Westlight rooftop bar. Tickets start at $70. </span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 27, 7 p.m.-2 a.m. | 111 North 12th St., Williamsburg</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Dewey&rsquo;s Pub &lsquo;90s Halloween</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Bring back the decade that brought us Britney Spears and the Furby at a throwback dance party. $15 gets you an open vodka bar from 9 p.m.-10 p.m.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 27, 9 p.m.-late | 135 W 30th St., Chelsea</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>&lsquo;80s party at The Happiest Hour</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&lsquo;80s movies will be screened and food and drink specials will be plentiful, so break out your leg warmers and find your scrunchies for an &lsquo;80s Halloween party at The Happiest Hour.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 30, 121 W. 10th St., Greenwich Village</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>80s GLOW at Sunday in Brooklyn</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;re a fan of Netflix&rsquo;s show about a group of female wrestlers in the &lsquo;80s, head to Sunday in Brooklyn on Halloween for neon face painting, tattoo artists, impersonators, neon robots, break-dancers and more. $55 include snacks and two drinks. Reservations must be made in advance. </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Oct. 31, 8 p.m. - 12 a.m. </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">| </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">348 Wythe Ave., Williamsburg</span></em></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Village Halloween Parade</strong></h3>\r\n<p>No list would be complete without mentioning the Village Halloween Parade, now entering its 45th year. The costumed public is welcome to participate in one of the largest shows of Halloween creativity in the U.S. every year, so get your costume ready and get more information here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Oct. 31, 7 p.m. | 6th Avenue and Canal Street</em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Photo credit: Jason Smith/Flickr</strong></em></p>', '2991540623_b9be47ede2_z.jpg', 1, '2018-10-18 05:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0),
(153, 'Ask a House Leader: How Does Getting Mail Work?', 1, 'ask-a-house-leader-how-does-getting-mail-work', '', 'Ask a House Leader: How Does Getting Mail Work?', 'Ask a House Leader: How Does Getting Mail Work?', 'We’re launching a new series, Ask a House Leader. We want you to always be comfortable talking about questions and concerns, but you can also ask questions here.', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our house leaders are vital to Outpost and their wells of knowledge run deep. That&rsquo;s why we&rsquo;re launching a new series, Ask a House Leader. We want you to always be comfortable talking about questions and concerns, but you can also ask questions here. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At Outpost, your house leader is someone you&rsquo;re going to want to get to know very well. They&rsquo;re your main connection to the company and will be there for you if you have questions about Outpost or if you need help with anything. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While we&rsquo;re all responsible for keeping the environment in our houses respectful, the house leaders are there to make sure things are in the best shape possible, whether that means keeping the house organized and essentials restocked or making sure quiet hours remain quiet hours.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our house leaders are vital to Outpost and their wells of knowledge run deep. That&rsquo;s why we&rsquo;re launching a new series, Ask a House Leader. We want you to always be comfortable talking about questions and concerns, but you can also ask questions here. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This week&rsquo;s first question is one we get often: </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How does getting mail work at </span></em><a href=\"../our-houses\" target=\"_blank\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outpost houses</span></em></a><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">? </span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>House Leader: </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Great question! The house leader at every house should be the one to keep the mail keys. House leaders are responsible for checking the mail every day and leaving it in a centralized location in the house; it might be on a shelf in the hallway or on the kitchen table, so ask your specific house leader what to expect. If you know something has been delivered and the mail hasn&rsquo;t been checked yet that day you can definitely ask your house leader to check for you. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The only exception would be if you happen to be at a house that is between leaders -- if that&rsquo;s the case, the key should be kept in a central location so everyone can check.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Ask a House Leader: How Does Getting Mail Work? (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/Screen%20Shot%202018-10-24%20at%2012.53.30%20PM.png\" alt=\"Ask a House Leader: How Does Getting Mail Work? (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Question: What is it like running a house? What do you even do? </span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>HL: </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">House leaders stay busy! We do more than restock cleaning supplies and make sure the dishes are done, although both of those things are important. We also take care of all of the move-ins and move-outs every week, help plan and execute events, make sure things stay clean and organized, show our houses, and -- one of the most important functions, in my opinion -- act as a main point of contact for the house. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That means we&rsquo;re the ones you can talk to if you&rsquo;re unsure how to extend your stay or if you notice the coffee maker is broken. We&rsquo;re here to answer your questions, give you support if needed and overall make sure every member has a great stay. If we don&rsquo;t know the answer to your question, we&rsquo;ll find out, so keep them coming! </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you have a question? Email </span></em><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">lauren.vega@outpost-club.com</span></em><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and we&rsquo;ll answer it in an upcoming column. Don&rsquo;t worry; you&rsquo;ll remain anonymous. </span></em></p>', 'mailboxes.jpg', 1, '2018-10-23 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(154, 'Introducing the New Outpost Club Member Portal', 1, 'introducing-the-new-outpost-club-member-portal', '', 'Introducing the New Outpost Club Member Portal', 'Introducing the New Outpost Club Member Portal', 'We’re excited to show you around the new and improved Outpost Club member portal, your resource for all things Outpost. ', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We&rsquo;re excited to show you around the new and improved </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outpost Club member portal</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, your resource for all things Outpost. It&rsquo;s here that you can view upcoming events, submit event requests, submit technical problems, and more.</span></p>', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We&rsquo;re excited to show you around the new and improved </span><a href=\"../user/login\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outpost Club member portal</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, your resource for all things Outpost. It&rsquo;s here that you can view upcoming events, submit event requests, submit technical problems, and more. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The game-changer with this latest update to the portal is the new notifications panel, where you can view new events and messages from Outpost. You can even view and pay your monthly invoice in the panel, located at the top of the screen after you log in. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another convenient feature of the new member portal is the technical request form, which you can find linked at the top right of the page when you log in. You&rsquo;re still welcome to report technical issues like burnt-out lightbulbs to your house leader, who will then make sure they get taken care of, but now you can also submit them directly to Outpost. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Just click the red &ldquo;Technical Request&rdquo; button in the top right corner, fill out your information, the urgency (try not to abuse the &ldquo;urgent&rdquo; options), and a description of the problem. Including a photo, if you have one, is always helpful. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Click &ldquo;Submit&rdquo; and you&rsquo;re good to go.</span></p>\r\n<p><video controls=\"controls\" width=\"100%\" height=\"600\">\r\n<source src=\"../files/uploads/blog/technical%20request%20tutorial.mov\" /></video></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Below your notification panel you&rsquo;ll find your events calendar, as before. Visit the centralized events page and you&rsquo;ll find a simplified process for submitting your RSVP to Outpost events: Just click &ldquo;Member&rdquo; then &ldquo;RSVP&rdquo; and you&rsquo;ll see a confirmation screen for your order. If it&rsquo;s a paid event, you&rsquo;ll be prompted to enter your payment information and get a confirmation. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Remember that for free events, you also have the option to RSVP on the event listing in the </span><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/outpostclub/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outpost Club private Facebook group</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As always, you can access your important documents and view the house leaders and staff on the portal, as well as find information on how to reach Outpost staff and Customer Service. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;re a current member, check your email for your username and password to log in. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We hope your new member portal will help you make the most of your experience at Outpost Club. Let us know if there&rsquo;s something you&rsquo;d love to see in the next iteration! </span></p>', 'Screen Shot 2018-10-26 at 12.52.51 PM.png', 1, '2018-10-26 05:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0),
(155, '#MemberMonday: Mandy Otero', 1, 'membermonday-mandy-otero', '', '#MemberMonday: Mandy Otero', '#MemberMonday: Mandy Otero', 'Today’s #MemberMonday post is about Mandy Otero, from East Bushwick House. Mandy wants to be a screenwriter in New York City and is well on her way to making her dreams come true.\r\n', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Today&rsquo;s #MemberMonday post is about Mandy Otero, from </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Bushwick House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Mandy wants to be a screenwriter in New York City and is well on her way to making her dreams come true. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Today&rsquo;s #MemberMonday post is about Mandy Otero, from </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Bushwick House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Mandy wants to be a screenwriter in New York City and is well on her way to making her dreams come true. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"7 #MemberMonday: Mandy Otero (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/Mandy%20Otero.png\" alt=\"#MemberMonday: Mandy Otero (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<h3>Tell us a bit about yourself.</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I&rsquo;m originally from Monterrey, Mexico, and I developed a passion for cinema when I was like 9. I saw the movie </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Schindler&rsquo;s List</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> without my parents&rsquo; permission and it blew my mind, and I decided I wanted to work in film. I made it a goal of mine early on that I wanted to move to New York, so I dropped out of college and moved here in January. </span></p>\r\n<h3>Why do you like Outpost Club?</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I like the people. I enjoy the company of individuals that I otherwise would not have met. </span></p>\r\n<h3>What&rsquo;s your favorite Outpost memory?</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I went to Coney Island with some&nbsp;Outpost people for the Mermaid Day parade and got lost inside the amusement park. We were looking for a roller coaster and had a map and couldn&rsquo;t find it anywhere, so we just stopped and got a funnel cake. </span></p>\r\n<h3>What are you working on now?</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Right now I&rsquo;m developing a web-series with two New York-based actresses. We&rsquo;re entering pre-production for the pilot that we&rsquo;ll use to crowdfund the rest of the series. It&rsquo;s a series about two women who become best friends and have to navigate the complicated life of young adults in this world trying to figure out their sexuality and gender expression.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'Mandy Otero.png', 1, '2018-10-29 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(404, 'Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes?', 1, 'why-do-so-many-nyc-buildings-remind-us-of-giant-wedding-cakes', '', 'Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes?', 'Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes?', '', '<p>You don&rsquo;t have to spend much time in New York to appreciate what makes the city&rsquo;s skyline unique: Everywhere you look, you can see the fingerprint of the century-old policy that led to the waves of progressively smaller tiers you can often see as you near the upper floors of high rises here, making the buildings look not unlike sharp-edged wedding cakes.</p>', '<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/building-1.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-1)\" /></p>\r\n<p>You don&rsquo;t have to spend much time in New York to appreciate what makes the city&rsquo;s skyline unique: Everywhere you look, you can see the fingerprint of the century-old policy that led to the waves of progressively smaller tiers you can often see as you near the upper floors of high rises here, making the buildings look not unlike sharp-edged wedding cakes.</p>\r\n<p>The tiers you can see on many of New York&rsquo;s most well-known buildings, including the Empire State Building above, may seem like nothing more than a stylistic choice &mdash; but they&rsquo;re actually thanks to a rule put in place more than a century ago to make sure natural light and fresh air could reach people at the ground level.</p>\r\n<p>The decades before World War II saw rapid development in New York City, and with bulky new buildings came increasing fears that those buildings would block too much light and stifle the movement of fresh air. The final straw was the construction of the 38-story Equitable Building, a behemoth that blocked sunlight from reaching the surrounding area:</p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/the-equitable-building.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-2)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>The Equitable Building</em></p>\r\n<p>The Equitable Building proved to be so controversial upon completion in 2015 that the City responded by passing the 1916 Zoning Resolution, the first citywide zoning ordinance in the U.S. The Zoning Resolution required all new buildings of a certain height to get narrower as they got taller, ensuring that our crowded sidewalks wouldn&rsquo;t live in darkness around the clock. In 1961, the resolution was updated to allow developers to build higher without setbacks as long as they provided adjacent space that was open to the public. So next time you take a break in a pocket park in Manhattan, you can thank the Zoning Resolution of 1961.</p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/manhattan-1940s.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-3)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>Manhattan in the 1940s. You can see the impact of the 1916 Zoning Resolution throughout.</em></p>\r\n<p>The setbacks can be found all over the city and internationally, but are especially noticeable on some of Manhattan&rsquo;s most well-known buildings, including the Empire State Building, Chrysler Building, the New Yorker hotel, the American Radiator Building and many more. The setback style ended up influencing architecture across the U.S. and internationally, but nowhere is it more concentrated than where it all began, right here in New York.</p>\r\n<p>Are any of your favorite New York buildings in the photos below?</p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/empire-state.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-4)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>Empire State Building</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/new-yorker.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-5)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>The New Yorker hotel</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-6), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/wall-street.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-6)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>120 Wall Street</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-7), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/french-building.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-7)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>Fred F. French Building</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-8), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/midtown-manhattan.jpg\" alt=\"Why do so many NYC buildings remind us of giant wedding cakes? (Image-8)\" /></p>\r\n<p><em>Midtown Manhattan</em></p>', 'building-1.jpg', 0, '2022-03-30 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(158, '7 Ways to Enjoy Autumn in Brooklyn', 1, '7-ways-to-enjoy-autumn-in-brooklyn', '', '7 Ways to Enjoy Autumn in Brooklyn', '7 Ways to Enjoy Autumn in Brooklyn', 'There’s still plenty to take advantage of before the colorful leaves give way to gray slush -- here are seven suggestions to make the most of the rest of autumn in Brooklyn.', '<p>There&rsquo;s still plenty to take advantage of before the colorful leaves give way to gray slush -- here are seven suggestions to make the most of the rest of autumn in Brooklyn.</p>', '<p>Autumn is a wonderful time of year in New York City: The horrific temperatures of underground subway stops cool down, the leaves change and, as F. Scott Fitzgerald wrote, &ldquo;Life starts all over again when it gets crisp in the fall.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s still plenty to take advantage of before the colorful leaves give way to gray slush -- here are seven suggestions to make the most of the rest of the season.</p>\r\n<h3>Have a picnic in Prospect Park</h3>\r\n<p>The fall foliage in Prospect Park is stunning right now; it&rsquo;s the perfect time to take one last stroll under the colorful canopy and set up a picnic brunch before winter comes. The park, Brooklyn&rsquo;s second-largest, is also home to Brooklyn&rsquo;s only lake, which only adds to the beauty of the trees changing color throughout the month.</p>\r\n<div class=\"hs-responsive-embed hs-responsive-embed-instagram\"><iframe class=\"hs-responsive-embed-iframe\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"//instagram.com/p/Bp7jlSNFZG8/embed/\" width=\"425\" height=\"505\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" data-service=\"instagram\"></iframe></div>\r\n<h3><strong>Go on an art walk around Bushwick </strong></h3>\r\n<p>A section of the L train route easily accessible from our Bushwick and East Bushwick houses is bursting with color around every corner, so grab your scarf and some coffee and get ready to take a self-guided tour of one of Bushwick&rsquo;s most vibrant neighborhoods.</p>\r\n<p>Get off the L at the Morgan stop if you want to see the street art gradually transform from graffiti to permission-based murals; otherwise, hop off at Jefferson to start right in the thick of things. Wandering around the blocks surrounding the stop will take you right through the well-known Bushwick Collective murals that are a constant draw for locals and tourists alike, and you can find more as you walk toward the DeKalb stop.</p>\r\n<div class=\"hs-responsive-embed hs-responsive-embed-instagram\"><iframe class=\"hs-responsive-embed-iframe\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"//instagram.com/p/Bp3S64oHCpd/embed/\" width=\"425\" height=\"505\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" data-service=\"instagram\"></iframe></div>\r\n<h3><strong>Take a walk through Brooklyn Heights </strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The historic Brooklyn Heights is beautiful at any time of year, but something about the leaves changing really makes it shine in autumn. The tree-lined streets and centuries-old brownstones feel so quintessentially Brooklyn that you can&rsquo;t help but to take your time and drink it all in. Head toward DUMBO and you&rsquo;ll hit the fruit streets -- Cranberry, Orange and Pineapple -- which look (and sound) like they&rsquo;ve been plucked out of a children&rsquo;s book set in New York, in addition to having great views of the city.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Bike the Brooklyn Bridge</h3>\r\n<p>The view from the Brooklyn Bridge is great regardless of what time of year you visit, but autumn is where the bridge really shines: You don&rsquo;t have to deal with the humidity of the summer, but it&rsquo;s not yet too cold to keep you indoors. If you don&rsquo;t have a bike, your best bet is to rent a Citi Bike for $3 from one of the three closest stations to the Brooklyn side: Front St./ Washington St., Henry St./Poplar St. and Cadman Plaza E/Red Cross Pl. Your best bet to avoid crowds is to go during the week; the bike lanes can get crowded with pedestrians on the weekend.</p>\r\n<div class=\"hs-responsive-embed hs-responsive-embed-instagram\"><iframe class=\"hs-responsive-embed-iframe\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"//instagram.com/p/Bp7n60QlsM6/embed/\" width=\"425\" height=\"505\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" data-service=\"instagram\"></iframe></div>\r\n<h3>Check out the shops in Cobble Hill and Boerum Hill</h3>\r\n<p>Just a short walk from our <a href=\"../the-downtown-brooklyn-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Downtown Brooklyn House</a> is a plethora of indie shops ranging from decades-old family-run businesses to trendy new shops. Head to Court Street to find a bustling area packed to the brim with shopping, eateries and bars. Walk down Smith Street to find an eclectic mix of boutiques, bars and a few indie bookstores. It&rsquo;s the perfect neighborhood to grab a coffee and see where your feet take you.</p>\r\n<div class=\"hs-responsive-embed hs-responsive-embed-instagram\"><iframe class=\"hs-responsive-embed-iframe\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"//instagram.com/p/BPTzMFxB0st/embed/\" width=\"425\" height=\"505\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" data-service=\"instagram\"></iframe></div>\r\n<h3><strong>Get some cider at Brooklyn Cider House</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Brooklyn&rsquo;s first cidery hasn&rsquo;t even been open a year yet, but has already undergone an expansion and become a local favorite. </span><a href=\"https://www.brooklynciderhouse.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Brooklyn Cider House</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> makes cider in the traditional Basque style with apples sourced from its own orchard in New Paltz, New York, and has plentiful seasonal food pairing options, as well. This time of year is perfect for drinking cider because the apple harvest wraps up in early October. </span></p>\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<h3>Visit the Brooklyn Botanic Garden</h3>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.bbg.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Brooklyn Botanic Garden</a> is the perfect respite from the hustle of city life. It has 52 acres of gardens and conservatories and regularly holds events and tours, although visitors are welcome to visit just to take in the sites. Look for the katsura tree, just east of Oak Circle, which is one of the of the oldest trees in the garden and at its most spectacular in autumn.</p>\r\n<div class=\"hs-responsive-embed hs-responsive-embed-instagram\"><iframe class=\"hs-responsive-embed-iframe\" style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"//instagram.com/p/Bp0XqcdlRn_/embed/\" width=\"425\" height=\"505\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" data-service=\"instagram\"></iframe></div>\r\n<div class=\"hs-responsive-embed hs-responsive-embed-instagram\">&nbsp;</div>', 'brooklyn fall.jpg', 1, '2018-11-08 06:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0),
(159, '#MemberMonday: Gian Luca Abbate', 1, 'membermonday-gian-luca-abbate', '', '#MemberMonday: Gian Luca Abbate', '#MemberMonday: Gian Luca Abbate', 'For this week\'s #MemberMonday, we talked to Gian Lucca Abbate, Outpost Club\'s Bed-Stuy House leader. Gian Luca is from Milan, Italy, and is visiting New York for the autumn. ', '<p>For this week\'s #MemberMonday, we talked to Gian Lucca Abbate, Outpost Club\'s Bed-Stuy House leader. Gian Luca is from Milan, Italy, and is visiting New York for the autumn.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>For this week\'s #MemberMonday, we talked to Gian Lucca Abbate, Outpost Club\'s <a href=\"../the-bed-stuy-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bed-Stuy House</a> leader. Gian Luca is from Milan, Italy, and is visiting New York for the autumn.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"#MemberMonday: Gian Luca Abbate (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/gian%20luca%20abbate.JPG\" alt=\"#MemberMonday: Gian Luca Abbate (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h3>Tell us a bit about yourself.&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m Gian Luca and I&rsquo;m from Italy! I have both Italian and Swedish origins since my dad is from Sweden.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In January I&rsquo;ll move to Stockholm, where I&rsquo;m starting my university studies all in English (I\'m studying economics), and for this reason after I finished high school in July I decided to improve my English by having a three-month experience in a country where they speak English as a first language.</p>\r\n<p>Since I have been in love with the U.S. since I was a child, I decided to come to this country. Now I&rsquo;m the house leader at Bed-Stuy House and in my free time I like going to the gym, exploring New York and especially spending time with my housemates!<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h3>What\'s your favorite thing about Outpost Club?</h3>\r\n<p>The thing I love the most about Outpost is the environment inside the houses. It&rsquo;s a really good way to learn how to live and share experiences with other people. It&rsquo;s always nice to spend time together in the house and to know that you have someone to talk to when you get home.</p>\r\n<h3>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</h3>\r\n<p>My favorite memory from living in the Bed-Stuy House would be the Sunday brunch! It&rsquo;s really nice sharing a meal with my housemates, talking and eating together, and, of course,&nbsp;spending the entire evening&nbsp;in the common area watching TV and movies with my friends from the house!</p>\r\n<h3>What\'s your favorite part of Brooklyn? Where do you still want to explore?&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p>Since I really like to explore this big and beautiful city, I\'ve visited almost every part of Brooklyn -- even though I haven\'t yet visited the Bay Ridge neighborhood and Prospect Park.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>My favorite part of Brooklyn is definitely downtown and DUMBO. You have a beautiful view on the skyline of lower Manhattan and you can find many spots to watch the sunset over this amazing city!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'gian luca abbate.JPG', 1, '2018-11-12 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(160, 'How to Pull Off a Great Friendsgiving', 1, 'how-to-pull-off-a-great-friendsgiving', '', 'How to Pull Off a Great Friendsgiving', 'How to Pull Off a Great Friendsgiving', 'Break out your stretchy pants and get ready for a Friendsgiving to remember. Here are some tips for making it fun for everyone. ', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Break out your stretchy pants and get ready for a Friendsgiving to remember. Here are some tips for making it fun for everyone.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I was never a big fan of Thanksgiving growing up, but Friendsgiving has developed into one of my favorite holiday traditions as an adult. The beautiful thing about celebrating Thanksgiving with friends is that you can do it however you&rsquo;d like; no tradition is too holy to exclude, no practice too silly to include. What&rsquo;s important is just being around people who mean something to you. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Friendsgiving holds even more potential this year, as so many people at Outpost Club have never taken part in a traditional American Thanksgiving dinner. So break out your stretchy pants and get ready for a Friendsgiving to remember, keeping the following in mind:</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>The more, the merrier -- but be considerate</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s in the name: Friendsgiving is for friends. Be courteous of your other housemates, though, and ask permission before you invite anyone else -- unless you all have a prior understanding that the dinner is open-invitation.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Keep dietary needs in mind</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Whether you&rsquo;re bringing a side dish or hosting the main event, don&rsquo;t forget to consider the dietary needs of your dinner guests. Vegetarianism and veganism are common enough today that most dinners will need to include separate dishes, and it never hurts to ask about food allergies, either. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Not every dish has to fit in with the dietary specifications of the pickier guests, but people will be grateful for options. If you&rsquo;re a guest, ask your host if there are any dietary needs you should be aware of. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"How to Pull Off a Great Friendsgiving (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/pumpkin%20pie.jpg\" alt=\"How to Pull Off a Great Friendsgiving (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Set up stations</h3>\r\n<p>Some of the same pitfalls of Thanksgiving apply to dinner with friends: The more people you have, the more likely it is that you won&rsquo;t be able to handle everything at once in a single kitchen.</p>\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s where stations come in: Recruit volunteers to put together sides and salads outside of the main kitchen. If you live at Outpost Club, you&rsquo;re lucky; <a href=\"../our-houses\">most of our houses</a> have more than one kitchen in which you can spread out and prepare your meal.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Introduce your own traditions</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you have a specialty dish your family begs for? Are you a whiz at making a beautiful ratatouille, or did you grow up making tamales with your family before every holiday? One of the great things about Friendsgiving is that you aren&rsquo;t stuck with the traditions of a single family, so don&rsquo;t feel limited to the traditional American Thanksgiving sides like stuffing and mashed potatoes if you&rsquo;re trying to decide what kind of dish to bring to dinner. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Conversely, if you&rsquo;ve never celebrated an American Thanksgiving, you may want to experience some for the first time: set out that morning to watch the Macy&rsquo;s Thanksgiving Day Parade, go around the table to share something you&rsquo;re thankful for or make a wish as you pull the wishbone with a friend.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Enjoy the celebration</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ultimately, it doesn&rsquo;t matter where the food came from or who cooked it; quality time is the real point of Friendsgiving. So grab a drink, pull up a chair and get ready to have some fun, because nothing is more Thanksgiving than sharing a meal with family, whether it&rsquo;s the one you&rsquo;re born into or the one you&rsquo;ve chosen for yourself. </span></p>', 'thanksgiving dinner-min.jpg', 1, '2018-11-14 06:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0);
