(220, 'How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays', 1, 'how-outpost-club-celebrated-the-holidays', '', 'How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays', 'How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays', 'We love a good reason to throw a party here at Outpost Club, and with the holidays in full swing, we took the opportunity to take part in some of our favorite holiday traditions. ', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We love a good reason to throw a party here at Outpost Club, and with the holidays in full swing, we took the opportunity to take part in some of our favorite holiday traditions. </span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We love a good reason to throw a party here at Outpost Club, and with the holidays in full swing, we took the opportunity to take part in some of our favorite holiday traditions. </span></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/_DSC0459-min.jpg\" alt=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On Christmas Eve, we gathered at our </span><a href=\"../the-bed-stuy-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bed-Stuy House</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for our Christmas bash, and spent the evening playing Cards Against Humanity, watching the Grinch and decorating gingerbread houses. </span></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/_DSC0470-min.jpg\" alt=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/_DSC0463-min.jpg\" alt=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/_DSC0485.jpg\" alt=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We kept things more low-key on Christmas Day and gathered at our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ridgewood House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for Chinese food and Christmas movies. </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Die Hard </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">and </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Love Actually </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">were on the menu for the night, which led to a spirited debate about what actually counts as a &ldquo;Christmas movie.&rdquo; </span></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/DSC06163-min.jpg\" alt=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-6), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/DSC06176-min.jpg\" alt=\"How Outpost Club celebrated the holidays (Image-6)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We had a blast spending the holidays with our members and can&rsquo;t wait for our </span><strong>New Year&rsquo;s Eve party</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> at the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Bushwick House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Hope to see you there, members and friends of Outpost!</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photos: Charlotte Ryckeboer</span></em></p>', '_DSC0404-min.jpg', 1, '2018-12-26 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(221, 'Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018', 1, 'year-in-review-how-outpost-club-spent-2018', '', 'Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018', 'Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018', 'Outpost Club has had an exciting 2018: We’ve grown by quite a bit and learned a lot -- and, most importantly of all, we’ve loved every moment we’ve been able to share with our members. ', '<p>Outpost Club has had an exciting 2018: We&rsquo;ve grown by quite a bit and learned a lot -- and, most importantly of all, we&rsquo;ve loved every moment we&rsquo;ve been able to share with our members. Here&rsquo;s a look at how we spent the year and some of the milestones we marked along the way. Here&rsquo;s to you in 2019, Outposters!</p>', '<p>Outpost Club has had an exciting 2018: We&rsquo;ve grown by quite a bit and learned a lot -- and, most importantly of all, we&rsquo;ve loved every moment we&rsquo;ve been able to share with our members. Here&rsquo;s a look at how we spent the year and some of the milestones we marked along the way. Here&rsquo;s to you in 2019, Outposters!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>We welcomed members from all over the world and all walks of life </strong></p>\r\n<p>One of our favorite things about coliving is that we have the opportunity to <a href=\"../blog_category/membermonday\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">meet so many people</a> we might not otherwise have been able to. We have members from dozens of countries and nearly every U.S. state, and whether you&rsquo;re writing the next great epic or building the next Facebook, we can guarantee there&rsquo;s someone else at Outpost who shares your interests.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>We held some killer events </strong></p>\r\n<p>We had a great time getting to know our community this year and had the opportunity to participate in some fantastic events, from <a href=\"../blog/outpost-club-at-pride\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">New York City PRIDE</a> to a special <a href=\"../blog/indie-singer-aw-shines-at-living-room-concert\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">living-room concert by indie-rock artist A.W.</a> We also kept active this year with our hiking trip to Bear Mountain, beach day and by <a href=\"../blog/outpost-club-welcomes-autumn-on-the-water\">kayaking on the East River</a>.</p>\r\n<p>A <a href=\"../blog/what-we-learned-at-outposts-blind-sculpting-party\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">blind-sculpting rooftop party</a> showed us a new way of seeing the world around us (thanks, Tacia!) and our <a href=\"../blog/membermonday-dasha-and-sputnik-yoga\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">rooftop yoga + cocktails series</a> gave everyone a reason to get moving. And that&rsquo;s just the tip of the iceberg -- we&rsquo;ve expanded our events program over the course of the year to make sure every member has a chance to get to know the entire Outpost community.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>We expanded the Outpost team</strong></p>\r\n<p>It always feels good to grow, and this year we welcomed Kijuan Smith and Lauren Vega to our team, Kijuan as our new community manager and Lauren as our social media and marketing manager. Welcome, both of you!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>We opened new houses </strong></p>\r\n<p>Not only did we open two new houses in Brooklyn this year -- one in East Williamsburg and one in <a href=\"../the-downtown-brooklyn-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Boerum Hill</a> -- but we also jumped across the East River to open <a href=\"../central-park-manhattan-house\" target=\"_blank\">our first house in Manhattan</a>, right by Central Park.</p>\r\n<p>2018 was a grand adventure -- thanks for being with us along the way. We&rsquo;re excited to see where next year takes us!</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018 (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/Outpost%20Club%20Beach%20Day.jpg\" alt=\"Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018 (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018 (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/halloween.png\" alt=\"Year in Review: How Outpost Club Spent 2018 (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '_DSC0472-min.jpg', 1, '2018-12-28 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(222, 'Outpost Club Rings in the New Year', 1, 'outpost-club-rings-in-the-new-year', 'how-outpost-club-rang-in-the-new-year', 'Outpost Club Rings in the New Year', 'Outpost Club Rings in the New Year', 'For our New Year’s Eve house party on Monday we went all out bringing the ‘90s back to life, and Outpost Club members certainly showed up ready to time travel.', '<p>For our New Year&rsquo;s Eve house party on Monday we went all out bringing the &lsquo;90s back to life, and Outpost Club members certainly showed up ready to time travel.</p>', '<p>Britney. Christina. Pop Rocks. CDs. Slinkies. For our New Year&rsquo;s Eve house party on Monday we went all out bringing the &lsquo;90s back to life, and Outpost Club members certainly showed up ready to time travel.</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/IMG_0686.JPG\" alt=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Some of the most entertaining moments of the night came when we taught our members who didn&rsquo;t grow up playing Twister just how difficult it is to go &ldquo;left hand, green&rdquo; when you&rsquo;ve already spun a &ldquo;right foot, red.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/C4A8A943-A61B-4FCF-BADE-A4545216B638.JPG\" alt=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Thanks to everyone who turned out and turned up! Here&rsquo;s to a rockin&rsquo; new year.</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/IMG_0687.JPG\" alt=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/IMG_0689.JPG\" alt=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/IMG_0688.JPG\" alt=\"Outpost Club Rings in the New Year (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>', 'IMG_0697.JPG', 1, '2019-01-03 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(223, 'These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries', 1, 'these-are-some-of-our-favorite-ridgewood-bakeries', '', 'These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries', 'These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries', 'One thing we’re endlessly grateful for in Ridgewood is the sheer amount of delightful bakeries that dot the neighborhood', '<p>One thing we&rsquo;re endlessly grateful for in Ridgewood is the sheer amount of delightful bakeries that dot the neighborhood. The next time you&rsquo;re in the mood for something sweet, point yourself in the direction of any of these Ridgewood favorites; you won&rsquo;t be disappointed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>One thing we&rsquo;re endlessly grateful for in Ridgewood is the sheer amount of delightful bakeries that dot the neighborhood. The next time you&rsquo;re in the mood for something sweet, point yourself in the direction of any of these Ridgewood favorites; you won&rsquo;t be disappointed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Rudy&rsquo;s Pastry Shop</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Stepping into Rudy&rsquo;s kind of feels like visiting an old, small-town coffee shop, which makes sense considering it&rsquo;s been around since 1934. The inviting indoor cafe is perfect for sampling the variety of traditional and more innovative baked goods Rudy&rsquo;s offers, including s&rsquo;mores cookies and Nutella tarts. Bonus: You can even have a variety of fresh cannoli filled for you on the spot. </span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">905 Seneca Ave. </span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/39AD7495-F0CD-47EB-A243-78D4BF26A003.JPG\" alt=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>El Monta&ntilde;ero</h3>\r\n<p>El Monta&ntilde;ero isn&rsquo;t strictly a bakery, and its Colombian lunch and dinner fare certainly deserves some attention, too. But it&rsquo;s El Monta&ntilde;ero&rsquo;s phenomenal Colombian pastries and desserts that planted the restaurant firmly on this list. Find a few blocks from the Seneca Ave. or Myrtle-Wyckoff stops.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">5521 Myrtle Ave.</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/3590DF1E-39D6-474F-8D56-77EC1111F424.JPG\" alt=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Grimaldi&rsquo;s Home of Bread</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Grimaldi&rsquo;s is one of the oldest bakeries in Ridgewood and still family-owned after four generations. Nearby residents swear you can smell the freshly baked bread every morning from blocks away, and the wide variety of pastries (thanks to Grimaldi&rsquo;s being a supplier for some local grocery stores) makes it worth the walk from the Forest or Seneca Ave. M stops. </span></p>\r\n<p><em>2101 Menehan St.</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/8E9CC6F1-9E85-4FAF-A582-A4CE2A90F8A3.JPG\" alt=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Polska Piekarnia</h3>\r\n<p>Stepping into this narrow shop is like stepping through a portal right into Poland, where the cozy bakery manages to offer everything from tarts and danishes to traditional Polish burek and pierogi. There&rsquo;s also a solid stock of packaged Polish foods and other goods. Polska Piekarnia, which used to be called the Old World Bakery, is just across the intersection from the Forest Ave. M stop.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">6691 Forest Ave.</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/0A096BDA-3DBD-4504-9BC0-8B4D4EE96991.JPG\" alt=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Gwendolyn&rsquo;s Corner Shop</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Gwendolyn&rsquo;s Corner Shop is almost too adorable to feel real, with saccharine pink walls and white accents that make you feel like you&rsquo;re in a dollhouse. The baked goods from this shop near the Forest Ave. M stop are no joke, though; the large variety of offerings, custom pies and freshly baked bread are sure to keep you coming back for more. </span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">818 Woodward Ave.</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/1E99C05F-13D9-4339-99C2-BF02604917A1.JPG\" alt=\"These Are Some of Our Favorite Ridgewood Bakeries (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Bonus: Joel&rsquo;s Bakery</h3>\r\n<p>I probably walked right past Joel&rsquo;s Bakery, off the Myrtle-Wyckoff stop -- and technically about 20 steps outside of Ridgewood (in Bushwick) -- dozens of times before noticing it, but I&rsquo;m glad I finally did. The tiny storefront opens into a Mexican-Caribbean bakery with stacks of fresh bread and loads of tasty treats. They also do full-scale custom cakes for special occasions. You can basically stumble into Joel&rsquo;s as you get off the train at Myrtle-Wyckoff, so there&rsquo;s no reason not to take a peek inside.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">1615 Palmetto St., Bushwick, Brooklyn</span></em></p>', 'BD617C05-400B-4E7C-9134-2615A8F77FA0.JPG', 1, '2019-01-04 06:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0),
(225, 'What to Know About Having Guests at Outpost ', 1, 'what-to-know-about-having-guests-at-outpost-', '', 'What to Know About Having Guests at Outpost ', 'What to Know About Having Guests at Outpost ', 'One of the great things about Outpost members is how social they are! We love when members have friends over as long as they treat everyone with respect, but there are a couple of important things to remember.', '<p>One of the great things about Outpost members is how social they are! We love when members have friends over as long as they treat everyone with respect, but there are a couple of important things to remember.</p>', '<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At Outpost, your house leader is someone you&rsquo;re going to want to get to know very well. They&rsquo;re your main connection to the company and will be there for you if you have questions about Outpost or if you need help with anything. Our house leaders are vital to Outpost and their wells of knowledge run deep. As part of our Ask a House Leader series, here&rsquo;s an answer to one recent question for them:</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Q: Am I allowed to have people over if they don&rsquo;t live at Outpost? Can they spend the night?</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A: One of the great things about Outpost members is how social they are! We love when members have friends over as long as they treat everyone with respect, but there are a couple of important things to remember. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">First, you&rsquo;re welcome to have up to two additional guests over during the day, but there are a few things you should know about having guests over during quiet hours, including overnight (even if you have a private room):</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you want to have an overnight guest, you should let your house leader know and reach out to bookings@outpost-club.com so they can make sure there&rsquo;s room for your guest. </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There&rsquo;s a $30 fee per night for each overnight guest to account for things like cleaning and bed linens. </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You can have up to two overnight guests at a time, for up to two consecutive nights. </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Second, as an Outpost Club member, it&rsquo;s your responsibility to make sure your guests are respectful of other members. We want our houses to be comfortable and welcoming for everyone, which makes it important for guests to follow Outpost Club rules, too, including things like following quiet hours and respecting others&rsquo; belongings.</p>', 'what-to-know-about-having-guests-at-outpost.jpg', 1, '2019-01-07 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(226, '9 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know', 1, '9-things-everyone-moving-to-new-york-should-know', '', '9 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know', '9 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know', '', '', '', 'StockSnap_39D8D5F9B2.jpg', 0, '2019-01-09 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(227, '8 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know', 1, '8-things-everyone-moving-to-new-york-should-know', '', '8 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know', '8 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know', 'Moving to New York can be an overwhelming experience, but one day you’ll suddenly realize that you’re exactly where you belong', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Moving to New York can be an overwhelming experience, but one day&nbsp;you&rsquo;ll suddenly realize that you&rsquo;re exactly where you belong. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Until you get there, though, there are plenty of things to know that will make your time in New York easier.</span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Moving to New York can be an overwhelming experience, between getting to know a new city and culture and trying to figure out where you fit in the midst of it all. And then one day you&rsquo;ll give someone directions to the train and not even blink when a rat runs across your path, and you&rsquo;ll suddenly realize that you&rsquo;re exactly where you belong. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Until you get there, though, there are plenty of things to know that will make your time in <a href=\"../nyc-rooms-for-rent\" target=\"_blank\">New York</a> easier. Here are a few: </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>The subway system is an untamable beast</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">New York&rsquo;s subway system is the most expansive in the world and runs 24/7. That means you can easily get away with not setting foot behind the wheel of a car when you live here -- but it also means it&rsquo;s kind of a mess, and delays and service changes happen all the time. Just because you can take the M into the city from Brooklyn during rush hour doesn&rsquo;t mean you&rsquo;ll be able to catch it at the same time late at night or on the weekend, so it&rsquo;s important to double-check service alerts before you go out. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That said, apps like Citymapper will quickly become essential, and the $2.75 per trip won&rsquo;t seem like too big a deal once you realize that taking a taxi or Lyft is rarely faster than taking a train, but way more expensive. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Carry cash even if you don&rsquo;t think you&rsquo;ll need it</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cash is still king in many places in New York City, including at some of the family businesses that will soon become your favorites. You also never know when you&rsquo;re going to need to load your Metrocard only to find that both the machines at your station are temporarily cash only. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Learn the unspoken rules of the city</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The majority of us follow an unspoken social code that helps us survive in a city of 8.6 million. Here are a few to start you off:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Don&rsquo;t lean against subway poles, ever, and never take up more than one seat.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Stand on the right and walk on the left on escalators, but walk on the right on stairs. </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you have to stop walking to look at your phone or orient yourself, </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">don&rsquo;t do it in the middle of the sidewalk. </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Step to the side. </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Let everyone off the subway car you&rsquo;re trying to enter before you board. </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Always have your debit card, cash or Metrocard out </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">before </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">you need to use it so you don&rsquo;t hold up the line at the bodega, turnstile, etc. </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>You can have fun without spending a fortune</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Some things about living in New York are expensive, but there&rsquo;s plenty to do in the city that won&rsquo;t break the bank. There are </span><a href=\"https://www.nyc-arts.org/collections/35/free-museum-days-or-pay-what-you-wish\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">tons of museums</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that are free, take donations or have weekly or monthly free days, for instance, and public parks like Central, Prospect and Brooklyn Bridge parks are always worth a visit. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Even wandering around in new neighborhoods is a treat, from Chinatown to <a href=\"../blog/the-appeal-of-living-in-bushwick\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bushwick</a> to Astoria; there&rsquo;s something for everyone just a train ride away.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>You&rsquo;re going to want to invest in a good umbrella</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It rains more often in New York than many people realize, and with every storm come piles of $3 umbrellas abandoned on the street corners because a slight breeze flipped them inside out, rendering them useless. And once it&rsquo;s raining, that $3 umbrella is going to cost you $15, so the first time your umbrella breaks mid-storm and you show up to an event looking like a cat that got dropped into a bathtub, you&rsquo;ll realize it&rsquo;s worth it to spend a bit more on an umbrella that will last. Just make sure it&rsquo;s not gigantic. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>We&rsquo;re not trying to be rude</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We aren&rsquo;t trying to make you feel bad when we don&rsquo;t smile at you as we rush past. We&rsquo;re just in a hurry, and there are so many people in New York that if you don&rsquo;t rush to get somewhere, you aren&rsquo;t going anywhere. Don&rsquo;t expect anyone to make small talk on the subway, either: We have very little personal space and sometimes our mental space is all we have to call our own. You&rsquo;ll soon learn to value it as much as we do. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Of course, all of that goes out the window if you ask us for directions. There&rsquo;s nothing we love more than showing off our knowledge of New York&rsquo;s public transportation system (as long as you&rsquo;re quick about it).</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2><strong>You&rsquo;re going to miss out on stuff, and that&rsquo;s OK </strong></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There&rsquo;s a lot going on in New York. Between work functions, parties and other invitations, you&rsquo;ll soon realize that you&rsquo;re being pulled in a million directions every day -- and there&rsquo;s literally not time for it all. At first it will be difficult to say no when someone invites you to free drinks or a gallery opening, but you&rsquo;ll eventually realize that as much as you want to explore every inch of your new home, it&rsquo;s just as important to take time for yourself. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>That said, you should take advantage of living in the greatest city in the world</h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Being in New York is an experience like no other. Get out there are live it.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"8 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/dean-rose-602672-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"8 Things Everyone Moving to New York Should Know (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /> </span></p>', 'aaron-burson-242126-unsplash.jpg', 1, '2019-01-11 06:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0),
(228, 'How to experience New York at a discount during NYC Winter Outing', 1, 'new-york-discount-winter-outing', '', 'How to experience New York at a discount during NYC Winter Outing', 'How to experience New York at a discount during NYC Winter Outing', 'The next few weeks are the perfect opportunity to finally get out of the house and do all of the exploring you’ve been meaning to get around to since you moved to New York. ', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The next few weeks are the perfect opportunity to finally get out of the house and do all of the exploring you&rsquo;ve been meaning to get around to since you moved to New York. </span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The next few weeks are the perfect opportunity to finally get out of the house and do all of the exploring you&rsquo;ve been meaning to get around to since you moved to New York. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jan. 21 kicks off NYC Winter Outing, a combination of Broadway Week, Restaurant Week and Must-See Week -- all programs sponsored by NYC &amp; Company, the city&rsquo;s marketing agency. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During Winter Outing, you can score two-for-one tickets on a variety of Broadway shows and well-known attractions, as well as deals on prix-fixe meals, by using the code MUSTSEE19 at checkout. Get the full details at </span><strong>nycgo.com</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and check out some of our favorites below:</span></p>\r\n<h2><strong>Attractions</strong></h2>\r\n<p>Get two-for-one deals on dozens of the attractions, museums, tours and experiences New York is known for, including the Museum of Modern Art, One World Observatory, the Rink at Rockefeller Center, the Empire State Building Observatory, Radio City Music Hall, Yankee Stadium, the Bronx Zoo and more.</p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Broadway Shows</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Get half-off on 22 different Broadway shows, including The Phantom of the Opera, Frozen, Chicago and Wicked. There&rsquo;s a minimum purchase of two tickets. </span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Prix-Fixe Meals</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Get a two-course lunch for $26 or a three-course dinner for $42 at your choice of hundreds of restaurants throughout the five boroughs, including eight in Brooklyn: </span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Barano</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Benchmark Restaurant</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Buttermilk Channel </span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">French Louie</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Greenhouse Cafe</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Leuca</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Osprey</span></li>\r\n<li>Yellow Magnolia Cafe</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">NYC Winter Outing runs from Jan. 21-Feb. 10.</span></p>', 'ian-dooley-281889-unsplash.jpg', 1, '2019-01-16 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(229, 'Destination: Café Madeline', 1, 'destination-caf-madeline', '', 'Destination: Café Madeline', 'Destination: Café Madeline', 'The cozy minimalism of Café Madeline’s unassuming interior belies the real reason we love it: a surprisingly deep, well-rounded menu on which nothing so far has been a disappointment.', '<p>The cozy minimalism of Caf&eacute; Madeline&rsquo;s unassuming interior belies the real reason we love it: a surprisingly deep, well-rounded menu on which nothing so far has been a disappointment.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The cozy minimalism of Caf&eacute; Madeline&rsquo;s unassuming interior belies the real reason we love it: a surprisingly deep, well-rounded menu on which nothing so far has been a disappointment. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Get there early to try the cheddar-chive biscuits that are known to run out quickly, or visit for a low-key brunch and try something like the farm egg scramble, with eggs, spinach or mushroom and pecorino served on sourdough. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You&rsquo;ll find something to love if coffee is your jam, since Madeline has a full espresso bar rounded out with signature drinks like a lavender latte or a rose latte with real petals. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One last tip: Go during the week if you want to avoid waiting in a line out the door on Saturday or Sunday. </span></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Destination: Caf&eacute; Madeline (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Screen%20Shot%202019-01-18%20at%201.49.24%20PM.png\" alt=\"Destination: Caf&eacute; Madeline (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Caf&eacute; Madeline, 1603 Cortelyou Rd., Ditmas Park</span></em></p>\r\n<p>Photos: <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/cafemadeline.cortelyou/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">@cafemadeline.cortelyou</a>/Instagram<br /><br /><br /></p>', 'Screen Shot 2019-01-18 at 1.47.55 PM.png', 1, '2019-01-18 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(230, '#MemberMonday: Richard Murray', 1, 'membermonday-richard-murray', '', '#MemberMonday: Richard Murray', '#MemberMonday: Richard Murray', 'For this week’s #MemberMonday, we talked to Richard Murray, a tech entrepreneur from Florida who lives at our East Williamsburg House. ', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For this week&rsquo;s </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">#MemberMonday</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, we talked to Richard Murray, a tech entrepreneur from Florida who lives at our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Williamsburg House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Read on to see how he&rsquo;s hoping to impact the world of coliving. </span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For this week&rsquo;s </span><strong>#MemberMonday</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, we talked to Richard Murray, a tech entrepreneur from Florida who lives at our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Williamsburg House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Read on to see how he&rsquo;s hoping to impact the world of coliving. </span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tell us a bit about yourself.</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I&rsquo;m an unabashed foodie who leaps at the chance to try out Brooklyn&rsquo;s delicious cuisines. I work at a tech startup in Manhattan without knowing how to write a single line of code -- but I have a knack for developing businesses, so that&rsquo;s what I focus on. I&rsquo;m also the founder of YellowKamp, which connects awesome people (yes, like you!) with awesome spaces. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It seems like I&rsquo;ve been living in NYC forever, although I&rsquo;ve only been here for around five months now! I moved here from sunny Orlando, Fla., to enjoy the big-city life that New York offers. I have not been disappointed -- not yet, at least -- as it&rsquo;s been a lot of fun and I think I&rsquo;ve grown a lot personally.</span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What&rsquo;s your favorite thing about Outpost Club?</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">My favorite thing about Outpost is the people who live in these houses; I&rsquo;ve met so many interesting people from all over. Everyone seems to get along and everyone is quite friendly. This was really important to me when I first moved here not knowing many people -- I wanted to meet people who I could make friends with and who would allow me to expand my worldview. I&rsquo;ve definitely found that. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For people like me, it&rsquo;s nice to know that you don&rsquo;t have to explore your new city alone. I&rsquo;ve had some of the best times hanging out with roommates and have even picked up a few new hobbies, like painting and improv.</span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do you have a favorite place in Brooklyn? Where do you want to explore more?</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I adore Prospect Park and would probably choose that as my favorite place in Brooklyn, but I have a few go-to spots that are on my list of favs. Dos Toros, Roberta&rsquo;s, and Sweet Chick are great for food. Barcade and Union Pool are fun places to drink. I also like to catch the midnight showings at Nighthawk Cinema when I can. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While I&rsquo;ve done a fair amount of exploring, there&rsquo;s still so much more for me to see. I&rsquo;d like to check out some of the museums and art galleries around town, and when the weather warms up a bit, I&rsquo;d like to check out some of the nearby beaches, as well.</span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What are you working on right now?</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I&rsquo;m building </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">YellowKamp.com</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. It&rsquo;s basically a site where people can find coliving spaces. I stumbled across coliving when I was searching for a place to stay in New York and it seemed like a cool concept, and it also made things super convenient for my move. I decided that I would give it a try, but wanted to be certain that I chose the right place. I looked around, and eventually found </span><a href=\"../\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outpost Club</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What I remember most was how much of a headache it was to find these. At the time there wasn&rsquo;t an easy way to find places that provided options for coliving specifically, so I built one. Now YellowKamp has info for all the coliving offered in eight cities across the globe (with more to come)! </span></p>', 'Screen Shot 2019-01-21 at 11.24.22 AM.png', 1, '2019-01-21 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(231, '5 things you didn’t know about Central Park ', 1, '5-things-you-didnt-know-about-central-park-', '', '5 things you didn’t know about Central Park ', '5 things you didn’t know about Central Park ', 'Here are five interesting things you may not know about America’s favorite park.', '<p>Here are five interesting things you may not know about America&rsquo;s favorite park.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><em>by Lauren Vega</em></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There&rsquo;s plenty to love about Central Park, from the expansive greenery to its panoramic views of the Manhattan skyline. It&rsquo;s also a park with a lot to offer, with dozens of fountains, monuments and statues that have been added over time since construction began in 1858, and myriad events and activities for the more than 40 million people who visit every year. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Those 40 million people make Central Park the most popular urban park in the world and one of the most-visited tourist attractions in the world, by the way. Here are five other interesting things you may not know about America&rsquo;s favorite park (besides that it\'s only a few minutes\' walk from our <a href=\"../central-park-manhattan-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Central Park Manhattan House</a>!):</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"5 things you didn&rsquo;t know about Central Park (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/juan-di-nella-473902-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"5 things you didn&rsquo;t know about Central Park (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Manhattan bedrock wasn&rsquo;t messing around</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A large chunk of Manhattan was built on a layer of bedrock that&rsquo;s very close to the surface,, which is what makes our skyscrapers possible (and why we don&rsquo;t have fossils). The Manhattan Schist, the layer of bedrock under Central Park, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">took so much effort to blast through</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that more gunpowder was used to clear the land for the park than was used in the Battle of Gettysburg during the American Civil War. </span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s appeared in more movies than any other single location &hellip;</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">...at least in the past two decades. According to a </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dec. 2017 analysis</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> of movies listed on IMDb, Central Park is present in 231 on-location shots, more than any other location aside from actual film studios.</span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It was the first landscaped public park in the United States</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The kinds of public parks we&rsquo;re used to today, with elaborately planned walkways, statues, fountains and green areas, were still a relatively new concept in the U.S. in the 1850s, </span><a href=\"http://www.centralparknyc.org/visit/park-history.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">when Central Park was conceived</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. But as Manhattan became more crowded than ever, it became obvious that people needed a place to escape the hustle and bustle of city life that wasn&rsquo;t a cemetery. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The result, an 843-acre Central Park designed by Frederick Law Olmsted and Calvert Vaux, has been held up as a standard for the world and used as a model for parks like the Golden Gate Park in San Francisco, Ueno Park in Tokyo and Stanley Park in Vancouver.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"5 things you didn&rsquo;t know about Central Park (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/juan-di-nella-473905-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"5 things you didn&rsquo;t know about Central Park (Image-2)\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are 36 bridges and arches in the park -- and no two are alike</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Olmsted and Vaux</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, Central Park&rsquo;s designers, believed that if bridges and arches had to be present in their park -- which they did to support roads and other necessary structures -- they should have been as unobtrusive as possible, noticeable only when someone walked right up to them, and even then blending with their surroundings. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The result of this attitude was 36 artful bridges and arches dotting the park, made of a variety of materials and in a plethora of styles, all meant to complement the specific area in which they were built: nothing more, nothing less. </span></p>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Central Park cost more than all of Alaska</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Just purchasing the park&rsquo;s 843 acres </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">s</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">et the New York legislature back $7.4 million</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, less than the $7.2 million the U.S. paid Russia for the entire state of Alaska a decade later. At 600,000 square miles, you could fit around 450,000 Central Parks in Alaska without breaking a sweat. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"5 things you didn&rsquo;t know about Central Park (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/liam-macleod-1141895-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"5 things you didn&rsquo;t know about Central Park (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>', '5-things-you-didnt-know-about-central-park--2.jpg', 1, '2019-01-23 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(232, 'This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago ', 1, 'this-app-will-show-you-what-your-neighborhood-looked-like-a-century-ago-', '', 'This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago ', 'This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago ', 'If you’ve ever wandered among Brooklyn’s brownstones or Midtown’s skyscrapers and tried to imagine what New York City was like before it became the cultural and economic behemoth it is today, now’s your chance to find out. ', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;ve ever wandered among Brooklyn&rsquo;s brownstones or Midtown&rsquo;s skyscrapers and tried to imagine what New York City was like before it became the cultural and economic behemoth it is today, now&rsquo;s your chance to find out. </span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;ve ever wandered among Brooklyn&rsquo;s brownstones or Midtown&rsquo;s skyscrapers and tried to imagine what New York City was like before it became the cultural and economic behemoth it is today, now&rsquo;s your chance to find out. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Urban Archive NYC, </span><a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/urban-archive-nyc/id1154228951?mt=8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">currently available on iOS</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, lets you view history in real-time as you walk down the street, whether you&rsquo;re in Harlem or Crown Heights. The app pinpoints locations near you of which historic photos are available, meaning you can see what your subway entrance or favorite restaurant looked like decades or even a century ago. It&rsquo;s been around for about a year, but the collection of photos just keeps growing.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&ldquo;New York City has thousands of historic locations, each with its own story &hellip; we are giving our users the ability to experience history where it happened,&rdquo; Urban Archive editor Ben Smyth wrote on </span><a href=\"https://medium.com/urban-archive/welcome-to-urban-archive-cc097a889df2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Medium</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The app also allows you to take a photo of the current location with a transparent overlay of the historic photo, allowing you to contrast how much the location has (or hasn&rsquo;t) changed over the years. And you can choose to be notified if you&rsquo;re near a location with a particularly interesting photo associated with it. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The nonprofit that launched the app, </span><strong>Urban Archive</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, has spent the past few years cataloguing the photo archives of libraries, museums and historical societies and agencies throughout New York, including the New York Public Library, the Museum of the City of New York and the Brooklyn Historical Society.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/IMG_0088%202.jpg\" alt=\"This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Wilson Avenue Line trolley tracks in 1946, looking northwest up Wilson Ave. toward Schaefer St. (New York Transit Museum/Urban Archive)</span></p>\r\n<p><img title=\"This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Screen%20Shot%202019-01-30%20at%201.02.36%20PM.png\" alt=\"This app will show you what your neighborhood looked like a century ago (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Looking northwest up Wilson Ave. from the same location: The building at the northeast corner remains largely unchanged. (Google)</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'IMG_0088 2.jpg', 1, '2019-01-30 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0);
