(243, 'How to celebrate Women\'s History Month in NYC', 1, 'how-to-celebrate-womens-history-month-in-nyc', '', 'How to celebrate Women\'s History Month in NYC', 'How to celebrate Women\'s History Month in NYC', 'Here are our suggestions for how you can pay tribute to incredible women everywhere, both past and present, in NYC this March.', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here are our suggestions for how you can pay tribute to incredible women everywhere, both past and present, in NYC this March.</span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Women are great. So great that in 1987, after being petitioned by the </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Women%27s_History_Project\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">National Women\'s History Project</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, Congress named March as </span><a href=\"https://womenshistorymonth.gov/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Women&rsquo;s History Month</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Here are our suggestions for how you can pay tribute to incredible women everywhere, both past and present, in NYC this March.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Entertain yourself</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Catch some feminist cinema at Williamsburg&rsquo;s </span><strong>Nitehawk Cinema</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This independent theater is celebrating Women\'s History Month with a series of films featuring the most badass heroines, from Tank Girl (March 8 and 9), to Edge of Tomorrow (March 16 and 17), and Buffy the Vampire Slayer (March 23 and 24). Find the full program </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">here</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, with tickets priced at $13.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Or how about celebrating your witty sisters with some female comedy? Comedy is still an area that&rsquo;s dominated by men, so help balance things out by trying shows like </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Party of Two</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, an all-female show at </span><strong>The Tank</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> hosted by Vanessa Valerio and Anita Flores on March 9. You&rsquo;ll love their take on the hilarious discrepancies between movie depictions of dating in New York and the seedy reality.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If art is more your thing, head to the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Brooklyn Museum</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to see </span><strong><a href=\"https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/dinner_party\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><em>The Dinner Party</em></a></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, an iconic piece of 1970s feminist art. This massive, triangular ceremonial banquet table with 39 place settings commemorating important women from history is being presented as the centerpiece of the Elizabeth A. Sackler Center for Feminist Art this March.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Stretch yourself</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Want to support women in sport? </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She&rsquo;s on Point! A Celebration of Girls in Sports</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is your chance. Join </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">NYC Parks</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on March 24 for a free day of sports and group activities, including soccer, basketball, double-dutch, flag football and cheerleading. There will also be sports clinics to learn new skills, so check out the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Eventbrite</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> page to register.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Volunteer</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Show your support for today&rsquo;s women by volunteering with </span><strong>Women in Need</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, an NYC non-profit that provides safe housing, critical services and ground-breaking programs to help homeless women and their children rebuild their lives. Choose from </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">volunteering</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> your administrative skills in the Bronx or running art activities for their after-school programs in Brooklyn.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How to celebrate Women\'s History Month in NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/womens-voices.jpg\" alt=\"How to celebrate Women\'s History Month in NYC (Image-1)\" /></span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Educate yourself</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For an overview of how far women have come in history, check out </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Women&rsquo;s Voices</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> at </span><strong>The Center for Women&rsquo;s History</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> this March. This multimedia </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">digital installation highlights the hidden connections among women who left their mark on New York and the nation. Featuring interviews, profiles, and biographies, </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Women&rsquo;s Voices </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">tells the stories of activists, scientists, athletes and social change advocates, from the first Latina Supreme Court Justice, Sonia Sotomayor, to Nobel Prize-winning scientist Barbara McClintock, and more.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Or try one of the w</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">orkshops, activities or performances at the Apollo Theater&rsquo;s </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Women of the World Festival</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. From March 12-17, the theater is running a full program of artists, community leaders, writers and activists, exploring a variety of cultural and civic issues, with a focus on female empowerment. Speakers you can gape at in awe include musician </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Alice Smith</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, White House Correspondent </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">April Ryan</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and Poet </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nikki Giovanni</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>', '636520581172357196-Womens-March-08.jpg', 1, '2019-03-07 06:00:00', NULL, 0, 0, 0),
(244, 'Best spring festivals in NYC', 1, 'best-spring-festivals-in-nyc', '', 'Best spring festivals in NYC', 'Best spring festivals in NYC', 'New York is an exciting place to be in the spring. Check out our picks of the best spring festivals.', '<p>New York is an exciting place to be in the spring. Check out our picks of the best spring festivals.</p>', '<p>New York is an exciting place to be in the spring. Check out our picks of the best spring festivals:</p>\r\n<h1><strong>The Tribeca Film Festival</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Attending the Tribeca Film Festival is not just for celebrities. Although you might not be able to sneak onto the red carpet, tickets for Robert De Niro&rsquo;s famous New York film festival actually start at just $12 for a Monday-Friday matinee. For evening and weekend screenings, prices begin at $24.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The festival is famous for shining a spotlight on local indie documentaries, features and foreign films, including both big-name filmmakers and emerging talent. This year&rsquo;s festival runs from April 25-May 5, taking place across Lower Manhattan and Chelsea, at the Regal Battery Park, Cin&eacute;polis Chelsea, Beacon Theatre, SVA Theatre and the festival&rsquo;s own Tribeca Festival Hub.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Best spring festivals in NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/tribeca-film-festival-2017-the-hub-at-spring-studios.jpg\" alt=\"Best spring festivals in NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Sakura Matsuri</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The annual cherry blossom festival is coming again to <a href=\"https://www.bbg.org/visit/event/sakura_matsuri_2019\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Brooklyn Botanic Garden</a> on April 27-28 for its 38th installment. With beautiful blossoms and a program full of events that showcase the rich history of Japanese culture, it&rsquo;s the perfect time to check out the garden&rsquo;s famous Cherry Esplanade.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>The Washington Square Outdoor Art Exhibit</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The Washington Square Outdoor Art Exhibit is an annual art exhibit held in Greenwich Village every spring. Inspired by Jackson Pollock&rsquo;s 1931 decision to bring his paintings to the Village sidewalk to sell for a few dollars, the event has grown into a staple of the Lower Manhattan calendar, with artists competing to showcase their work to the public.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This year, the free exhibit will take place on Memorial Day Weekend and June 1 and 2.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Macy&rsquo;s Flower Show</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Every spring, the Macy&rsquo;s Herald Square store showcases some of the most beautiful flowers in New York City. This free flower show started over 70 years ago and now takes over the entire store every spring, with hundreds of thousands of live flowers, plants and trees from around the world blooming in unexpected places like store countertops, windows and specially designed bridges and columns.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The show also includes flower demonstrations and free tours and runs from March 24 to April 7.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Best spring festivals in NYC (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1547591900_pastshow_img6.png\" alt=\"Best spring festivals in NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>The Bloody Mary Festival</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Drink yourself warm this spring with the Bloody Mary Liberation Party&rsquo;s Bloody Mary Festival. Revel in 2.5 hours dedicated to trying the best versions of this famous drink from a range of New York bars. Combine this with live music, temporary tattoos, a bagel bar and cheese station and you&rsquo;ve got your Sunday sorted. This festival is for one day only, on April 7, at Grand Prospect Hall on Prospect Avenue.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Frieze Art Fair</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">No list would be complete without this famous outdoor art fair, held at Randall&rsquo;s Island Park. Showcasing the best in contemporary art, the eighth installment of this art extravaganza features the world&rsquo;s most exciting emerging artists as well as iconic names, plus a range of talks, live performances, new artist commissions and the city&rsquo;s most chic restaurants.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'cherry-blossom-festival-nyc.jpg', 1, '2019-03-08 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(277, '#MemberMonday: Kamila Costa', 1, 'membermonday-kamila-costa', '', '#MemberMonday: Kamila Costa', '#MemberMonday: Kamila Costa', 'Meet Kamila Costa from Brazil, house leader at our Ridgewood house and self-proclaimed cinephile.', '<p>Meet Kamila Costa from Brazil, the house leader at our Ridgewood houses and self-proclaimed cinephile.</p>', '<p>Meet Kamila Costa from Brazil, the house leader at our&nbsp;Ridgewood house and self-proclaimed cinephile.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em><strong><img title=\"#MemberMonday: Kamila Costa (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/60264494_413998156060544_1040488254459084800_n.jpg\" alt=\"#MemberMonday: Kamila Costa (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></strong></em></span></p>\r\n<h1>Tell us a bit about yourself.</h1>\r\n<p>I\'m passionate about history, sociology, art, photography, music and cinema. (I\'m truly a cinephile.) I like to meet new people, and learn about new cultures and the history behind the places I choose to go.</p>\r\n<h1>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</h1>\r\n<p>I already have a collection of good memories here in the Outpost -- however, if I have to choose one, I\'ll go with the first Outpost event that I went to at the South Williamsburg house: the s\'mores event on May 4th. I met great people and had a lot of fun that Saturday!</p>\r\n<h1>What&rsquo;s your favorite part of New York?</h1>\r\n<p>Wow, this is a hard choice ... But Brooklyn has my heart for sure.</p>\r\n<h1>What are you working on right now?</h1>\r\n<p>For now, I\'m still improving my English, especially the writing part. My goal is to learn as many things as I can, &nbsp;especially in what is related to people, communities and socialization.</p>', '60264494_413998156060544_1040488254459084800_n.jpg', 1, '2019-05-20 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(246, 'Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City', 1, 'where-to-celebrate-st-patricks-day-in-new-york-city', '', 'Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City', 'Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City', 'New York is home to some of the biggest St Patrick’s Day celebrations in the world. So where do you begin? Read on for our best picks of how to celebrate this great Irish and Catholic holiday.\r\n', '<p>New York is home to some of the biggest St Patrick&rsquo;s Day celebrations in the world. So where do you begin? Read on for our best picks of how to celebrate this great Irish and Catholic holiday.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>New York is home to some of the biggest St Patrick&rsquo;s Day celebrations in the world. So where do you begin? Read on for our best picks of how to celebrate this great Irish and Catholic holiday.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Float down to a parade</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Manhattan </span><strong>St Patrick&rsquo;s Day Parade</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is one of the oldest and largest in the parade calendar. A strictly no-float event, the lineup of marching bands, bagpipes and Irish dancers begins at 11 a.m. on Saturday, running from 44th St. up 5th Ave. But for a better chance at seeing the revelry, we recommend </span><strong>Brooklyn&rsquo;s version</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on Sunday in Park Slope. The Brooklyn </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St Patrick\'s Day Parade</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> kicks off at 1 p.m. and runs from Prospect Park West and 15th St. down to 7th Ave. and Garfield Place, then back over to Prospect Park West.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/st-patrick-day-parade-new-york-city.jpg\" alt=\"Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Get some heritage</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Irish Arts Center in Hell&rsquo;s Kitchen is running their annual </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St Patrick&rsquo;s Open Day</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">again this year. Enjoy authentic Irish music, dancing and workshops and try your hand at learning some Irish words and dance moves. Or why not take a walking tour of &ldquo;Little Ireland&rdquo; on the Lower East Side, a hidden hub of Irish immigrant history? Learn about the contribution that the Irish have made to Manhattan at the Big Onion Irish Walking Tour for just $25 per person.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Get literary</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Irish Arts Center is holding its ninth annual </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Book Day</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on Friday, with free books by Irish writers being given away in 12 free pop-ups across the five boroughs. The stands go live at 8 a.m. and stay open until the books run out (usually by 1 p.m.). More details will be released on the day of, but in Brooklyn, you&rsquo;ll find your station at 4th Ave. between 68th and Bay Ridge Ave.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Crawl yourself Irish</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s no secret that the Irish like to drink, and there is no shortage of pub crawls in Manhattan and Brooklyn on St Patrick&rsquo;s Day. From just $11, the </span><strong>St Paddy&rsquo;s Day Weekend Pub Crawl</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> gives you access to 50 participating bars across the city, with drink specials galore. Running from 5 p.m. Friday through 7 p.m. Sunday, this cheesy extravaganza means wearing green and getting fully involved in the festivities.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/images.jpg\" alt=\"Where to celebrate St. Patrick\'s Day in New York City (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;d like a quieter crawl, try the 2-day </span><strong>Kiss Me, I&rsquo;m Irish</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> crawl in Lower Manhattan, or the Saturday-night-only </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St. Paddy&rsquo;s Pubcrawl</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> in Astoria.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">And if you\'d rather stay in one place, the Columbia Wine Co.&rsquo;s </span><strong>St. Patrick\'s Day Festival</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> will have a range of Irish Whiskey, liquor and other treats on offer, with up to 15 bottles open for you to try on Saturday from 5 p.m.-8 p.m. Get your tickets </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">here</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Or why not embrace the coming warmth of spring on the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day Party Cruise</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">? Enjoy onboard DJs, food and music on the Jewel Yacht for an epic party night on the East River, running until 11 p.m., when you can head straight to the included after party at Doha Nightclub in Long Island City.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A cheaper on-land alternative is the St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day party on historic </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Stone Street</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This free street festival runs from noon Saturday and is your chance to bar hop along the various stalls, trying Jameson, Guiness, Gummy Bear shots and Corned Beef. </span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Try a low-key bar</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;re looking for a simple night, Bushwick&rsquo;s </span><strong>Brooklyn Cider House</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is the place for you. They&rsquo;re running an all-day brunch from 11 a.m. to 11 p.m. on Sunday for St. Paddy&rsquo;s, including an array of Irish themed dishes and drinks like green eggs and ham, corned beef and cabbage, irish coffee and green cider.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Or head over to </span><strong>The Bell House</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on Sunday for a night of punk-infused Celtic soul. The lineup includes Too-Rye-Aye, an 11-person group led by </span><strong>Ted Leo</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, who will be playing hits like &ldquo;</span><strong>Come On Eileen</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&rdquo; from 6 p.m. until late with a cover charge of just $15.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Pre-game with Outpost</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;re looking for something closer to home, come to Outpost&rsquo;s </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St Patrick&rsquo;s Day Pre-Game</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on Saturday night (BYOB). We&rsquo;ll be playing Irish games and wearing green before heading out to </span><strong>Bootleg Bar</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to enjoy the rest of the night.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></p>', 'st-patrick-day-parade-new-york-city.jpg', 1, '2019-03-14 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(247, 'Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for', 1, 'brooklyn-bakeries-with-pie-to-die-for', '', 'Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for', 'Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for', 'It’s that time of year again: Pi Day is upon us. But with so many bakeries to choose from and a limit to how many slices you can physically fit in your stomach, how do you decide which bakeries to try? Here are our top picks.', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s that time of year again: </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pi Day</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is upon us. But with so many bakeries to choose from and a limit to how many slices you can physically fit in your stomach, how do you decide which bakeries to try? Here are our top picks.</span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s that time of year again: </span><strong>Pi Day</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is upon us. But with so many bakeries to choose from and a limit to how many slices you can physically fit in your stomach, how do you decide which bakeries to try? Here are our top picks:</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Four &amp; Twenty Blackbirds</strong>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/HT_salted_caramel_apple_pie_four_twenty_blackbirds_cook_book_sk_131115_wmain_1.jpg\" alt=\"Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Consistently voted the best pie in Brooklyn, </span><strong>Four &amp; Twenty Blackbirds</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> has to be the first recommendation on our list. This tiny pie shop has garnered an international reputation since its 2009 opening, being featured in a variety of international food publications including </span><a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/06/dining/four-and-twenty-blackbirds-prospect-heights.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The New York Times</span></em></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Founded by sisters Melissa and Emily Elsen, the pies are a product of their childhoods spent making pies with their Grandma Liz in South Dakota, and the Brooklyn </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">outpost</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> still holds these same family values, with the pies coming handmade with all-butter crusts. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The shop is particularly famous for its salted-caramel apple pie, which is a little slice of something wonderful, and the pumpkin, lemon and salted honey varieties are also crowd pleasers. All of the ingredients are sourced locally and organically wherever possible. You can find these delicious slices in your neighborhood, just a short walk from our </span><a href=\"../the-downtown-brooklyn-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Downtown Brooklyn House</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">439 3rd Avenue, Brooklyn, NY 11215</span></em></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Buttah</strong>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/15774721_1404074809636689_4279684556916035646_o.jpg\" alt=\"Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Buttah</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is another Brooklyn favorite. Located on Onderdonk Avenue, a 15-minute walk from our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ridgewood House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, this under-the-radar bakery is one of the neighborhood&rsquo;s best kept secrets. Just don&rsquo;t expect to sit down, because it&rsquo;s a traditional pie shop, not a caf&eacute;, which means it&rsquo;s all about pick up and go. A neon pink sign is the only giveaway that there&rsquo;s a rich range of pies and creamy cupcakes inside the door &mdash; with deliciously Brooklyn prices.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">377 Onderdonk Ave, Ridgewood, NY 11385</span></em></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Rudy&rsquo;s Bakery &amp; Caf&eacute;</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you want traditional, homestyle pies, try </span><strong>Rudy\'s Bakery &amp; Caf&eacute;</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a Ridgewood landmark since 1934. This historic bakery has an extensive line of pastries, strudels, cupcakes and, of course, pies, in a space filled with old-world charm that you just can&rsquo;t fake that&rsquo;s only a 7-minute walk from our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ridgewood House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. The smell of freshly made fruit, cream and seasonal pies fills the air and the wood-paneled walls take you back to your grandparents&rsquo; homemade recipes. We love their cookie-crust Nutella tarts made by Pastry Chef Cristina.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">905 Seneca Ave, Ridgewood, NY 11385</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/25JOINT1-articleLarge-v2.jpg\" alt=\"Brooklyn bakeries with pie to die for (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em></p>\r\n<h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Brooklyn Whiskers</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Or why not check out </span><strong>Brooklyn Whiskers</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><strong>,</strong> a vegan outpost in the heart of Bushwick with some pretty incredible pie. Tucked away in a little yellow corner on Bushwick Avenue, this vegan bakery and caf&eacute; serves the best plant-based pastries and custom creations in Bushwick, as well as amazing coffee roasted by local </span><strong>Caffe Vita</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Our favorite is the gluten free Oatmeal Cream Pie, but the daily changing menu has a whole range of options to meet your fancy. Brooklyn Whiskers is just a short walk from our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bushwick House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">760 Bushwick Ave, Brooklyn, NY 11221</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '4115edbdfbb781625948c20a06199d2f72bdb189.jpg', 1, '2019-03-14 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(251, 'Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg', 1, 'neighborhood-guide-south-williamsburg', '', 'Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg', 'Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg', 'Welcome home, residents of the new South Williamsburg House! And for all other members of Outpost, welcome to another chapter of our neighborhood guide series!', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Welcome home, residents of the new </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">South Williamsburg House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">! And for all other members of Outpost, welcome to another chapter of our neighborhood guide series!</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Welcome home, residents of the new </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">South Williamsburg House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">! And for all other members of Outpost, welcome to another chapter of our <a href=\"../blog_category/neighborhood-guide\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">neighborhood guide</a>&nbsp;series!</span></p>\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ve spent the past few weeks scouring the neighborhood for the best spots at the intersection of Williamsburg, Bushwick and Bed-Stuy to grab a coffee, do some shopping or just hang out, and we&rsquo;ve compiled it all in an easy-to-use guide. So, drop off your luggage and throw on some comfortable shoes, cause we&rsquo;ve got some places for you to check out.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>SUBWAYS</strong></h1>\r\n<p><strong>These are the closest spots with the widest range of trains to take you into the city or throughout Brooklyn.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Flushing Ave. Station</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Trains: M/J</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: 1-min. walk </span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Montrose Ave. Station</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Train: L</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: 10-min. walk </span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Flushing Ave. Station</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Train: G</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: 10-min. walk</span></em></p>\r\n<h1><strong>GROCERIES</strong></h1>\r\n<p><strong>You gotta eat, and we\'ve picked out the best options for your grocery runs.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Mr. Kiwi&rsquo;s</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>957 Broadway, 11221</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Hours: Open 24 hours</strong></p>\r\n<p>Just a few blocks (or one subway stop) away is cult-favorite Mr. Kiwi&rsquo;s, your one-stop for high-quality and affordable fresh fruits and vegetables, along with organic and vegetarian options that can be difficult to find elsewhere. Grab a fresh-pressed juice while you&rsquo;re there for less than $5, too.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 8 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Food Bazaar Supermarket</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>21 Manhattan Ave., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Hours: 7 a.m.-11:30 p.m.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Food Bazaar has the general selection of groceries and household supplies you&rsquo;d expect from any supermarket, but where it shines is with its international food selection. Whether you&rsquo;re craving something from home or experimenting with different cuisines, chances are you&rsquo;ll be able to find it at Food Bazaar.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 8 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Coconut Kosher Supermarket</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>15 Throop Ave., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Hours: 7:30 a.m.-Varies</strong></p>\r\n<p>Coconut is a few blocks up Broadway (or one stop on the M/J train, at Lorimer St.). It has a great variety of kosher foods and is a local favorite for its selection and quality.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 11 min.; Bike: 4 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o.jpg\" alt=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bizarre. Credit: Lois C./Yelp</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;</span></em></p>\r\n<h1><strong>GYMS</strong></h1>\r\n<p><strong>Whether you\'re trying to get in the best shape of your life or maintain your form, we get it. We checked out a couple of the local gyms and found the best, most affordable and diverse options.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Planet Fitness</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>777 Broadway, 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p>Planet Fitness is known for its affordability, but this location takes it one step further with a great selection of cardio and weight equipment and a friendly staff. Another great thing about this location is that it&rsquo;s open 24/7.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 2 min; Bike: 1 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Richie&rsquo;s Gym</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>6 Stanwix St., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p>Richie&rsquo;s is a great option if you want to focus on strength training, with a wide selection of weight equipment and plenty of mirrors and room to lift. There are also cardio machines. This location is known as a great location for anyone to work out without self-consciousness.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 8 min; Bike: 5 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Bushwick CrossFit</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>10 Wilson Ave., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re into CrossFit, this might be the perfect location for you. Bushwick CrossFit has glowing reviews of it&rsquo;s fantastic staff and flexible class times.</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 11 min; Bike: 5 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Brooklyn__Bushwick___NY_photo_5_0.jpg\" alt=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Credit: </span></em><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Planet Fitness</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>COFFEE SHOPS</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Looking to get your caffeine fix? Maybe just need a chill spot to get productive, or even just have a chat with a friend? Whatever your situation, here are our recommendations for the best coffee shops in town.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Bushwick Grind</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>63 Whipple St., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Bushwick Grind is a cozy, artistic coffee shop with good food and even better coffee. For a special treat, visit on a Wednesday to try the barista&rsquo;s favorite creations.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 6 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Cafe Erzulie</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>894 Broadway, 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Cafe Erzulie is a wonderful Haitian neighborhood spot that spends its days as a cafe and flower shop -- who doesn&rsquo;t need more beauty in their life? -- and by night, it transforms into a cocktail bar. The cafe also has a beautiful backyard garden, in case you want to escape the city for a bit.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 6 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Little Skips</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>941 Willoughby Ave., 11221</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Little Skips is like a second home for the Bushwick creative scene, with a fun, artsy vibe and plenty of seating to work on whatever makes you tick. In addition to good coffee and plenty of food on offer, they host occasional art shows, weekly open mics and more, all in collaboration with the Bushwick creative community.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 12 min; Bike: 6 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Ange Noir Cafe</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>247 Varet St., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Ange Noir is a trendy French cafe with plenty of seating and a wide variety of foods to fit any diet, whether you&rsquo;re vegan, gluten-free or a carnivore. It&rsquo;s a bit darker inside than other cafes, perfect for an evening coffee.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 10 min; Bike: 5 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_1.jpg\" alt=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Little Skips. Credit: Brian M./Yelp</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>FOOD</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>For those times you don\'t feel like cooking, or when you want to step out for a bite with some friends from the house. We\'ve tried it all (believe us) and these are the number one spots in the area.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Concrete</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>906 Broadway, 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Concrete is known for its simple, delicious menu of Sicilian-inspired food with a Brooklyn twist. The space features local artists&rsquo; work on the walls and has plans to expand its creative services in the future.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 6 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Samurai Papa</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>32 Varet St., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Sometimes you just need a comforting bowl of ramen at the end of a long day, and there&rsquo;s no place better in terms of variety than Samurai Papa, which has a menu full of options for carnivores, vegetarians and vegans alike.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 7 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>La Isla Cuchifritos</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>6 Graham Ave., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">La Isla is a longtime neighborhood favorite. The unassuming interior is a reminder that the restaurant relies entirely on its food for its reputation, and it&rsquo;s no wonder it&rsquo;s been serving up some of the best Latin-American food in Brooklyn for more than half a century.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 4 min; Bike: 2 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/51557119_367155047349626_8721316085372995278_n.jpg\" alt=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Credit: Picgra</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>NIGHTLIFE </strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Want to kick off the weekend the right way? Try these spots for the best taste of nightlife in the neighborhood.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Bizarre</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>12 Jefferson St., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Bizarre is a cool, sometimes crazy hangout with live entertainment that&rsquo;s always a blast. There are two happy hours on most days (4 p.m.-8 p.m. daily and 12 a.m.-2 a.m. Sun.-Thu.), and weekend brunch includes one of the most reasonably priced bottomless mimosa deals you&rsquo;ll find in Brooklyn.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 8 min; Bike: 4 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>SKYTOWN</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>921 Broadway, 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">SKYTOWN is the place to go for craft cocktails, and if you&rsquo;re hungry you can fuel yourself with some of the bar&rsquo;s modern American comfort food. They also have a good beer selection and great bartenders, to boot.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 6 min; Bike: 3 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Rebecca&rsquo;s</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>610 Bushwick Ave., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">This low-key LGBTQ bar is full of funky vibes and awesome drink specials. They have a ton of events, super-friendly bartenders and are a welcoming space for all.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 8 min; Bike: 4 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Duckduck</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>161 Montrose Ave., 11206 </strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Duckduck is a chill, well-priced hangout where you&rsquo;ll probably notice ducks you hadn&rsquo;t seen before every time you go. The bartenders are friendly and they have one of the best happy hours you&rsquo;ll find: Drinks are buy-one-get-one 4 p.m.-8p.m. daily.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 11 min; 4 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_2.jpg\" alt=\"Neighborhood Guide: South Williamsburg (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Credit:&nbsp;Bizarre. Lois C./Yelp</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>PARKS</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>If you ever just need a moment of peace, or a space to play a game of basketball, try out one of these locations.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Sternberg Park</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Lorimer and Boerum streets</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Sternberg Park will be perfect for you if walking between home and the train isn&rsquo;t enough outdoor activity for you. The park has both handball and basketball courts -- just bring your equipment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 11 min; Bike: 5 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Steve A./Yelp</span></em></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>POST OFFICE</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>United States Postal Service</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>47 Debevoise St., 11206</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Whether you want to ship something, open a P.O. box or get a money order, USPS is still the cheapest and most reliable mailing service you&rsquo;ll find.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Distance: Walk: 4 min; Bike: 2 min</span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>That\'s just a taste of your new neighborhood. We\'re certain you\'ll love your home and these incredible places, and we\'re positive you\'ll find more amazing places. If you have a suggestion for a new spot to add to our list or tips for any of the places already listed, let us know&mdash;comment on our Facebook page and we\'ll check it out ourselves!</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br /><br /></span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'o.jpg', 1, '2019-03-25 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(248, '#MemberMonday: Lotus Brown', 1, 'membermonday-lotus-brown', '', '#MemberMonday: Lotus Brown', '#MemberMonday: Lotus Brown', 'This week’s #MemberMonday feature is Lotus Brown, an advertising student from Chicago and a member of our East Bushwick House.', '<p>This week&rsquo;s #MemberMonday feature is Lotus Brown, an advertising student from Chicago and a member of our East Bushwick House.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This week&rsquo;s <strong>#MemberMonday</strong> feature is Lotus Brown, an advertising student from Chicago and a member at our East Bushwick House.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"#MemberMonday: Lotus Brown (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/A5FB5CDD-4A1E-490E-8D13-1D66C998EC39.JPG\" alt=\"#MemberMonday: Lotus Brown (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Tell us a bit about yourself.</h1>\r\n<p>Hey, guys! I&rsquo;m Lotus and I just moved to NYC from Chicago 2 months ago for an advertising program. I come from the land of really good pizza, really cold winters, Obama and unique art installations. (You may have heard of The Bean; if not, check it out.) I&rsquo;m excited to see all of the interesting and innovative things New York City has to offer.</p>\r\n<h1>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</h1>\r\n<p>My favorite Outpost memory so far has been spending New Year\'s Eve here at the East Bushwick house. I had just moved to the city and we had a \'90s-themed celebration that night. Outpost members from different houses that I had never met before showed their lovely faces and we had fun together jamming out to \'90s tunes and watching the ball drop in Times Square. Afterwards, we went up to the rooftop and watched our neighbors pop fireworks in the rain. It was definitely a great introduction to the city and one of the best nights of my life. Can&rsquo;t wait until the Fourth of July!</p>\r\n<h1>What&rsquo;s your favorite part of New York?</h1>\r\n<p>New York is just a bigger, dirtier, more diverse version of Chicago! Actually, that&rsquo;s not true. Contrary to popular belief, NYC and Chicago are completely different places. The thing I like the most about New York so far, though, is how wacky and creative the city is. You really can find some of the most offbeat things here -- from the Troll Museum to the annual No Pants Subway Ride that happens in January; it really is a unique place where anything can happen! I also love the fashion. New Yorkers are very stylish!</p>\r\n<h1>What are you working on now?</h1>\r\n<p>Right now, I&rsquo;m working on building my copywriting portfolio as I&rsquo;m studying at Miami Ad School to become a copywriter. I&rsquo;m enjoying the process of generating new ideas and all that being a part of the creative side of advertising entails. If anyone wants to chat about advertising stuff, give me a holler!</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'A5FB5CDD-4A1E-490E-8D13-1D66C998EC39.JPG', 1, '2019-03-18 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0);
