(258, 'Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live', 1, 'why-east-williamsburg-is-a-great-place-to-live', '', 'Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live | Outpost Club blog', 'Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live', 'Walking around East Williamsburg feels like traversing the light side of the moon. Read our blog to get full information about East Williamsburg living and our houses.', '<p>Walking around East Williamsburg feels like traversing the light side of the moon&hellip; but with more kombucha. This neighborhood has &ldquo;industrial chic&rdquo; down to a T and, with a commute into Manhattan of less than 30 minutes, it&rsquo;s easy to see why it&rsquo;s at the top of many Brooklynites&rsquo; lists of desired places to live and why our East Williamsburg House is one of our most popular houses.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Walking around East Williamsburg feels like traversing the light side of the moon&hellip; but with more kombucha. This neighborhood has &ldquo;industrial chic&rdquo; down to a T and, with a commute into <a href=\"../nyc-rooms-for-rent\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Manhattan</a> of less than 30 minutes, it&rsquo;s easy to see why it&rsquo;s at the top of many Brooklynites&rsquo; lists of desired places to live and why our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Williamsburg House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is one of our most popular houses.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Historically an industrial area, immigrants from Italy, Puerto Rico and other Latin-American countries settled in East Williamsburg from the late 19th century and the melting pot of cultures is still tangible. The Italian community thrives along the north end of Graham Avenue, known as &ldquo;Via Vespucci,&rdquo; while the south end of Graham Avenue (also known as &ldquo;Avenue of Puerto Rico&rdquo;) has been the center of Latin-American immigrant life since the 1950s. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the 1990s, the area saw an influx of young artists, professionals and students, making the atmosphere a unique fusion of its two neighbors, Williamsburg and Bushwick. The area still maintains its historical industrial life, giving it a real personality of its own. Read on to find out why so many people want to live in East Williamsburg.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/benefits/Screen%20Shot%202019-04-10%20at%202.52.56%20PM.png\" alt=\"Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<h1>The sense of discovery</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Most of East Williamsburg looks like factories&mdash;until you get closer&mdash;and this is all part of the fun. This neighborhood is filled with artistic and cultural gems, hidden away by the industrial aesthetic, which makes discovering them all the more rewarding. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hipster grocery stores and murals sit next to working factories producing everything from glass to beer. You&rsquo;d be forgiven for thinking the sound of metal work and scraping steel meant Google Maps had taken you to the wrong location, but in East Williamsburg the industrial and the cultural co-exist. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You&rsquo;ll find hidden-away DIY spaces, tech start-ups and trendy new shops in the most unexpected places, with that artistic vibe you dreamed of when you first decided to move to Brooklyn. For instance, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">a continuous </span><strong>mural</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vandervoort</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Place </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">stretches </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">almost the entire block between Thames Street and Flushing Avenue.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At </span><strong>56 Bogart</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, find a converted factory filled with artists&rsquo; studios and galleries, or explore </span><strong>The Loom</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a tucked away mini-mall filled with galleries, shops, a cafe, a tattoo parlor and a yoga studio. We love tropical beauty bar </span><strong>Wild Oleander</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a neon and flamingo-filled oasis in a basement with a side entrance down to the action, as well as vintage stores like </span><strong>Urban Jungle, Beacon&rsquo;s Closet</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and the touring </span><strong>Mobile Vintage Shop</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and used book store </span><strong>Human Relations</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Perhaps the most unexpected of all is </span><a href=\"https://www.brooklynzoony.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Brooklyn Zoo</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, an indoor training facility with recreated street scenes, complete with graffiti by local artists, which holds adult parkour classes, Ninja Warrior training, breakdancing classes and more. </span></p>\r\n<h1>The accessibility</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Williamsburg is arguably one of the best located neighborhoods in the whole of Brooklyn. The area is on the border of Greenpoint, Williamsburg, Bed-Stuy, Bushwick and Ridgewood &mdash; pretty much everywhere you&rsquo;ll ever need to go on nights or days out. This means that if you like walking, you can actually walk your way around Brooklyn, which is a pretty rare thing to be able to do. These neighboring areas all have their own unique personality, so you can head west into Williamsburg if you want to browse hipster </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">coffee shops</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (or go to the Apple Store), north into Greenpoint for </span><strong>McCarren Park</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or perogies, east into Ridgewood for a leafy stroll or Bushwick for endless murals and the famous </span><strong>House of Yes</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Williamsburg House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is a 14-minute walk to McCarren Park, an 11-minute walk to Graham Avenue and a 28-minute walk to Broadway. East Williamsburg is also incredibly accessible to Manhattan, being on the west side of Brooklyn. From our East Williamsburg House, you can be in the East Village in just 25 minutes, making it the perfect base if you want a shorter commute into the city. Hop on the L train at Grand Street, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Montrose Avenue</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Morgan Avenue</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, the J or the M at </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Flushing Avenue</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or even the G (at the other Flushing) to go in and out of Manhattan, up and down Brooklyn and into Queens.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/EastWilliamsburg.jpg\" alt=\"Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Credit: MySpace NYC Real Estate&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<h1>The sheer number of bars and restaurants</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East Williamsburg has access to the most bars and restaurants of any Brooklyn neighborhood and it seems like another joint pops up every week. According to </span><a href=\"https://medium.com/@karlsluis/brooklyns-best-neighborhood-by-the-numbers-35631a58c30e\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Medium</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, within a mile&rsquo;s walk from anywhere in the neighborhood, you can find 316 restaurants and 196 bars, with everything from cocktails to Moroccan food to juice bars. Famous </span><strong>Roberta&rsquo;s</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><strong> pizza</strong> was the original foothold of the neighborhood and is still one of the most popular spots for students and young professionals. This pizza place has an outdoor terrace with a relaxed and sociable vibe and its own Tiki Bar during the summer months. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For laid back glamour and a good old-fashioned grilled cheese and beer combo, try </span><strong>One Stop</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, just around the corner from our East Williamsburg House, or take a short walk to </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Grimm Artisanal Ales</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, the local brewery. Our favorite brunch spot is </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Guadalupe Inn</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which serves one of the best value bottomless brunches in Brooklyn, with delicious food and moorish mimosas. </span><strong>Norwind&rsquo;s </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">also has an unmissable happy hour, while </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Well</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> hosts regular live music events with a patio that&rsquo;s just perfect for summer.</span></p>\r\n<h1>...and coffee shops</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Walking around, you&rsquo;ll be struck by the number of inviting signs for &ldquo;coffee&rdquo; hanging subtly in windows or doorways. What&rsquo;s great is that the vibe of most of these cafes is completely relaxed and, unlike many of their Manhattan equivalents, the servers don&rsquo;t mind you buying one coffee and staying there all day on your laptop. Our favorite is </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ange Noir Cafe</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a sweet spot with comfy armchairs, a relaxed vibe and fast WiFi. The place is frequented weekly by the Bushwick Writer&rsquo;s Group, who hold regular workshops and &ldquo;shut up and write&rdquo; sessions here. This coffee shop also hosts regular concerts and stand-up comedy events in the back room.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Right around the corner, </span><strong>Swallow Cafe</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is another welcoming place to work on your screenplay, and </span><strong>City of Saint Coffee Roasters</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> has some of the best quality coffee in the city. The friendly staff at these spots stay open late, so you don&rsquo;t need to worry about having to cut your day early at 5 p.m., making East Williamsburg the perfect place to get creative.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img title=\"Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Screen%20Shot%202019-04-10%20at%202.48.44%20PM.png\" alt=\"Why East Williamsburg Is a Great Place to Live (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Credit: City of Saints Coffee Roasters/Instagram</span></em></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>The neighborhood is highly secure, and violent crime is incredibly infrequent. The <a href=\"../new-york\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">apartments</a> in this area are often the perfect size, even though the neighborhood may not be the most appealing. Some have an outside space as well. If people give East Williamsburg a chance, it might make a fantastic family neighborhood.</p>', 'daryan-shamkhali-102885-unsplash.jpg', 1, '2019-04-10 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:06:38', NULL, 0, 0),
(260, 'Outpost Club Announces West Coast Expansion for Coliving Housing', 1, 'outpost-club-announces-west-coast-expansion', 'outpost-club-announces-west-coast-expansion-for-coliving-housing', 'Outpost Club Announces West Coast Expansion for Coliving Housing', 'Outpost Club Announces West Coast Expansion for Coliving Housing', 'A leader in the coliving housing market in New York, Outpost brings market expertise for new housing opportunities in the tight San Francisco Bay Area housing market.', '<p>A leader in the coliving housing market in New York, Outpost brings market expertise for new housing opportunities in the tight San Francisco Bay Area housing market.</p>', '<p>SAN FRANCISCO, April 16, 2019&nbsp;- Outpost Club, a leading New York real estate technology platform for affordable, fully furnished, all-inclusive coliving, announced today its expansion to the West Coast with its first home in the San Francisco Bay Area. The housing platform for renters will add 250 affordable units in the City. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Outpost Co-Founder and CEO Sergii Starostin said <strong>, \"Young professionals, interns and post-grads use Outpost to jump into their careers without the worry of high living costs. Our platform captures the entire housing process, including&nbsp;sourcing, presenting, signing, paying, moving in and in-home experience.\"</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>Outpost has seen an exponentially increasing demand for its platform attracting over 400 applicants per month under tight housing market conditions. It currently operates 10 coliving homes with 200 beds across Manhattan, Brooklyn and Queens in New York City.</p>\r\n<p>Working with its strategic partner in San Francisco, SAYJ Global Partners, Outpost is establishing a long-needed rental experience for professionals in the Bay Area, where it is difficult to find high-quality housing that is safe, affordable and flexible.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>\"Outpost is working to keep prices low while maintaining quality homes to assist professionals benefiting from coliving advantages,\" </strong>said Judith Iglehart, a SAYJ Partner<strong>. \"There is a clear social need in the Bay Area for Outpost for renters beyond the technology sector, including young teachers and public workers.&nbsp;Outpost has the platform and a sustainable model to succeed on the West Coast.\"</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>\"We\'re excited to utilize the existing housing supply in the Bay Area and strengthen our partnerships on the West Coast. We\'re bringing the convenience and community that Outpost is most known for in NY,\" </strong>said Starostin<strong>. \"Our approach to coliving means young professionals are able to evolve their housing experience within Outpost as they develop their careers.\"</strong></em></p>\r\n<h2><strong>About Outpost</strong></h2>\r\n<p>Outpost Club, one of New York\'s leading coliving operators with 10 houses and more than 200 members, operates in the $600B U.S. rental market. Outpost makes better use of cities\' existing housing through master leases to build strong communities of people who see value in shared space. For more information, visit <a href=\"../\" target=\"_blank\">outpost-club.com</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Contacts:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Lauren Vega</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"mailto:lauren.vega@outpost-club.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">lauren.vega@outpost-club.com</a></p>\r\n<p>Judith Iglehart</p>\r\n<p>Judith@sayjglobalpartners.com</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>www.sayjglobalpartners.com</em></strong></p>', 'eric-ward-436177-unsplash.jpg', 1, '2019-04-16 05:00:00', NULL, 1, 0, 0),
(261, 'Destination: Koko Ramen', 1, 'destination-koko-ramen', '', 'Destination: Koko Ramen', 'Destination: Koko Ramen', 'Introducing Koko Ramen, our favorite place to get authentic Japanese ramen in Brooklyn, just a short walk from our Flatbush House', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Introducing </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Koko Ramen</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, our favorite place to get authentic Japanese ramen in Brooklyn, just a short walk from our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Flatbush House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Koko has an unassuming exterior, like most of New York City&rsquo;s gems: Its plastic red door and wooden panelled walls only hint at the magic inside. A yellow sign floating on the roof with a bowl of steaming ramen stencilled on it is your only indication to step inside: Ramen will follow.</span>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Introducing </span><strong>Koko Ramen</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, our favorite place to get authentic Japanese ramen in Brooklyn, just a short walk from our </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Flatbush House</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Koko has an unassuming exterior, like most of New York City&rsquo;s gems: Its plastic red door and wooden panelled walls only hint at the magic inside. A yellow sign floating on the roof with a bowl of steaming ramen stencilled on it is your only indication to step inside: Ramen will follow.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><br /><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Koko Ramen (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Yelpap1480584609ms-450x600.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Koko Ramen (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /><em>Photo: ITrueReview</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This cozy Japanese noodle shop is a highlight in the Cortelyou side of the neighborhood, just a few blocks from </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">the Courtelyou Q stop. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Established in 2016, Koko has quickly become a neighborhood favorite. Its small size means that at peak times there can be a line of ramen fans rolling out of the door, but before you panic, they also do take-out.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The main thing Koko Ramen is famous for is its happy hour, which runs from 12-7pm everyday. Get a side dish of edamame, chicken wings or gyoza free with your ramen dish, or choose from a Japanese beer or hot sake for just $5. But Koko Ramen is so much more than just this deal.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Koko Ramen (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_3.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Koko Ramen (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Photo: Koko Ramen/ Facebook</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The decor feels intimate and authentic, with lanterns dipping down at odd intervals and multi-colored ramen bowls and chopsticks stuck to the wooden panel walls. The seating consists of small wooden tables alongside bar stools looking out the front window, which adds&nbsp;to the community vibe. And of course, the friendly servers always bring your food out with a smile. The small size makes Koko the perfect place for a date or solo dining (but maybe not for a roommate group meal, unless you want half your group to be sat outside). If you&rsquo;re worried about getting a table, just be sure to go in the early evening or just before closing time.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We loved the Roast Duck Ramen ($16), with roasted duck, bean sprouts, kikurage mushrooms, bok choy and ajitama (soft boiled) egg. Somehow, the duck remained crispy (as it should be!) even despite the broth. Koko is most famous for their Koko Tonkotsu Ramen ($14), made with creamy pork bone broth and pork belly kakuni, spinach, menma, and a soft boiled egg, which comes complete with two fatty chunks of quality pork. Koko has found the secret to making a creamy broth that&rsquo;s not too salty with thick noodles that absorb every ounce of its flavor. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Pork Buns, Takoyaki and crispy Chicken Wings are also extremely popular with Brooklynites, who come from across the borough to get their ramen fix. Finish your meal with the Lava Cake, a flowing chocolate treat that truly melts in your mouth. Just make sure to head to an ATM before you check out Koko, because the restaurant is cash-only, although this certainly didn&rsquo;t spoil our night. Koko is a very special Flatbush institution indeed.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Koko Ramen (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o4.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Koko Ramen (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /><em>Photo: Alyssa S. / Yelp</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Koko Ramen</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">375 Marlborough Rd</span></em></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Brooklyn, NY 11226</span></em></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'o4.jpg', 1, '2019-04-16 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(262, 'Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet', 1, 'earth-day-small-things-you-can-do-to-help-the-planet', '', 'Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet', 'Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet', 'Happy Earth Day! The idea behind Earth Day is to demonstrate your support for environmental protection', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Happy Earth Day! The idea behind Earth Day is to demonstrate your support for environmental protection. The first Earth Day took place in 1970 and now it&rsquo;s celebrated in more than 193 countries across the globe -- and why (on Earth) wouldn&rsquo;t it be? Here are a few small things that you can do this Earth Day to help our planet out.</p>', '<p>Happy Earth Day! The idea behind Earth Day is to demonstrate your support for environmental protection. The first Earth Day took place in 1970 and now it&rsquo;s celebrated in more than 193 countries across the globe -- and why (on Earth) wouldn&rsquo;t it be? Here are a few small things that you can do this Earth Day to help our planet out:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/noah-buscher-1162202-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Reduce single-use plastic</h1>\r\n<p>Single-use plastic is exactly that: plastic you only use once, but which hangs around in the environment for many moons afterward. This includes plastic water bottles, bags and straws. According to <a href=\"https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/10/every-minute-one-garbage-truck-of-plastic-is-dumped-into-our-oceans/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">World Economic Forum</a>, humans produce 78 millions tons of plastic packaging every year, 32 percent of which is left to flow into our oceans, pouring the equivalent of one garbage truck of plastic into the ocean every minute.</p>\r\n<h1>Use a reusable water bottle</h1>\r\n<p>When was the last time you bought a drink in a plastic bottle, then threw it away the same day? <a href=\"https://www.aiga.org/case-study-watershed\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">According to AIGI, Americans purchase about 50 billion water bottles per year, averaging about 13 bottles per month.</a> Even aside from the environmental impact, this is an expensive way to stay hydrated.</p>\r\n<p>Thankfully, reusable water bottles are easy to pick up and very much in style right now. Brands like S&rsquo;well have managed to make them into fashion statements, with colorful designs and temperature-regulating materials, so you can use your bottle for hot coffee and tea as well as for cold drinks. S&rsquo;well even has a limited edition Earth Day bottle.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/jonathan-chng-1057613-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"Earth Day: Small things you can do to help the planet (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>BYO shopping bag</h1>\r\n<p>You can reduce your plastic (and therefore landfill) usage by using reusable shopping bags. <strong>Waste Management</strong> found that around 4 trillion plastic bags are used worldwide annually and only 1 percent of these are recycled. Although New York state is going to start charging us for plastic bags soon, there&rsquo;s no reason why you can&rsquo;t start right now. You can get small and even fashionable fold-away bags like these on Amazon or at local grocery stores like Trader Joe&rsquo;s.</p>\r\n<h1>Go strawless</h1>\r\n<p>The war on straws has begun! Half a billion straws are used in the world every day, which are probably the easiest things to cut out of your lifestyle. The anti-staw movement is fast gaining traction (read more at Plastic Pollution Coalition) and it&rsquo;s becoming a statement to reject a straw at a bar. You can also bring your own reusable straw if you can&rsquo;t go without.</p>\r\n<h1>Recycle</h1>\r\n<p>According to <a href=\"https://www.recycleacrossamerica.org/recycling-facts\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Recycle Across America</a>, ​U.S. recycling levels are currently 21.4 percent, mostly due to confusion about how to recycle, but if this were to reach 75 percent, it would be the environmental equivalent of removing 55 million cars from our roads each year. At Outpost, we want to move toward that target. We provide clearly labeled bins for recycling and landfill, so be sure to keep using these. And remember: Recycling isn&rsquo;t just good for the planet -- it&rsquo;s New York law.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Reduce your meat consumption</h1>\r\n<p>Going vegan is one of the most beneficial things you can do for the environment (all those cows produce a lot of methane -- learn about this and other factors <a href=\"https://www.peta.org/issues/animals-used-for-food/global-warming/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">here</a>) and according to <strong><a href=\"https://mercyforanimals.org/study-a-vegan-diets-environmental-impact\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mercy For Animals</a></strong><strong>,</strong> a vegan diet impacts the environment up to 84 percent less than that of a meat eater.</p>\r\n<p>Although it might be hard to go the whole way, you can still make an impact by reducing your meat and dairy consumption however you can. Maybe have one meatless day a week, or introduce one plant-based substitute into your diet. Every little bit helps, after all.</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'caleb-ekeroth-7479-unsplash.jpg', 1, '2019-04-22 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(263, 'Introducing Outpost Club membership tiers', 1, 'introducing-outpost-club-membership-tiers', '', 'Introducing Outpost Club membership tiers', 'Introducing Outpost Club membership tiers', 'Here at Outpost Club, we’re always looking for opportunities to make a difference to our members in the areas that matter most to them -- so we want to let you know about a change to our memberships that will give you access to a host of new benefits and flexibility during your time with us.', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here at Outpost Club, we&rsquo;re always looking for opportunities to make a difference to our members in the areas that matter most to them -- so we want to let you know about a change to our memberships that will give you access to a host of new benefits and flexibility during your time with us. </span></p>', '<p>Here at Outpost Club, we&rsquo;re always looking for opportunities to make a difference to our members in the areas that matter most to them -- so we want to let you know about a change to our memberships that will give you access to a host of new benefits and flexibility during your time with us.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Here&rsquo;s how it works: You choose your membership level -- Gold, Silver or Bronze -- and, once you&rsquo;ve paid your one-time membership fee, gain access to all the perks of that level, which you can read more about here.</strong></p>\r\n<h2>Why is Outpost Club changing its membership model?</h2>\r\n<p>What this change does is solve for the unpredictability of daily life; we&rsquo;ve taken into account the fact that our members tend to value mobility and want flexibility in their living arrangements. We&rsquo;ve preserved the benefits of our current membership for Silver and Bronze members, while building benefits into the new Gold membership that are meant to make it as easy as possible to adjust if your plans change.</p>\r\n<p>Flight canceled? We&rsquo;ll work with you so you have somewhere to stay while you rebook. Friends in town last-minute for the weekend? They can stay for free, no problem. Opportunity of a lifetime taking you out of town for a few months? We&rsquo;ll pause your stay. Whatever life throws at you, our Gold membership is meant to take care of it.</p>\r\n<h2>How does this benefit me?</h2>\r\n<p>Outpost members at all levels will continue to enjoy the same benefits they&rsquo;ve gotten used to during their stay, like included utilities and WiFi, cleaning services, fully furnished houses, access to Outpost Club events and provided household essentials. We&rsquo;re committed to making Outpost a great place to live regardless of whether you choose the Gold, Silver or Bronze plan.</p>\r\n<p>Our Gold membership is a great opportunity to take full advantage of our new perks, even if you&rsquo;re only staying with us for a short time. Those perks include exclusive monthly pricing, the ability to have a guest stay at Outpost for free for four nights per month; your friends and family won&rsquo;t have to worry about finding a place to stay during their visit, and you won&rsquo;t have to worry about an overnight guest fee!</p>\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ll also be able to pause your stay if your plans change for up to 90 days at any point during your membership, and you&rsquo;ll enjoy a free week&rsquo;s stay at an Outpost Club house at any point in the 6 months following the end of your membership and the flexibility to cancel your stay with 30 days&rsquo; notice for only $250.</p>\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ll see the full benefit of our exclusive monthly Gold rates if you&rsquo;re staying with us for even longer, as a Gold membership will pay for itself after 4 months.</p>\r\n<h2>What does it mean for my existing membership?</h2>\r\n<p>Nothing, unless you want it to! Current Outpost Club members will be grandfathered into our previous membership model, meaning that through the end of your current agreement, you&rsquo;ll be locked into the membership originally signed up for. Your pricing will stay the same unless you choose to make a change to your current agreement. Here&rsquo;s what that means:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If you stay in your current room in your current house, your original agreement will be honored.</li>\r\n<li>If you choose to make certain changes to your original agreement -- meaning switching houses or downgrading your membership -- you&rsquo;ll be moved to the new membership model.</li>\r\n<li>If you choose to upgrade your membership (for example, by moving from a shared room to a private room), you may choose to continue under your original membership agreement.</li>\r\n<li>If you choose to extend your original agreement, you&rsquo;ll move to the new membership model.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Introducing Outpost Club membership tiers (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/MA_201180.jpg\" alt=\"Introducing Outpost Club membership tiers (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h2>What do the memberships include?</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Bronze and Silver memberships include the following, with the exception of Silver members being able to move in on any day of the month (instead of just on the 1st):</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>All-inclusive membership: We take care of utilities, WiFi and household essentials</li>\r\n<li>Access to multiple events every month</li>\r\n<li>Fully furnished, recently remodeled houses</li>\r\n<li>24/7 security in all common areas</li>\r\n<li>Cleaning and maintenance: We take care of your home so you don\'t have to</li>\r\n<li>Free stays: Your guests stay for free up to 1 night per month\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Silver members: If you are a Silver member with a private bedroom, you may have a guest stay in your room up to three times per month.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>In addition to all of the perks Silver members enjoy, your Gold membership includes:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Exclusive membership rates</li>\r\n<li>Free stays: Your guests stay for free up to 4 nights per month\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If you have a private bedroom, you may have a guest stay in your room up to seven times per month.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Access to all Outpost Club houses</li>\r\n<li>Priority access to new Outpost Club houses</li>\r\n<li>One free week\'s stay during 6 mos. after the end of your membership agreement</li>\r\n<li>Flexibility: Cancel your stay with 30-day notice for a $250 fee</li>\r\n<li>Pause your stay for 30-90 days</li>\r\n<li>Airplane insurance: We\'ll work with you if your travel plans change for up to two additional nights of stay</li>\r\n<li>Same-day move-in option</li>\r\n<li>No late-night check-in fee</li>\r\n<li>Flexible deposit options</li>\r\n<li>Free premium events</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em><strong>The Bronze level is free with your membership. You can upgrade to a Silver membership for a one-time fee of $29 and to Gold for a one-time fee of $690. You can check out the full details of the new membership plans <a href=\"../memberships\">here</a>.</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '350manhattan_large-5_1.jpg', 1, '2019-04-23 05:00:00', NULL, 1, 0, 0),
(264, 'Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend', 1, 'where-to-see-the-cherry-blossoms-in-brooklyn-this-weekend', '', 'Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend | Outpost Club blog', 'Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend', 'You might have noticed that the Brooklyn streets are looking a little more colorful these days: Spring is officially here and it’s all thanks to the blooming cherry blossoms.', '<p>You might have noticed that the Brooklyn streets are looking a little more colorful these days: Spring is officially here and it&rsquo;s all thanks to the blooming cherry blossoms. These beautiful trees are finally gracing us with their pink and white hues and this weekend is the height of it all: The Brooklyn Botanic Garden&rsquo;s annual Cherry Blossom Festival is here!</p>', '<p>You might have noticed that the Brooklyn streets are looking a little more colorful these days: Spring is officially here and it&rsquo;s all thanks to the blooming cherry blossoms. These beautiful trees are finally gracing us with their pink and white hues and this weekend is the height of it all: The Brooklyn Botanic Garden&rsquo;s annual Cherry Blossom Festival is here!</p>\r\n<p>Even if you can&rsquo;t catch the festival, here are our top picks of where to check out the blooms this weekend (because they won&rsquo;t be around forever!).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/bbg_spring_cherryesplanade_antoniomrosario-1489079942-826-1490882945-3578.jpg\" alt=\"Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /><em>Photo: Patch.com</em></p>\r\n<h3>Brooklyn Botanic Garden</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Sakura Matsuri</strong> is Brooklyn Botanic Garden\'s annual cherry blossom festival and is taking place this weekend. Enjoy 52 acres of the most beautiful cherry blossoms, plus a timetable of events celebrating Japanese culture, including live music, dance performances, art demonstrations, tea ceremonies, Japanese inspired food and more. The garden has more than 200 trees, with rows of bright pink blossoms flowering all down Cherry Esplanade.</p>\r\n<p>You can even <strong>check the Cherry Watch</strong>, the <strong>Garden&rsquo;s web page that is updated each day</strong> with live updates on the petal blooming status of every tree in the main collection. Plus, the Botanic Garden is right by Prospect Park, as well as our Flatbush and <a href=\"../the-bed-stuy-house\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bed-Stuy</a> houses, so you can make a day of it. Find out more and get your tickets here or RSVP to the Facebook event here.</p>\r\n<h3>McCarren Park</h3>\r\n<p><strong>McCarren Park</strong> is a Brooklyn oasis of calm and happiness. It makes us even more happy now that there are cherry blossoms to stare at. This 35-acre greenland is a Brooklyn favorite, always filled with sunbathers, games of kickball, soccer and tennis, and runners. Located between Greenpoint and Williamsburg and right by our East Williamsburg House, the park is home to flowering Eastern Redbud trees this spring. These trees grow to about 30 feet tall and are lit up at nighttime for the perfect view.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/brooklyn-botanic-garden-cherry-blossoms-5.jpg\" alt=\"Where to see the cherry blossoms in Brooklyn this weekend (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Photo: Brownstoner</em></p>\r\n<h3>Prospect Park</h3>\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re not ready for the crowds or the ticket price of the official Cherry Blossom Festival, adjacent to the Botanic Garden is beautiful Prospect Park. Enter at the Grand Army Plaza and walk along the stone path in the Long Meadow to see the full view. You can look up where all the different types of trees and flowers will blossom in the park with the Prospect Park Alliance&rsquo;s <strong>Spring Bloom Guide</strong><a href=\"https://www.prospectpark.org/news-events/news/spring-bloom-guide/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">.</a> Bring a picnic and spend your Saturday chilling on the grass beneath the cherry trees!</p>\r\n<h3>Greenwood Cemetery</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Greenwood Cemetery</strong> has both pink and white cherry blossom trees blooming. Walk along <strong>Battle Avenue</strong> and <strong>Crescent Water</strong> to see the highest number of trees, although the cherry blossoms are dotted all through the graves and mausoleums. The cemetery is famous and worth a visit on its own merits, being the home of beautiful stone architecture and the graves of several deceased famous New Yorkers.</p>\r\n<p>Brooklyn\'s cherry blossom season lasts from mid-March until late April. But different cherry tree species bloom at various times during the spring. While specific dates are difficult to predict, some trees usually bloom before others. Do not pass up the opportunity to see this lovely location. Outpost Club <a href=\"../full-apartments\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">apartments</a> have the greatest view of the cherry blossoms.</p>', 'bbg_spring_cherryesplanade_antoniomrosario-1489079942-826-1490882945-3578.jpg', 1, '2019-04-25 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:08:30', NULL, 0, 0),
(265, '#MemberMonday: Jasper Heymans', 1, 'membermonday-jasper-heymans', '', '#MemberMonday: Jasper Heymans', '#MemberMonday: Jasper Heymans', 'This week\'s #MemberMonday is Jasper Heymans from Belgium, a new member of our East Bushwick House.', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This week\'s #MemberMonday</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;is Jasper Heymans from Belgium, a new member of our East Bushwick House.</span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This week\'s <strong>#MemberMonday</strong></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;is Jasper Heymans from Belgium, a new member of our East Bushwick House.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"#MemberMonday: Jasper Heymans (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/IMG_2910.JPG\" alt=\"#MemberMonday: Jasper Heymans (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Tell us a bit about yourself.</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hey, I&rsquo;m Jasper. I&rsquo;m 22 years old, a Product Design student from Belgium and I&rsquo;m here for an internship in product design until June.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">My favorite Outpost memory is not one moment, but the fact that I met so many inspiring people that create amazing moments. (Yes, cheesy, haha, I know.) </span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>What&rsquo;s your favorite part of New York?</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I really like Chinatown. The atmosphere there is amazing and the food as well. But on a sunny day, walking over Brooklyn Bridge and chilling at Brooklyn Bridge Park is my favorite thing to do so far.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>What are you working on now?</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Right now I&rsquo;m concentrating on my internship, but back home some interesting projects are waiting for me which I&rsquo;ll finish with a lot of new inspiration and knowledge.</span></p>', 'IMG_2910.JPG', 1, '2019-04-29 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(266, 'Outpost\'s first San Francisco house will be in Japantown', 1, 'outposts-first-san-francisco-house-will-be-in-japantown', '', 'Outpost San Francisco Is Officially Open | Outpost Club blog', 'Outpost\'s first San Francisco house will be in Japantown', 'It’s only been a few weeks since we announced we were planning to expand to the West Coast, and we’re excited to say that as of today, that dream has become a reality', '<p>We may have just announced we\'re heading to the West Coast, but now we have even more exciting news for you: Outpost is opening our first location, in the historic&nbsp;Japantown&nbsp;neighborhood of San Francisco.</p>', '<p>We may have just announced we\'re heading to the West Coast, but now we have even more exciting news for you: Outpost is opening our first location, in the historic&nbsp;Japantown&nbsp;neighborhood of San Francisco.</p>\r\n<p>Our new house has two floors of spaces designed with comfort and community in mind, whether you want to camp out&nbsp;in our large co-working space to finish a project or lounge on the couch watching Netflix (it\'s included!).&nbsp;The house is close to public transit, parks, and plenty of shopping, dining and entertainment options.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>San Francisco is home to one of only three Japantowns left in the U.S., and the six blocks the neighborhood encompasses are packed to bursting with Japanese culture, from restaurants and theaters to locally owned shops and caf&eacute;s. The first thing you\'ll notice, though, is the Peace Pagoda, a historical monument and gift to San Francisco by its sister city, Osaka.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The five-tiered pagoda, situated at the heart of the neighborhood, was constructed in the \'60s as a monument to friendly Japanese-American relations. Architect&nbsp;Yoshirō Taniguchi, who also designed the &nbsp;National Museum of Modern Art in Tokyo, had this to say about the towering structure:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"The Peace Pagoda lifts up its hundred-feet-high spire to the skies of California. It presents a magnificent view to all esthetically minded people who raise their eyes up to the horizon on the perimeters of San Francisco.\"</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Outpost\'s first San Francisco house will be in Japantown (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/4479558353_ab7a3ac529_b.jpg\" alt=\"Outpost\'s first San Francisco house will be in Japantown (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Photo: Michael Ocampo</em></p>\r\n<p>In the pagoda\'s shadow lie a rich variety of neighborhood institutions. Make sure to pay a visit to&nbsp;Kinokuniya Bookstore, Japan\'s largest bookstore chain, for a variety of Japanese books, magazines and gifts, then head to Playground, where you\'ll find San Francisco\'s only combination restaurant-bar-private karaoke.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When you\'re in the mood to explore more of what the city has to offer, you\'ll find yourself centrally located to many of San Francisco\'s gems, from Golden Gate Park -- which is even larger than New York\'s Central Park -- to the Haight-Ashbury (known as the birthplace of hippie counterculture) and the Mission (with its killer nightlife) neighborhoods.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Once you\'re tired out, come home to Japantown and spend a few hours deciding what to watch on Netflix or lounge with your housemates over a glass of wine. As always, membership at Outpost gets you access to premium spaces and perks like exclusive events, weekly cleaning and household essentials that never run out -- and that\'s not to mention&nbsp;all the great people you\'ll meet!</p>\r\n<p>Be one of the first to sign up to get special membership rates in celebration of Outpost x SF. Interested? Just shoot us your contact info <a href=\"mailto:customer.service@outpost-club.com\">here</a> and we\'ll be in touch.</p>\r\n<p>Although The Outpost Club is pleased to give you lovely residences in San Francisco, it is not all we have to offer. You can either use the shared housing scheme or <a href=\"../new-york\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">rent an apartment</a> in New York or Philadelphia. We can offer superb flats in these cities, and we haven\'t forgotten about the students either.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><em>Top photo credit: David Sanabria</em></strong></p>', 'Screen Shot 2019-04-30 at 3.03.13 PM.png', 1, '2019-04-30 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:47:38', NULL, 0, 0);
