(362, '5 classic books perfect for quarantine', 1, '5-classic-books-perfect-for-quarantine', '', '5 classic books perfect for quarantine', '5 classic books perfect for quarantine', 'Whether you’re looking to laugh until you cry or escape to another world, now is a great time to delve that long, ever growing list of classic books on your bucket list. Here are our top picks of the ones to read during quarantine. ', '<p>Whether you&rsquo;re looking to laugh until you cry or escape to another world, now is a great time to delve that long, ever growing list of classic books on your bucket list. Here are our top picks of the ones to read during quarantine.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Whether you&rsquo;re looking to laugh until you cry or escape to another world, now is a great time to delve that long, ever growing list of classic books on your bucket list. Here are our top picks of the ones to read during quarantine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>1. Jane Eyre</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Jane-Eyre-AmazonClassics-Charlotte-Bront&euml;-ebook/dp/B0721B7NPX/ref=sr_1_4?dchild=1&amp;keywords=Jane+eyre&amp;qid=1587467569&amp;sr=8-4\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Jane Eyre</a></em> is the perfect inspiration story for quarantine. Why? You&rsquo;re hard pressed to find such a tough cookie as Jane in classic literature who still always maintains her sense of kindness. She bears her turbulent life with the most positive outlook, always ready to see the good in people and willing to share the little that she has with others. It&rsquo;s an incredibly heartwarming story filled with twists and turns; </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Charlotte Bront&euml;&rsquo;s Gothic masterpiece will transport you from your cramped apartment straight to nineteenth century England (and whether you&rsquo;re identifying more with Jane or the madwoman in the attic right now is up to you!)</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If there were ever a time we needed to escape to a magical realm through our wardrobes, it would be now. Take a trip to Narnia with C.S. Lewis&rsquo;s <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Lion-Witch-Wardrobe-Chronicles-Narnia/dp/0064404994/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1AGALKD9TQHH2&amp;dchild=1&amp;keywords=the+lion+the+witch+and+the+wardrobe&amp;qid=1587467611&amp;sprefix=the+lion+the%2Caps%2C220&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">timeless tale</a> full of fauns, dwarves and turkish delight and let Mr Tumnes cheer you up, whether you&rsquo;re a Peter, Edmund, Susan or Lucy. Even though it&rsquo;s a children&rsquo;s book, this tale is beautifully written and perfect to dive into over a hot cup of coffee in your lunch break.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>3. Mrs Spring Fragrance</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the theme of childhood escapism, we love Sui Sin Far&rsquo;s <em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Mrs-Spring-Fragrance-Collection-Chinese-American-ebook/dp/B00GSV9D9E/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=1&amp;keywords=mrs+spring+fragrance&amp;qid=1587467686&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mrs Spring Fragrance</a></em></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a classic of Chinese-American literature. This popular short story collection written in the late 19th and 20th centuries are a mixture of stories for adults and for children set in Seattle and San Francisco. Chronicling the struggles and joys of Chinese families in North America, Sui Sin Far weaves classic Chinese folklore stories with her personal experiences to explore the conflicts between Eurasians and recent immigrants in a touching, meaningful way.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>4. Frankenstein</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Mary Shelley&rsquo;s <em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Frankenstein-Mary-Shelley/dp/1512308056/ref=sr_1_2?dchild=1&amp;keywords=Frankenstein+Mary+shelley&amp;qid=1587467791&amp;sr=8-2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Frankenstein</a>&nbsp;</em>tells the story of Victor Frankentein, a young scientist who conducts a crazy scientific experiment, creating a hideous creature which takes on a life of its own. This short novel mixes Gothic and Sci-Fi elements in a fascinating narrative, raising important questions about friendship, taking responsibility for your actions and the ever important debate of nature versus nurture. It&rsquo;s also a gripping read that will make you forget your quarantine blues (and make you thankful to be tucked away inside your home and not outside with the monsters!)</p>\r\n<h1><strong>5. Mrs Dalloway</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Virginia Woolf&rsquo;s <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Mrs-Dalloway-Virginia-Woolf/dp/0156628708/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=1&amp;keywords=mrs+dalloway&amp;qid=1587467906&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">masterpiece novel</a> is a favorite of many. It&rsquo;s also a perfect read for quarantine. Woolf&rsquo;s exploration of time and the little moments of life which make up the bigger picture will make you appreciate that in-joke with a friend on the phone or even that occasional walk to the grocery store, making you realise that time can be fluid and broken down in many ways, even in these strange times we find ourselves in. Woolf also explores trauma and psychoanalysis while remaining uplifting and charming in tone, making you fall in love with the world of Clarissa Dalloway (even if you can&rsquo;t have your own party!)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Bonus: The Argonauts</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Okay, this one is a modern classic. Maggie Nelson&rsquo;s <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Argonauts-Maggie-Nelson/dp/1555977359/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=1&amp;keywords=Maggie+Nelson+the+argonauts&amp;qid=1587467973&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">2015 memoir</a> about love, gender, gender theory, having children and queer family making is an incredibly touching quarantine read. Nelson weaves in critical theory to her own experiences, meditating on the practical implications for her life and the lives of her reader&rsquo;s, as we watch her deal with queerphobia, gender stereotyping and familial realities in this beautifully written work of &ldquo;autotheory.&rdquo;</span></p>', '2_17.jpg', 1, '2020-04-21 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(284, 'Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019', 1, 'outpost-celebrates-nyc-pride-2019', '', 'Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019', 'Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019', 'This was a special year for NYC Pride, marking the first year a US city has ever hosted WorldPride', '<p>This was a special year for NYC Pride, marking the first year a US city has ever hosted WorldPride, as well as commemorating the 50th anniversary of the Stonewall Uprising, which many believe launched the LGBTQ radical movement in the United States. The Outpost team came out in full force to support the LGBTQIA+ community last Sunday.</p>', '<p>This was a special year for NYC Pride, marking the first year a US city has ever hosted WorldPride, as well as commemorating the 50th anniversary of the Stonewall Uprising, which many believe launched the LGBTQ radical movement in the United States. The Outpost team came out in full force to support the LGBTQIA+ community last Sunday.&nbsp;We started off the day with our Pride Brunch event at the Montrose Williamsburg House.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019 (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Pride1.jpg\" alt=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019(Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Members from our houses across the city made their way to this new Outpost location for a selection of sweet and savoury crepes, mimosas and flowing conversation. With its large kitchen island and high ceilings, this house was the perfect place to kick off the day in style.</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019 (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Pride3.jpg\" alt=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019(Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Members came wearing a variety of colors and flags in support of Pride and we even had a glitter station, where Claire showed off her artistic side (and generosity!) by painting beautiful designs on the Outpost members. Jianela, a member of our East Bushwick House, said, &lsquo;I like how accepting people were. Also, I enjoyed everyone&rsquo;s outfits and seeing everyone support the flag and what it represents.&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019 (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Pride2.jpg\" alt=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019(Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After brunch, the Outpost cohort headed to&nbsp;the center of the action at Union Square. We watched the march from the main strip along 5th Avenue, taking in the vast array of floats, performance artists and protesters which passed by. Around </span><a href=\"https://abc7ny.com/society/mayor-5-million-people-attended-worldpride-events-in-nyc/5375712/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">5 million people attended</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> WorldPride in New York City over the weekend, but with the friendly atmosphere and positive vibes it didn&rsquo;t feel overcrowded. Other members of Outpost also attended the </span><a href=\"https://www.thedailybeast.com/queer-liberation-march-first-ever-in-new-york-city-showed-a-new-old-way-to-feel-pride\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Queer Liberation March</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, an alternative event which took place hours before the NYC Pride March, without corporate-sponsored floats.</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019 (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Pride7.png\" alt=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019(Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The march marked the end of a month of events in celebration of Pride in NYC, which included a special exhibition at the <strong>New York Public Library</strong> and a series of art shows, concerts and informative public talks. As day turned to night, the Empire State Building even illuminated its tip in rainbow colors for the occasion, and the Outpost contingent continued to celebrate in the city that never sleeps.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img title=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019 (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Pride6.jpg\" alt=\"Outpost celebrates NYC Pride 2019(Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Outpost was proud to share this year&rsquo;s Pride march with a couple of first-timers, including Lauren, our Marketing Manager, and Daniel, the House Leader at our Bed-Stuy House.</p>\r\n<p>Lauren said of the day: &lsquo;It was so meaningful to me to be able to share my first Pride with such a great group of people. We laughed, we screamed, we got glitter in our eyes ... I had some beautiful conversations with people I&rsquo;ve come to care about and had an absolute blast. I can&rsquo;t wait until next year.&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Daniel told us: &lsquo;It was my first pride event that I had the chance to attend. I was lucky enough to be in a city which is not only famous for having the best pride celebrations in the world, but is also where it all began. Being part of the 50th anniversary of the Stonewall Riots has been an amazing experience. As a proud member of the queer community, it was awesome to celebrate love, freedom and equality for all our LGBTQ+ brothers and sisters. Without mentioning that I had the best time mainly because I was surrounded by incredible people!&rsquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'outpost-celebrates-nyc-pride-2019.jpg', 1, '2019-07-03 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(285, 'Member Monday:  Sudesika Prabaharan', 1, 'member-monday-sudesika-prabaharan', '', 'Member Monday:  Sudesika Prabaharan', 'Member Monday:  Sudesika Prabaharan', 'Meet Su, the House Leader at our South Williamsburg House and a girl with a serious passion for travel.', '<p>Meet Su, the House Leader at our South Williamsburg House and a girl with a serious passion for travel.</p>', '<p>Meet Su, the House Leader at our South Williamsburg House and a girl with a serious passion for travel.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Member Monday:  Sudesika Prabaharan (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/58818412_2385579754990004_7913513075792150528_n.jpg\" alt=\"Member Monday:  Sudesika Prabaharan (Image-1)\" width=\"480\" height=\"492\" /></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Tell us a bit about yourself.</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hello you guys! My name is Su. I was born in Sri-Lanka and raised in France. I started traveling on my own at age 19, and since then the thirst of discovering new places, new cultures and meeting people from all over the world that I gained hasn&rsquo;t been quenched a bit.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">My favorite Outpost memory &hellip; there are too many to count, even though I have not been here for long. One of my favorite times was the introduction of corn hole in our backyard at South Williamsburg. I had a lot of fun discovering this game and sharing this unique moment with different members of the Outpost community, some of whom I would say were expert-level corn hole competitors. I also love spending time on the roof with other Outpost members, sharing our stories, doing our evening workout or just simply sitting quietly and listening to the city being alive around us &hellip; all of these become exceptional moments when in NYC.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>What&rsquo;s your favorite part of New York?</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;</span></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">My favorite part of New York? That\'s a tough one, because each corner of New York City has its own beauty. I love the vibrant energy running through the city. I think it is the high concentration of diversity in one unique, beautiful town, which gives such a strong and fierce personality to NYC. You can be anyone, do anything, and there is always something new and fun to discover. In fact, writing this post has inspired me to get out and get to know New York City even more.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>What are you working on now?</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I am working on developing and discovering new skills. At the present moment I am spending time drawing and I am trying to get together a drawing portfolio by the end of the summer. I also have a big interest in essential oils and in their healing properties, so I am personally working on creating my own essential mixes and trying to develop my brand.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'thumbnail.jpg', 0, '2019-07-22 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(289, '7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC', 1, '7-ways-to-escape-the-humidity-in-nyc', '', '7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC', '7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC | Outpost Club blog', 'There is no denying that the summers in New York City are humid. Together with Outpost Club, let\'s figure out how to avoid the humidity.', '<p>Summer in New York City is humid, there&rsquo;s no doubt about it. With averages of 50- to 75-percent humidity (and most recently, with the scale hitting 82 percent), you&rsquo;re probably wondering what you can do to escape this heavy weather. Well, we&rsquo;ve got you covered.</p>', '<p>Summer in New York City is humid, there&rsquo;s no doubt about it. With averages of 50- to 75-percent humidity (and most recently, with the scale hitting 82 percent), you&rsquo;re probably wondering what you can do to escape this heavy weather. Well, we&rsquo;ve got you covered.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_12.jpg\" alt=\"7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo:&nbsp;<em>Wing Y., Yelp</em></p>\r\n<h1><strong><strong>1. Check out a museum</strong></strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Museums and galleries abound in New York, and almost all of them have super-strong AC alongside mind-expanding exhibitions. Our top recommendation goes to </span><strong><a href=\"https://www.metmuseum.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Met</a></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, simply because it&rsquo;s so big that you could spend an entire day there gazing at the more than 5,000 years of art history &mdash; plus, it offers pay-what-you-wish admission for New York residents, so there&rsquo;s no need to worry about breaking the bank.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We also love the Mela Foundation&rsquo;s </span><strong>Dream House</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a brightly colored space filled with AC and pillows to whittle the day and night away, as well as </span><strong>The New York Earth Room</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a giant display room filled with cooling earth across the floor.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. Head to an indoor garden</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The city has several indoor gardens that allow you to enjoy the best of nature while still feeling the AC breeze. Our favorite is the </span><a href=\"https://tclf.org/landscapes/ford-foundation-atrium\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ford Foundation Atrium</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> nearby Grand Central, tucked away inside glass panels in the Ford Foundation building. This 160-foot-tall garden is filled with trees and tropical plants, and even has its own reflection pool. It&rsquo;s the perfect place to enjoy fresh air without the moisture of the NYC outdoors.</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_11.jpg\" alt=\"7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo:&nbsp;<em>Christin M., Yelp</em></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>3. Shop inside</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Air-conditioned malls are an obvious way to escape the humidity, although in New York there&rsquo;s more to it than that. We love </span><strong>Brookfield Place</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for window-shopping and dining in the summertime, but there are also plenty of less conventional mall options, including flea markets like </span><strong>The Alley Flea Market</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> in Bushwick or </span><strong>Artists &amp; Fleas</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> in Williamsburg, which include indoor areas.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>4. Play some games</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Board game cafes are your answer to air-conditioned, daytime fun. We love </span><strong>The Uncommons</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> near Washington Square Park as an escape from the heavy NYC air. Enjoy a selection of hundreds of boardgames, as well as coffee, WiFi and good vibes.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_14.jpg\" alt=\"7 ways to escape the humidity in NYC (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo:&nbsp;<em>Mandi W., Yelp</em></span></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>5. Head to the library</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The </span><strong><a href=\"https://www.nypl.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">New York Public Library</a></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is an amazing thing. With 92 locations across the city filled with AC, it&rsquo;s the perfect place to escape the humidity. Of course, we love the main </span><strong>Stephen A. Schwarzman Building</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> branch for its imposing architecture and cool white marble.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>6. Check out a Broadway show</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;re looking for an indoor activity without the high temperatures, why not check out a Broadway or an Off-Broadway show? These shows are a major NYC bucket-list item and often have affordable tickets for the lunchtime matinees. Try </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">TodayTix</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for reduced-price seats or turn up at the box office early in the morning for cheap same-day tickets.</span></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>7. If you have to be outside&hellip;</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Sometimes the best things are outside. If you have to or want to be out in the humidity, make sure you wear lightweight clothing. Another tip is to bring a second shirt to change into after your sweaty walk or subway expedition, so you can arrive looking half decent at your destination. Even with the humidity, NYC is still buzzing with things to see and do in the summer.</p>\r\n<p>Don\'t overlook the wonderful activity you enjoy doing at home. The pace of life in New York is unique, and occasionally, just looking out the window can elicit strong emotions. What could be more enjoyable than a cup of coffee in the morning with a friend? <a href=\"../coliving\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Living together</a>, of course, since spending the summer in New York with pals is worthwhile.</p>', 'JACKSON_SEASON19_SHOWIMAGES_1238x520_v35-6042a653ee.jpg', 1, '2019-07-18 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:09:45', NULL, 0, 0),
(286, 'What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July', 1, 'what-outpost-got-up-to-on-the-4th-of-july', '', 'What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July', 'What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July', 'Every year, Outpost celebrates the 4th of July, and this year was bigger than ever before. Members from all of our eleven New York City houses came out to celebrate American Independence the old fashioned way--with an all-day BBQ party.\r\n', '<p>Every year, Outpost celebrates the 4th of July, and this year was bigger than ever before. Members from all of our eleven New York City houses came out to celebrate American Independence the old fashioned way--with an all-day BBQ party.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Every year, Outpost celebrates the 4th of July, and this year was bigger than ever before. Members from all of our eleven New York City houses came out to celebrate American Independence the old fashioned way--with an all-day BBQ party.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/4th%20July-9.jpg\" alt=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On a beautifully sunny Thursday afternoon, we headed to the South Williamsburg House to socialize and celebrate in style. We kicked off the festivities with games of cornhole and bocce ball, while Outpost volunteers helped prepare the BBQ. There was red, white and blue decorations, flags and some of our members even came dressed in costume for the occasion.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/4th%20July-5.jpg\" alt=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The food was incredible, with classic American favorites like hot dogs and burgers rolling out throughout the day, plus potato salad, chips and every other side you can think of. We even had an American flag cake for dessert and of course plenty of punch to get us through the hot day.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/4th%20July-26.jpg\" alt=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>When the sun went down, we headed to the rooftop to watch the fireworks. What we didn&rsquo;t expect was all the smaller fireworks displays, as people from Manhattan and Brooklyn spent the night setting off their own version of the official fireworks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It was amazing to watch all of these displays happening at the same time and it really gave us a sense of the New York City community. The night ended with dancing, laughing and plenty of memory-making and we can&rsquo;t wait to get planning for next year.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/4th%20July-3.jpg\" alt=\"What Outpost got up to on the 4th of July (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '4th July-9.jpg', 1, '2019-07-10 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(287, 'Tonight’s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it', 1, 'tonights-manhattanhenge-what-it-is-and-where-to-watch-it', '', 'Tonight’s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it', 'Tonight’s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it', 'It’s that time of year again: Manhattanhenge is here. Also called the Manhattan Solstice, Manhattanhenge is a unique moment when the setting sun is aligned with the east-west streets of the main street grid of Manhattan, creating the spectacle of a full-disk sun perfectly framed by Manhattan’s skyscrapers.\r\n', '<p>It&rsquo;s that time of year again: Manhattanhenge is here. Also called the Manhattan Solstice, Manhattanhenge is a unique moment when the setting sun is aligned with the east-west streets of the main street grid of Manhattan, creating the spectacle of a full-disk sun perfectly framed by Manhattan&rsquo;s skyscrapers.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>It&rsquo;s that time of year again: Manhattanhenge is here. Also called the Manhattan Solstice, Manhattanhenge is a unique moment when the setting sun is aligned with the east-west streets of the main street grid of Manhattan, creating the spectacle of a full-disk sun perfectly framed by Manhattan&rsquo;s skyscrapers.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Tonight&rsquo;s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Manhattanhenge_2016-07-12-FRD.png\" alt=\"Tonight&rsquo;s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Manhattanhenge only happens twice a year and this weekend will be your last chance to catch it in 2019. Tonight is your last chance to catch a full disk, the best version of the Manhattanhenge experience, while tomorrow night a half-disk will be visible, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">according to the American Museum of Natural History</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. The name </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is a reference to </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Stonehenge</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which was constructed so that the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">rising sun</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, seen from the center of the monument at the time of the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">summer solstice</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, aligns with the outer </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Heel Stone</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;re into the details, the reason for Manhattanhenge is that the street grid for most of Manhattan is rotated 29&deg; clockwise from true east-west, which means when the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">azimuth</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">sunset</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is 299&deg;, the sunset aligns with the streets on that grid.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In order to catch Manhattanhenge tonight, make sure you&rsquo;re in the city by 8 p.m. The sun will set at 8:20 p.m, but it&rsquo;s good to arrive beforehand to see the changing colors of the sky &mdash; and you may have to fight to get a good spot among the crowds of tourists and locals who will flock to the streets for the occasion.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Tonight&rsquo;s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Unknown.jpg\" alt=\"Tonight&rsquo;s Manhattanhenge: What it is and where to watch it (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Accuweather</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The best places for viewing Manhattanhenge are 14th, 23rd, 34th, 42nd, and 57th streets. Because the sun sets in the west, it&rsquo;s not too important which avenue you choose to stand on, although the wider the cross street, the better. Because the best shots will include plenty of NYC skyscrapers in the background, we recommend not standing too far west. Our pick would be 42nd street and either Lexington or 3rd avenues, so you get the beautiful Chrysler Building in your shot.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There will also be another opportunity to catch the sunset at the same time tomorrow, although this will only be a half disk, so the main show will certainly be tonight. Be prepared for crowds and get your filters ready; you&rsquo;re about to take part in a New York institution.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'Manhattanhenge_2016-07-12-FRD.png', 1, '2019-07-12 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(288, 'The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg', 1, 'the-15-best-instagram-spots-in-williamsburg', '', 'The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg | Outpost Club blog', 'The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg', 'Williamsburg is a photographer\'s paradise. To make things easier, we\'ve picked out the 15 best spots to snap and hashtag.', '<p>Williamsburg is a photographer\'s paradise. To make things easier, we\'ve picked out the 15 best spots to snap and hashtag.</p>', '<p>Williamsburg is a photographer\'s paradise. To make things easier, we\'ve picked out the 15 best spots to snap and hashtag.</p>\r\n<h3>1. Bedford Avenue</h3>\r\n<p>Get off at the Bedford Avenue L stop and walk down the avenue between the Apple Store and McCarren Park and you&rsquo;ll find a line of boutiques that will equal what you think of as &lsquo;typical&rsquo; Williamsburg. Picturesque jewelry stores like Norbu Bijoux and The Stone Flower will make the perfect centerpiece for your&nbsp;shots.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/64887801_355030741841585_7876161090099662783_n.jpg\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>N</em><em>orbu</em>&nbsp;<em>Bijoux</em></p>\r\n<h3>2. Chris Riggs \"Love and Peace\" Mural</h3>\r\n<p>&nbsp;This mural at 175 Marcy Avenue is colorful and unique, making it the perfect material for your next Instagram shot.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/56191581.png\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo:&nbsp;<em>Expose Art Magazine</em></p>\r\n<h3>3. The Williamsburg Bridge</h3>\r\n<p>Obvious, but still important. Walk over the Williamsburg Bridge to get that iconic shot.</p>\r\n<h3>4. North Brooklyn Farms</h3>\r\n<p>Adjacent to the Williamsburg Bridge, North Brooklyn Farms is a tranquil pop-up park with fairy lights, seating and a colorful greenhouse. The perfect foreground for your Brooklyn Bridge shot.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/rooftop-pool-5b4fac8bdc2e4-optimized-860x600.jpg\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo:&nbsp;<em>The Williamsburg Hotel</em></p>\r\n<h3>5. The Williamsburg Hotel</h3>\r\n<p>The rooftop at The Williamsburg Hotel has some of the best views of the Manhattan skyline (which you can enjoy while sipping on a cocktail and topping up your tan).</p>\r\n<h3>6. Smorgasburg</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Located in the East River State Park, local food market&nbsp;Smorgaburg pops up every weekend with more than 100 vendors specializing in a variety of cuisines. Grab a snap of your food with the East River in the background for the perfect post.</span></p>\r\n<h3>7. The Bagel Store Original Rainbow Bagel</h3>\r\n<p>Stop by the Bagel Store at 754 Metropolitan Ave to try &ldquo;the bagel that broke the internet&rdquo;. The bagels here are multi-colored, trippy and extremely Instagrammable.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_9.jpg\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Danielle P., Yelp</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>8. Domino Park</h3>\r\n<p>Nearby the Brooklyn bridge, this man-made park has everything a photographer could ask for: River-side views of the Manhattan skyline and the statue of liberty, perfectly fake grass, a dog park and even bocce ball for people-watching. Along with neighboring Grand Ferry Park, this is the place for your Instagram pictures.</p>\r\n<h3>9. &ldquo;Spread Love It&rsquo;s the Brooklyn Way&rdquo; Mural</h3>\r\n<p>This colorful mural on N 8th St. and Bedford Ave makes a great Instagram addition, as well as sending positive vibes out to your feed.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/unnamed-8-1.jpg\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: OurBKSocial</p>\r\n<h3>10. Brooklyn Brewery</h3>\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re a beer fan, make sure you get the Brooklyn Brewery in your photo gallery. Both the outside and inside of this building are covered with artistic murals and logos just waiting to be captured.</p>\r\n<h3>11. McCarren Park</h3>\r\n<p>McCarren Park is a Williamsburg gem, particularly for photographers. We love the Dog Run for cute pooch pics.</p>\r\n<h3>12. Rough Trade Record Store</h3>\r\n<p>This record store is photogenic from any angle. Snap the poster-covered walls or the lines and lines of records that fill this warehouse-style space.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-6), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/rough-trade-nyc-f3aaec92e91da79f77941d14ab2ab5b68be1c0345c804b1b46b1dcfeb2920373.jpg\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-6)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo:&nbsp;<em>Rough Trade</em></p>\r\n<h3>13. East River State Park</h3>\r\n<p>East River State Park is the perfect base for pictures of the Manhattan skyline. It&rsquo;s known for its exceptional sunsets, so hang around just that little bit longer.</p>\r\n<h3>14. Feng Sway</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A mix between a vintage store and a nursery, this beautiful shop is lined with clothing and plants from top to bottom and has been named the best vintage store in the world by </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">W Magazine</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. All this makes it one of the best places to snap an Instagram picture.</span></p>\r\n<h3><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-7), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1f92b36e2865f2b0afa79fc612294e27d8cb7dda_nyc-feng_sway-042118-selasi_tawia.jpg\" alt=\"The 15 Best Instagram Spots in Williamsburg (Image-7)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: So Far Sounds</p>\r\n<h3>15. The Lot</h3>\r\n<p>This non-profit radio station hosts live DJ sets, tucked away on a lot off of Nassau Avenue. The events are low key and have been described as hanging out in a friend&rsquo;s backyard, making it the perfect place to get that classic Williamsburg picture.</p>\r\n<p>Photographers can add stunning new images to their portfolios. But keep in mind that your home can also be attractive, not just buildings and graffiti. You can <a href=\"../new-york\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">rent apartments</a> in Williamsburg with the aid of Outpost Club in addition to shooting on camera.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '1f92b36e2865f2b0afa79fc612294e27d8cb7dda_nyc-feng_sway-042118-selasi_tawia.jpg', 1, '2019-07-17 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:23:21', NULL, 0, 0),
(290, 'Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park', 1, 'getting-lost-for-a-day-in-golden-gate-park', '', 'Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park', 'Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park', 'Golden Gate Park is a favorite San Francisco oasis, with more than 1,000 acres of greenery, including landscaped gardens, lakes, picnic groves and plenty of winding trails just waiting to be explored. It’s the perfect place to wander around on your day off, and what better way is there than to throw out the map and let yourself get lost?', '<p>Golden Gate Park is a favorite San Francisco oasis, with more than 1,000 acres of greenery, including landscaped gardens, lakes, picnic groves and plenty of winding trails just waiting to be explored. It&rsquo;s the perfect place to wander around on your day off, and what better way is there than to throw out the map and let yourself get lost?</p>', '<p>Golden Gate Park is a favorite San Francisco oasis, with more than 1,000 acres of greenery, including landscaped gardens, lakes, picnic groves and plenty of winding trails just waiting to be explored. It&rsquo;s the perfect place to wander around on your day off, and what better way is there than to throw out the map and let yourself get lost?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_15.jpg\" alt=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Linh C., Yelp</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The entire park was created out of sand dunes by park engineer William Hammond Hall and gardener John McLaren in the 1870s, and now receives more than 13 million visitors each year. Located on the west side of San Francisco, bordering beautiful Ocean Beach, it&rsquo;s the ideal place to relax.</p>\r\n<p>Start on the east side of the park near historic McLaren Lodge and work your way westward through this expansive park, preferably with a good book in hand. You&rsquo;ll be struck almost instantly by the Conservatory of Flowers, an imposing Victorian building made mostly of glass. Walk along the flowerbeds and palm trees of Conservatory Valley to get a closer look: This beautiful building, opened in 1879, is the oldest building in Golden Gate Park. Step inside and explore the 1,700 species of aquatic and tropical plants this expansive green house holds, including orchids, giant water lillies and carnivorous plants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_16.jpg\" alt=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>David G. Yelp</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Conservatory regularly holds special exhibits, so you may be lucky enough to stumble upon a limited-edition horticultural display. You&rsquo;ll also probably see one of the many geckos that are used instead of harmful pesticides to keep pests away. During the summer months (this year through Oct. 21), the Conservatory is illuminated from 9 p.m. to 11:30 p.m., transforming this landmark into a colorful artefact with spinning flower images, animated butterflies and more. And if you&rsquo;re still hungry for plantlife after this, try the adjacent Arizona Garden and Dahlia Garden or the Botanic Garden, with collections of rhododendrons, camellias, magnolias, succulents and more.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Next, walk onwards to the Music Concourse, a landscaped basin between the </span><strong>California Academy of Sciences </strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">and the </span><strong>de Young Museum</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This green space hosts free concerts on Sundays during the summer and there are always picnickers and bookworms sitting in the sunshine and shade alike. At the center of the Music Concourse is the beautiful Rideout Fountain. Built in 1924, this fountain will soothe your soul &mdash; plus, the ring of benches around it is perfect for people-watching.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_17.jpg\" alt=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo:&nbsp;<em>Golden Gate Park</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The next stop is the Japanese Tea Garden, one of our favorite places in the park. With free admission on Monday, Wednesday and Friday mornings, this garden is your ticket to relaxation. It&rsquo;s actually the oldest Japanese tea garden in the United States and was originally created for the 1894 California Midwinter International Exposition as the fair&rsquo;s Japanese Village exhibit. The entire garden is landscaped in the Japanese style, with winding paths running through its 3.5 acres of carefully chosen plants, which include Japanese maples, twisting pines, clipped azaleas and flowering cherry trees. Walk past koi ponds, stone lanterns, wooden gates and more. We love the hundred-year-old five-story pagoda and the high-arching Drum Bridge, which reflects in the pond below. The teahouse is the best place to take a break from your walk, with a wide selection of teas and other hot drinks to keep you hydrated.</p>\r\n<p>Stroll past the loungers spread out on the grass of the Great Meadow and enjoy the sight of egrets and ducks in the waterfowl pond as you make your way through to Stow Lake, the park&rsquo;s largest body of water. This lake, opened in 1893, was designed for leisure boating, and you can still rent a pedal boat from the boathouse. Take a small hike up Strawberry Hill Island, the highest point in Golden Gate Park at more than 400 feet, which is situated in the middle of the lake, to get the best view. Follow the trail at the lake&rsquo;s perimeter and you&rsquo;ll reach Huntington Falls, a 110-foot artificial waterfall that cascades from a reservoir higher up on Strawberry Hill.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o_18.jpg\" alt=\"Getting lost for a day in Golden Gate Park (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Golden Gate Park</em></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Continue through the National AIDS Memorial Grove, a reflective space filled with rhododendrons and redwoods, and peep in on the buffalo at the Bison Paddock to really feel a sense of getting back to nature. The Herschell-Spillman Carousel is an ideal place to experience the thrill of childhood again, originally built in 1914 and colorfully painted with scenes of farmyard animals and the Bay Area. This indoor, historic carousel costs just $2 for adults to ride and is certainly a blast from the past.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Finish your wander at the Park Chalet restaurant, a cafe and restaurant beside the beach with panoramic views of the Pacific Ocean. All we can say after that is well done; you&rsquo;ve earned that ice cream (or beer!).</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'o_2.jpg', 1, '2019-07-25 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(291, 'Member Monday: Nayra Brandão', 1, 'member-monday-nayra-brando', '', 'Member Monday: Nayra Brandão', 'Member Monday: Nayra Brandão', 'Meet Nayra, a digital nomad from Brasil who loves discovering new places, people and things.', '<p>Meet Nayra, a digital nomad from Brasil who loves discovering new places, people and things.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Meet Nayra, a digital nomad from Brasil who loves discovering new places, people and things.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Member Monday: Nayra Brand&atilde;o (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/o1.jpg\" alt=\"Member Monday: Nayra Brand&atilde;o (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h1>Tell us a bit about yourself</h1>\r\n<p>I am Nayra Brand&atilde;o, originally from Manaus, Brazil, a city in the state of Amazonas. I\'m a lawyer addicted to travel, wine, photography and human connections. In 2018 I left the stability of a career in a renowned public company to&nbsp;follow my purpose: to travel the world, facing the challenges of being a digital nomad. Since then, I\'ve been encouraging&nbsp;more women to live this transformative experience and&nbsp;to travel alone. As part of this new time in my life, I\'ve come to New York to improve my English and participate in cultural and professional activities.</p>\r\n<h1>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</h1>\r\n<p>Outpost gave me a new vision of co-living, opening my mind to this way of living, and it is a great honor to be part of team of such an exciting company. Since it\'s all about people in the end, the main memory I have of Outpost is all the people I\'ve met and I\'m still getting to know here, who shared their stories with me at super-exciting parties or in team meetings.</p>\r\n<h1>What&rsquo;s your favorite part of New York?</h1>\r\n<p>At this moment, Brooklyn has my heart completely.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>What are you working on now? </strong></h1>\r\n<p>I dedicate my time here between being a House Leader for Outpost, studying and improving my English, working as a nomad lawyer and enjoying my time in New York as much as I can, sharing my nre experiences and tips in my Instagram (@nayrabf).</p>', 'o1.jpg', 1, '2019-07-29 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0);
