(313, '7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC', 1, '7-quiet-places-hidden-in-nyc', '', '7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC | Outpost Club blog', '7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC', 'New York is known for being busy, bustling and fast-paced. Although this is exactly what makes us love the big apple, sometimes you need a break. That’s why we’ve put together a list of our favorite oases where you can escape the noise for some well-earned quiet time.', '<p>New York is known for being busy, bustling and fast-paced. Although this is exactly what makes us love the big apple, sometimes you need a break. That&rsquo;s why we&rsquo;ve put together a list of our favorite oases where you can escape the noise for some well-earned quiet time.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">New York is known for being busy, bustling and fast-paced. Although this is exactly what makes us love the big apple, sometimes you need a break. That&rsquo;s why we&rsquo;ve put together a list of our favorite oases where you can escape the noise for some well-earned quiet time.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><a href=\"https://www.fordfoundation.org/about/the-ford-foundation-center-for-social-justice/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">1. The Ford Foundation</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_14.jpg\" alt=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://www.fordfoundation.org/ideas/equals-change-blog/posts/transforming-a-landmark-into-a-center-for-social-justice/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ford Foundation</a></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Ford Foundation Center for Social Justice is a hub for social good with an office in East Midtown. What&rsquo;s special is the atrium: a leaf-filled garden in the middle of Manhattan which is completely open to the public. Walk through the trees, sit by the central fountain and take in the rainforest-inspired surroundings for the perfect break from the bustling streets around.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><a href=\"http://thebattery.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">2. Battery Park</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the south tip&nbsp;of Manhattan below Wall Street, Battery Park is a peaceful stretch of greenery where you can walk, run or sit in the grass and almost forget you&rsquo;re in the city. Enjoy views of the Statue of Liberty and New Jersey as you bask in the silence. We recommend walking along the boardwalk up to Rockefeller Park and past the Irish Hunger Memorial for the fullest&nbsp;sense of retreat.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_8.jpg\" alt=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/TheMetCloisters/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Met Cloisters, Facebook</a></em></span></p>\r\n<h1><a href=\"https://www.metmuseum.org/visit/plan-your-visit/met-cloisters\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">3. The Met Cloisters</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Part of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, this lesser-known branch showcases medieval art in a remote French monastery. The museum includes tranquil gardens as well as access to picturesque Hudson River views, surrounded by gardens and the beautiful Fort Tyron Park. It&rsquo;s so quiet you can hear a pin drop, making it hard to believe you&rsquo;re still in New York City, just north of Harlem.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><a href=\"https://parks.ny.gov/parks/155/details.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">4.&nbsp;East River State Park</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">East River State Park is our favorite tucked-away spot in Brooklyn. Located in Williamsburg, the Park borders the coast of the East River. You can even walk down to the river while taking in the city views, making it the perfect place to catch the sunset. Walk along the riverside to Domino Park, where you&rsquo;ll find landscaped gardens, fountains and public games, such as bocce ball.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_13.jpg\" alt=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://parks.ny.gov/parks/155/details.aspx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">New York Parks</a></em></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"https://govisland.com/about\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">5. Governor\'s Island</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Governor&rsquo;s Island is a quiet little island just a 7-minute ferry ride from Wall Street. The entire island is car-free, making it a tranquil spot perfect for strolling around on a weekend afternoon. Explore the multiple green spots, including Hammock Grove (with plenty of hammocks for lounging in) and historic Castle Williams.</p>\r\n<h1><strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_14.jpg\" alt=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em><a href=\"https://govisland.com/about\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Governor\'s Island</a></em></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/riverside-park\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">6.&nbsp;Riverside Park</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Riverside Park is a favorite among New Yorkers as an oasis of peace and quiet. Located near Columbia University, this park follows the river and is a hot spot for students, runners and dog walkers. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The steps down to the park means that it feels like entering a whole other world completely separate from city life.</span></p>\r\n<h1><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pages/West-111th-Street-Peoples-Garden/123299484383971\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">7. West 111th Street People&rsquo;s Garden</a></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_9.jpg\" alt=\"7 quiet places (hidden) in NYC (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/meteorry/21833873708\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Perry Tak, Flickr</a></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This little-known park is the perfect place to relax away from the buzzing Manhattan streets. Step into a miniature world of brass statues of the most weird and wonderful designs with a tranquil fountain at the center. At the back of the park you&rsquo;ll find The Cathedral School of St. John the Divine, whose gardens you can explore for free (and if you&rsquo;re lucky, even catch sight of their famous peacocks!)</span></p>\r\n<p>Parks, woodlands, and islands are excellent locations for peaceful recreation. But keep in mind that your home or room may be the quietest area. The Outpost Club is directly responsible for locating a suitable peaceful area. All you have to do is <a href=\"../new-york\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">rent a room</a>, and we\'ll take care of selecting the ideal location.</p>', '2_2.jpg', 1, '2019-10-22 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:19:08', NULL, 0, 0),
(316, 'Destination: 3-19 Coffee', 1, 'destination-3-19-coffee', '', 'Destination: 3-19 Coffee', 'Destination: 3-19 Coffee', 'Located at 3359 26th St on the edge of the Mission District, 3-19 Coffee is a coffee shop with a difference. Or, to be more accurate, a coffee shop that’s making a difference. \r\n', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Located at </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3359 26th St on the edge of the Mission District, 3-19 Coffee is a coffee shop with a difference. Or, to be more accurate, a coffee shop that&rsquo;s </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">making </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">a difference.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Located at </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">3359 26th St on the edge of the Mission District of San Francisco, <a href=\"http://319coffee.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">3-19 Coffee</a> is a coffee shop with a difference. Or, to be more accurate, a coffee shop that&rsquo;s </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">making </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">a difference.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: 3-19 Coffee (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_19.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: 3-19 Coffee (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em><a href=\"http://319coffee.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">3-19 Coffee</a></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dedicated to changing the world through the fusion of art, coffee and consumer responsibility, 3-19 Coffee grew out of a community-based project in Honduras. The co-founders travelled to Santa Elena where they sponsored art activities and got to know the community and local farmers through communal events. It&rsquo;s these same people who 3-19 now source their coffee from. 3-19 ensures that the communities they buy their coffee from always benefit economically, socially and environmentally, even setting aside a portion of their profits for social projects in the communities where they work. This means that every cup of coffee you get at 3-19 comes with a conscience.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: 3-19 Coffee (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_12.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: 3-19 Coffee (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo: <em><a href=\"http://319coffee.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">3-19 Coffee</a></em></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">And the benefits of a 3-19 coffee don&rsquo;t stop there. They also partner with local San Fancisco artists to bring you uniquely designed canisters, showcasing their work and connecting artists with coffee enthusiasts. They&rsquo;re committed to getting to know and helping the artists they work with in every way possible, meeting them in person and even producing a promotional video to help increase their reach. So 3-19 coffee is good for both Honduran and SF communities at the same time.</span></p>\r\n<p><br />The SF location of 3-19 is also a great place to hang out. With a full espresso and coffee menu starting at just $3 a cup, it\'s not a bad deal for an ethical cup-full. The vibe is relaxed with wooden tables, exposed brick walls and plenty of natural light coming through the large windows and the staff are always happy to have a chat. It\'s the perfect&nbsp;place to grab a cappuccino before work or sit with your laptop, all the while knowing you\'re making a difference to communities both at home and away.</p>', '2_3.jpg', 1, '2019-10-28 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(318, 'Member Monday: Dani Healy', 1, 'member-monday-dani-healy', '', 'Member Monday: Dani Healy', 'Member Monday: Dani Healy', 'This week for Member Monday, Dani Healy, traveler and systems consultant, tells us her favorite things about Outpost.\r\n\r\n', '<p>This week for Member Monday, Dani Healy, traveler and systems consultant, tells us her favorite things about Outpost.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>This week for <strong>#MemberMonday</strong>, Dani Healy, traveler and systems consultant, tells us her favorite things about Outpost.</p>\r\n<p><img title=\"Member Monday: Dani Healy (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/IMG_4938.JPG\" alt=\"Member Monday: Dani Healy (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h1>Tell us a bit about yourself.</h1>\r\n<p>Hey, I\'m Dani. I\'ve been at Outpost a bit over two months now and it has been one of the greatest living experiences I have ever had. I\'m in NYC to work as a systems consultant for technology companies, however, I travel so often for work I didn\'t want to commit to a long term lease, which is why I originally chose Outpost. Little did I know upon arriving that I would be meeting some of the greatest friends I have ever made.</p>\r\n<h1>What\'s your favorite Outpost memory?</h1>\r\n<p>Outpost is way more than a coliving space, it\'s a place where no matter what happens, you <em>always&nbsp;</em>have someone you can talk to. Whether it be someone that will be there to hold your hand when you\'re scared, someone to laugh with around a bonfire and some to call your best friends. I have so many great memories with all of my friends here and I truly can\'t choose just one. But just knowing that I have bonded so closely with so many people here in so many different ways is probably the most valuable thing that Outpost has provided for me in my short time here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>What\'s your favorite part of New York?</h1>\r\n<p>My favorite part of NYC is walking through the city really late at nighttime. It\'s so peaceful.</p>\r\n<h1>What are you working on now?</h1>\r\n<p>Currently, I am still working as a systems consultant with various projects around the country.</p>', 'IMG_4938.JPG', 1, '2019-11-04 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(319, 'Living with roommates as an introvert', 1, 'living-with-roommates-as-an-introvert', '', 'Living with roommates as an introvert | Outpost Club blog', 'Living with roommates as an introvert', 'Introverts come in many shapes and forms but at the bedrock of any introvert is one point: social interactions drain you more than extroverts. You may love or hate interacting with people, but no matter what you need alone-time in between to recharge.', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Introverts come in many shapes and forms but at the bedrock of any introvert is one point: social interactions drain you more than extroverts. You may love or hate interacting with people, but no matter what you need alone-time in between to recharge.</span></p>\r\n<p>So when it comes to apartment-hunting, your first thought might be a studio apartment, but these are often expensive and you might not actually want to live on your own because of safety or social reasons (yes, paradoxically, introverts get lonely too!). If you&rsquo;ve decided to live in a shared space, here are some tips to make day-to-day life run smoothly.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Introverts come in many shapes and forms but at the bedrock of any introvert is one point: social interactions drain you more than extroverts. You may love or hate interacting with people, but no matter what you need alone-time in between to recharge.</span></p>\r\n<p>So when it comes to apartment-hunting, your first thought might be a studio apartment, but these are often expensive and you might not actually want to live on your own because of safety or social reasons (yes, paradoxically, introverts get lonely too!). If you&rsquo;ve decided to live in a shared space, here are some tips to make day-to-day life run smoothly.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Be upfront and honest with your roommates</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The risk of living with roommates as an introvert is that they might think you&rsquo;re being rude by not wanting to hang out with them all the time, so dodge this bullet by explaining to them that you&rsquo;re an introvert. You can be as detailed as you like, saying that you like to hang out occasionally but need some time to yourself, or if you don&rsquo;t feel comfortable going into it, just explain that you have a stressful job/ school work and you&rsquo;re sorry if you don&rsquo;t have time to hang out as much as they might want to. As long as you explain it politely, they\'ll understand.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Living with roommates as an introvert (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_17.jpg\" alt=\"Living with roommates as an introvert (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Find you own sense of privacy</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are a few tricks to getting alone-time in a shared apartment. If you have your own room, it&rsquo;s not too much of an issue. Simply part ways with your roommates with a smile (and if they ask, you can say you&rsquo;ve got a Netflix show to binge). In shared rooms this may seem harder, but little things like wearing headphones (you don&rsquo;t even need to be listening to music) send a polite signal that you&rsquo;re not available to talk. You can even have a discussion with your roommates and ask if it&rsquo;s alright not to talk in the bedroom itself. If you have a bunk bed, try&nbsp;draping a throw over the railings to&nbsp;give yourself instant privacy without seeming rude.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Time your recharging time wisely</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Timing can be important when finding your chance to recharge in a shared living space. Get to know your roommates&rsquo; schedules and work your me-time around it, whether that means getting up earlier than your roommates or staying up later, or making sure you fit your cooking time into the time slot when nobody is home. If you live in an Outpost house, remember your space is not just the apartment itself. Explore the TV room, backyard or rooftop at different times of day, as these spaces are often free on certain days like weekdays.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Living with roommates as an introvert (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_18.jpg\" alt=\"Living with roommates as an introvert (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Be friendly when you do see your roommates</strong></h1>\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re roommates aren&rsquo;t going to see you very often, you might as well try to make the times they do see you pleasant. Tiny things like smiling on your way to the shower can make a big difference to&nbsp;maintaining roommate harmony when you might not want to hang out with them every day. You can also show friendliness through other, non-social acts. If you have time, making coffee for your roommates in the morning or baking cookies for everyone on your day off sends a welcoming signal&nbsp;without having to engage in social interactions (and everyone loves a little hand-written note when it&rsquo;s not passive aggressive).</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Find a sacred space</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Finding a space outside the home can be a great way to recharge. This space can act as an oasis when you&rsquo;re overwhelmed by people, allowing you uninterrupted me-time. Whether it&rsquo;s a local coffee-shop, park or even a mall you like to wander around, there&rsquo;s always somewhere quiet to be found in the throng of a city. Take a stroll around your neighborhood or Google \"quiet spaces\" in the area for inspiration.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Living with roommates as an introvert (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_11.jpg\" alt=\"Living with roommates as an introvert (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Jump into socializing occasionally</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you can, it&rsquo;s better to socialize with your roommates occasionally. For one thing, once you know people hanging out with them will drain you slightly less as you\'ll be more comfortable. It&rsquo;s also good to get outside of your comfort zone every now and again. This might mean setting a weekly \"date night\" for a group dinner or a movie or, if you live at Outpost, going along to one of our regular social events. Just remember that going along to an event or even hanging out in your apartment doesn&rsquo;t stop you leaving early and&nbsp;you&rsquo;ll still be proud of yourself for giving it a go.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The benefits of <a href=\"../coliving\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">coliving</a> are universal, but selecting a roommate carefully is important. The main source of human emotions and perceptions is spending time with lovely people. As a result, everything is directly dependent on you, and the Outpost Club will take care of your housing.</p>', '1_7.jpg', 1, '2019-11-04 06:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:17:47', NULL, 0, 0),
(320, 'The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month', 1, 'the-best-free-sf-exhibitions-to-catch-this-month', '', 'The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month', 'The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month', 'It feels good to get a bit of culture! And it feel even better when it\'s free. Here are our favorite SF exhibitions going on this month (which you can enjoy without the price tag) and where to find them.', '<p>It feels good to get a bit of culture! And it feel even better when it\'s free. Here are our favorite SF exhibitions going on this month (which you can enjoy without the price tag) and where to find them.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It feels good to get a bit of culture! And it feel even better when it\'s free. Here are our favorite SF exhibitions going on this month (which you can enjoy without the price tag) and where to find them.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_20.jpg\" alt=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo:&nbsp;<em>Kari Orvik,&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">San Francisco Camerawork</span></em></span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>\"Geneva\"&nbsp;at San Francisco Camerawork</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Under the radar </span><strong>San Francisco Camerawork</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is one of San Francisco&rsquo;s hidden art gems. Founded in 1974, this gallery showcases new and emerging photographers from SF and the surrounding areas.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What: Through December 20, you can check out the free exhibition </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Geneva, </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&nbsp;a photographic series by San Francisco photographer Kari Orvik focusing on the SF Outer Mission neighborhood at the corner of Mission Street and Geneva Avenue. The exhibition features the people and architectural sites of the area looked at through new eyes on materials including metal, glass and digital portraits and landscapes.</span></p>\r\n<p>Where: <em>1011 Market Street, Mid-Market, San Francisco, 94103</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_21.jpg\" alt=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo:&nbsp;<em>Kari Orvik,</em>&nbsp;<em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">San Francisco Camerawork</span></em></p>\r\n<h2><strong>\"5 Artisti\" at Museo Italo Americano</strong></h2>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The </span><strong>Museo Italo Americano</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> was the first U.S. institution dedicated to Italian art and culture when it first opened its doors in 1978 and it&rsquo;s gone from strength to strength since then. The intimate collection includes both contemporary and historical Italian and Italian-American art and the latest exhibit doesn&rsquo;t disappoint.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What: \"5 Artisti\" </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">showcases the work of 5 Italian and Italian-American artists working in a range of different mediums. Running through February 2 2020, you can catch &ldquo;Mind Maps&rdquo; by Sofia Carmi, which explores fantasy and mind travel through abstract and expressionist painting, the stunning photographs of Art De Fabio&rsquo;s &ldquo;Faces and Places of Umbia&rdquo; (a beautiful little region referred often to as the &ldquo;Green Heart&rdquo; of Italy) and the architectural, geometric designs of Robert La Rocca in his &ldquo;Beyond the Edge.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Where: <em>2 Marina Boulevard, Marina District, San Francisco, 94123</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><em><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_22.jpg\" alt=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></em></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo:<em>&nbsp;Art De Fabio,&nbsp;<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Museo Italo Americano</span></em></span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Chinese Historical Society of America Museum</strong></h1>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://chsa.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Chinese Historical Society of America Museum</a></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> was also the first of its kind, being the first museum in the country to highlight the contributions of the Chinese in the U.S when it opened in 1963.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What: The </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">new permanent exhibition, &ldquo;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Chinese American: Exclusion/Inclusion,&rdquo; is a must-see for anyone interested in the history of Chinese in America, as it traces the history of Chinese immigration to the states and the lives of Chinese-Americans as they changed from the late eighteenth century to now, including exlusion laws and discrimination and well as inspiring stories and little known facts.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_17.jpg\" alt=\"The best free SF exhibitions to catch this month (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Chinese Historical Society of America</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Where:</span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> 965 Clay Street, San Francisco, </span></em><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">94108</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '1_8.jpg', 1, '2019-11-06 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(321, 'Destination: Poets House, NYC', 1, 'destination-poets-house-nyc', '', 'Destination: Poets House, NYC', 'Destination: Poets House, NYC', 'Poets House is one of those rare New York City places which most people haven\'t heard of and consequently is blissfully quiet, open and serene.', '<p>Poets House is one of those rare New York City places which most people haven\'t heard of and consequently is blissfully quiet, open and serene.</p>', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><a href=\"https://poetshouse.org/about-poets-house-library/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Poets House</a> is one of those rare New York City places which most people haven\'t heard of and consequently is blissfully quiet, open and serene.&nbsp;Part library, part literary centre and part free space to hang out and get some zen time, Poets House should be the next place on your list of hidden NYC spots.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Poets House, NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_23.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Poets House, NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://poetshouse.org/about-poets-house-library/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Poets House</a></em></p>\r\n<p>Located bedise Rockefeller Park near the Financial District, Poets House is a free space open to the public. Wander in through the park surroundings and climb the winding wooden staircase to find a serene space filled with books, comfy chairs and more. If you\'re looking for a place to write or work, this is it. The chairs and desks almost all have outlets next to them and you can login to the free WiFi quickly and easily without an account. What\'s more, the park and riverside location of Poets House means you can enjoy direct views of the Hudson River while you type or doodle away, which looks all the more amazing through&nbsp;the large, airy windows.</p>\r\n<p>And if it\'s books you need, there are plenty. With over 70,000 books in their collection, Poets House lives up to its name as a national poetry library. You can even reserve quiet reading rooms to make sure you give that attempt at the new Great American Novel your undivided attention. Plus, there\'s always an art exhibit happening in the adjoining&nbsp;Cheney Chappell Exhibition Space to inspire you, which is currently showing a fascinating collection called \"Gay New York: Walt Whitman to the Present.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Poets House, NYC (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_18.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Poets House, NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://poetshouse.org/about-poets-house-library/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Poets House</a></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Aside from the space itself, you can catch workshops, classes and talks at Poets House nearly every week, including writing master classes, book fairs and live readings by leading authors. You can check out the calendar of upcoming events on their website <a href=\"https://poetshouse.org/programs-events/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p>So if you\'re looking for a space to work, read, relax and maybe get some new ideas flowing, you\'ve found it.</p>', '1_9.jpg', 1, '2019-11-08 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(323, 'Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates', 1, 'why-everyone-in-their-20s-should-try-living-with-roommates', '', 'Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates | Outpost Club blog', 'Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates', 'Everyone likes their own space (some more than others), but living with roommates can be an incredible experience. Especially when you\'re in your 20s, roommates can help you figure out both life and yourself, getting to grips with a city as you laugh your way through the good and the bad times as a team.', '<p>Everyone likes their own space (some more than others), but living with roommates can be an incredible experience. Especially when you\'re in your 20s, roommates can help you figure out both life and yourself, getting to grips with a city as you laugh your way through the good and the bad times as a team.</p>', '<p>Everyone likes their own space (some more than others), but living with roommates can be an incredible experience. Especially when you\'re in your 20s, roommates can help you figure out both life and yourself, getting to grips with a city as you laugh your way through the good and the bad times as a team.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_18.jpg\" alt=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<h3>1. They help you get your arms around a&nbsp;new city</h3>\r\n<p>If you\'re <a href=\"../nyc-rooms-for-rent\" target=\"_blank\">new to a city</a>, roommates are the answer to several of those newbie problems. First, they help you tick off the problem of not knowing anyone. Reach out to your roommates and smile and you\'ll probably find the favor returned to you. If they\'ve lived in the city for a while, they can be a good source of insider knowledge from everything from how to order a local ID to which grocery store is the cheapest, or if they\'re new like you you can spend time exploring the city together and making new memories.</p>\r\n<h3><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_16.jpg\" alt=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />2. They can save you money</h3>\r\n<p>Most people know it\'s cheaper to live with roommates. High rents in cities means it\'s much more affordable to share spaces, and in co-living apartments like Outpost you can both save money and have more overall space by living with roomates, thanks to the communal backyards, rooftops and common rooms many of our houses offer. What you might not think about is how all the little things you share with roommates can add up to save you money: cooking potluck dinners, sharing a pizza on movie night and sharing other goods like blenders and tupperware can all add up. In a traditional living environment, you\'ll also share on bills, toilet paper and other add-ons by splitting the costs, but thankfully at Outpost that\'s all included in our flat fee.</p>\r\n<h3>3. They can broaden your horizons</h3>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_17.jpg\" alt=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Moving in with roommates (especially strangers) is essentially throwing yourself into a new, alien situation. That might sound scary but it\'s great for personal growth. By living with people you\'ll get to meet both them and their friends, opening yourself up to things and ideas that you may not have come across otherwise. If your roommate is a professional rock climber you might become an expert on rock climbing. Or if you\'re lucky enough to live with a film or television young professional, you might end up at a premier. Anything could happen when you decide to live with new people.</p>\r\n<h3>4. They teach you to be considerate</h3>\r\n<p>When you live on your own, you\'re the only one you have to take care of, but really life in the broader sense includes a good deal of&nbsp;consideration and sharing. Living with roommates can teach you consideration&nbsp;because you know that other people share&nbsp;the space at the same time as you. That means you shouldn\'t leave your dishes for days on end or leave the bathroom or the backyard in a mess. You also don\'t bring friends home at late hours of night or talk outside someone else\'s door because, well, you\'re a nice person, and it\'s better that way.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>5. They\'re a shoulder to cry on</h3>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/christie-kim-yxXk-sAn1BM-unsplash.jpg\" alt=\"Why everyone in their 20s should try living with roommates (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Moving to a new city is tough. Starting a new job is tough. Actually, most things you\'ll do in your twenties will be tough, but also equally amazing and character building. Roommates mean there will always be someone to come home to to laugh or cry about your day. You can share the highs and the lows with them and hopefully come out with some life-long friends&nbsp;who can handle your worst and still deserve you at your best.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The beginning of a career growth process can be challenging and uncertain. You will face this problem on your own since you don\'t have anyone to turn to for assistance. Every young person must go through the stage of <a href=\"../coliving\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">coliving</a>, and the Outpost Club\'s job is to make sure your future apartment has the greatest possible conditions.</p>', '2_4.jpg', 1, '2019-11-08 06:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:44:51', NULL, 0, 0),
(324, 'The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco', 1, 'the-5-best-vegan-cafes-in-san-francisco', '', 'The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco', 'The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco', 'Sometimes being vegan can mean having to do a little more research into where to get the best food. We\'ve made things easier by finding the 5 best vegan cafes in SF we think any plant-based eater will adore.', '<p>Sometimes being vegan can mean having to do a little more research into where to get the best food. We\'ve made things easier by finding the 5 best&nbsp;vegan cafes in SF we think any plant-based eater will adore.</p>', '<p>Sometimes being vegan can mean having to do a little more research into where to get the best food. We\'ve made things easier by finding the 5 best&nbsp;vegan cafes in SF we think any plant-based eater will adore.</p>\r\n<h1>1. Next Level Burger</h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_24.jpg\" alt=\"The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo:&nbsp;<em>Fatcow.com</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Next Level is a vegan&rsquo;s answer to Chick Fil A, only better for the planet and almost certainly healthier. Serving up fast (vegan) food in a calm, bright environment, it&rsquo;s the perfect place to grab a quick lunch or a hangover treat. With decadent options like burgers, crinkle fries and thick vegan shakes, as well as healthier choices like salads and grilled sandwiches, it&rsquo;s up to you how indulgent&nbsp;you want to be. We love the crispy chicken burger (vegan of course), which has a patty more convincingly meaty than McDonalds&rsquo;.</span></p>\r\n<h1>2. Nourish Cafe</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nourish Cafe lives up to its name: everything here is about health and vitality (both your own and the planet&rsquo;s), serving up the best vegan food with a conscience. They pride themselves on only using organic, plant-based ingredients, which are all totally GMO free. The menu includes brunch favorites like avocado toast and quinoa waffles with hazelnut spread, as well as every day treats like the banh mi sandwich and the ever-popular Nourish bowl. The space is bright with large windows and plenty of white and pine wood, but with only 6 tables total it&rsquo;s better to go at off-peak times to guarantee a place to sit.</span></p>\r\n<h1><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_25.jpg\" alt=\"The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Nourish Cafe</em></p>\r\n<h1>3. Beloved Cafe</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beloved Cafe is a vegan and vegetarian juice and tea bar with plenty of planet-friendly food to munch on and a bohemian, laid-back vibe. They even make their own chai from scratch every morning, with ginger, lemongrass, cinnamon, black tea and whole milk, and they&rsquo;re smoothie selection is almost endless. Choose from healthy ingredients including ashwaganda, maca, spirulina and more, blended with fruit, veggies and their signature homemade almond milk for the perfect vegan treat.</span></p>\r\n<h1>4. Greens&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Greens is one of our favorite vegan restaurants in the city partly because of its amazing view: this vegetarian and vegan haven sits on a gorgeous location overlooking the San Francisco Bay and the Golden Gate Bridge. Proudly at the forefront of the farm to table movement for over 35 years, this hidden gem serves both healthy and wholesome food for breakfast, lunch and dinner. We love the black bean chili and the spring thai red curry, both made from the freshest ingredients from a Zen farm in Marin, and they&rsquo;re happy to make any vegetarian dish on the menu vegan if you ask with a smile.</span></p>\r\n<h1><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_15.jpg\" alt=\"The 5 best vegan cafes in San Francisco (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Greens</em></p>\r\n<h1>5. Shizen Vegan Sushi Bar</h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We love this small but mighty sushi bar for the best sushi in SF, minus the fish. Shizen\'s creative menu is so much more than avocado rolls, with a range of options to suit any taste. And it&rsquo;s not all about sushi either, with a selection of vegan ramen and gyoza available too. The only problem is because of the small size it gets booked fast&nbsp;so make reservations online and be prepared to wait (but it&rsquo;s worth it!).</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '1_10.jpg', 1, '2019-11-16 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(326, 'Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink', 1, 'destination-safeway-holiday-ice-rink', '', 'Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink', 'Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink', 'There’s nothing like ice skating to get you into the holiday spirit. This year, we’re heading to the Union Square ice rink, the most visited ice rink in SF.', '<p>There&rsquo;s nothing like ice skating to get you into the holiday spirit. This year, we&rsquo;re heading to the Union Square ice rink, the best ice rink in SF.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There&rsquo;s nothing like ice skating to get you into the holiday spirit. This year, we&rsquo;re heading to the Union Square ice rink, the best&nbsp;ice rink in SF.</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_20.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo: <em>SFMTA</em></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">This beautiful rink in the middle of Union Square is a San Francisco institution, overlooked by the twinkling lights of the city&rsquo;s best Christmas tree. From November 6 until January 20 2020, the ice rink will pop up for skating sessions each day between 10am and 11:30 pm.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_19.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Union Square Ice Rink</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bring your date, your bestie or your parents to skate in this unique setting. Tickets start at just $15.26 and lockers are available on site for $3 each, allowing you thirty minutes to skate and take pictures in the twinkling lights. There are even special events taking place on the ice; catch the 30th Annual </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Macy&rsquo;s Tree Lighting Celebration</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on Friday, November 29 at 6pm, or why not watch</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Drag Queens on Ice</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> take the stage to amaze the crowd on December 5 at 8pm. There&rsquo;s even a </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">silent disco</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on December 12 at 6pm for those who want to start the (early) weekend off feeling cool.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_19.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Safeway holiday ice rink (Image-3)\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo: <em>SF Recreation &amp; Parks</em></span></p>\r\n<p>Location:</p>\r\n<p><em>333 Post Street</em><br /><em>San Francisco, CA</em></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '1_11.jpg', 1, '2019-11-18 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0);
