(359, 'Great online courses you can try for free', 1, 'great-online-courses-you-can-try-for-free', '', 'Great online courses you can try for free', 'Great online courses you can try for free', 'There are so many online courses available at the moment, it\'s hard to know where to begin. That\'s why we\'ve picked out our favorite picks for this week, all of which are available to start for free and online now.\r\n', '<p>There are so many online courses available at the moment, it\'s hard to know where to begin. That\'s why we\'ve picked out our favorite picks for this week, all of which are available to start for free and online now.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>There are so many online courses available at the moment, it\'s hard to know where to begin. That\'s why we\'ve picked out our favorite picks for this week, all of which are available to start for free and online now.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>1. CitiesX: The Past, Present and Future of Urban Life</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://www.edx.org/course/citiesx-the-past-present-and-future-of-urban-life\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">This course</a> is a great introduction to a social sciences study on cities--where you may live but never think about as a social, historical organ. For the first time ever, more than 50% of people worldwide live in urban areas. This course will give you an insight into the past, present and future of cities, focusing on cities around the world, including New York City, Rio de Janeiro, Mumbai, London and many more.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You&rsquo;ll learn about the growth of cities such as Rome, Sao Paulo and Seattle, while looking forward to the future by gaining a deeper understanding and appreciation of urban spaces. This includes an introduction to pressing social and urban planning issues such as public health, transportation, gentrification and more, using interviews and insights from academics, policy makers, urban leaders and city residents to examine not just what cities are and have been but what the future might look like for urban life in the next century. Taught by Harvard&rsquo;s Professor of Economics, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Edward Glaeser, this course runs online over 11 weeks for 5-7 hours a week and can be completed at your own pace.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. The Science of Happiness</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now more than ever is a great time to learn how to understand and cultivate happiness. This </span><a href=\"https://www.edx.org/course/the-science-of-happiness-3\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">free course</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from the University of California Berkeley is the perfect place to start. What&rsquo;s different about this course is its focus on the science behind the emotion. This course explores the roots of a happy and meaningful life, exploring how cutting-edge research on emotions can be applied to our own lives. The course focuses on a fundamental finding from positive psychology: that happiness is linked to having strong social connections and contributing to the greater good of the world (no matter how narrowly or broadly we define this). </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Spanning the fields of </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">psychology, neuroscience, evolutionary biology, and more, this course will help you tap into and nurture your own happiness through classes and interviews with world-renowned experts, including&nbsp; Barbara Fredrickson, Paul Ekman, Sonja Lyubomirsky, and Jon Kabat-Zinn. This 8 week course takes just 4-5 hours a week of studying--while the benefits could be not only helpful but long lasting.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1>3. What is &ldquo;the mind&rdquo; and what is artificial intelligence?</h1>\r\n<p><br /><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This </span><a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/learn/mind-machine-artificial-intelligence#instructors\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">course</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> offered by UC-Boulder examines the ways in which our current understanding of human thinking can be illuminated and challenged by modern artificial intelligence and computer science. You&rsquo;ll learn our idea of what &ldquo;the mind&rdquo; actually is has shifted over the past half-century,&nbsp; with insights from cognitive psychology, machine learning, neuroscience, evolutionary psychology, and game theory and where this has left us in terms of current research directions and controversies. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pitched at a beginner&rsquo;s level and taking just 11 hours total to complete, this course will introduce students to the Turing test, the history and current situation of attempts to create artificial systems that can pass this test, as well as the details of Searle&rsquo;s Chinese Room thought experiment, among others. It will define and debate the boundaries of intelligence and the line between human and machine and how different understandings of thinking itself can lead to different definitions of problems.</span></p>\r\n<h1>4. Lessons from Ebola: Preventing the Next Pandemic</h1>\r\n<p>As you probably know, the lessons of history are key to understanding and improving the present. This <a href=\"https://www.edx.org/course/lessons-from-ebola-preventing-the-next-pandemic\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">free course </a>on the history of the Ebola pandemic--what went wrong, how the virus spread and what could have been done differently--will give a unique insight into the current pandemic. The 2014 Ebola outbreak highlighted the fragility of global health systems in many of the same ways as the current situation and can be seen as an opportunity to learn lessons from the past. This course lays out the global governance structure and features experts, academics and health practitioners in online classes arranged over four weeks, which takes just 3-5 hours of studying a week.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2_14.jpg', 1, '2020-04-16 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(340, 'How to live clutter-free in a shared room', 1, 'how-to-live-clutter-free-in-a-shared-room', '', 'How to live clutter-free in a shared room', 'How to live clutter-free in a shared room', 'Living in a shared room might seem like a recipe for clutter, but with forward planning you can maximize the space you have and stay organized.', '<p>Living in a shared room might seem like a recipe for clutter, but with forward planning you can maximize the space you have and stay organized.</p>', '<p>Living in a shared room might seem like a recipe for clutter, but with forward planning you can maximize the space you have and stay organized.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Discuss storage places with your roommate(s)</strong>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How to live clutter-free in a shared room (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_24.jpg\" alt=\"How to live clutter-free in a shared room (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In a shared room, it&rsquo;s always better to communicate. When you first move in, simple discuss with your roommate(s) where you will all keep your things. So long as you portion out the room and storage units fairly, this will avoid arguments in the future and make sure that you all have clearly defined boundaries from the start.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Use space smartly</strong></h1>\r\n<p><strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How to live clutter-free in a shared room (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_25.jpg\" alt=\"How to live clutter-free in a shared room (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s easy to stay clutter-free if you&rsquo;re clever about the way you use space. Firstly, make sure that you&rsquo;ve used all available storage space such as closets, as hanging is the perfect way to see multiple items of clothing at once. You can also utilise the space under your bed by using storage boxes.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s best to store your suitcases under your bed, but suitcases can be more than just empty space. They can also be a place to store off-season clothes or other items you don&rsquo;t use very often, freeing up space in your room for other, less cluttered items.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Don&rsquo;t bring or buy anything you don&rsquo;t really need</strong></h1>\r\n<p><strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How to live clutter-free in a shared room (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_37.jpg\" alt=\"How to live clutter-free in a shared room (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before you arrive, you can minimize clutter by not bringing anything that&rsquo;s not truly necessary. If you&rsquo;re only staying in your shared room for a short amount of time, leave knick knacks and appliances at home. At co-living spaces such as Outpost, everything is included, so only clothes and toiletries are needed.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Once you&rsquo;ve moved in, simple resist the urge to shop too much. Many co-livers create a rule where they get rid of one old item for every new item bought, which means you won&rsquo;t end up accumulating a load of clutter. You can also mail items home or donate unwanted clothes or books to charity once you&rsquo;re no longer using them.</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '3_7.jpg', 1, '2019-12-31 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(341, 'How coliving is combatting urban loneliness', 1, 'how-coliving-is-combatting-urban-lonelineness', '', 'How coliving is combatting urban lonelineness', 'How coliving is combatting urban lonelineness', 'With a population of over 8 million people, you might think it’s easy to meet people in New York. But unfortunately, it’s not that simple. ', '<p>With a population of over 8 million people, you might think it&rsquo;s easy to meet people in New York. But unfortunately, it&rsquo;s not that simple.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>With a population of over 8 million people, you might think it&rsquo;s easy to meet people in <a href=\"../nyc-rooms-for-rent\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">New York</a>. But unfortunately, it&rsquo;s not that simple.&nbsp;Urban isolation and loneliness is a growing issue in the United States. According to a 2018 survey, more than two in ten adults in the US (22%) say they always or often feel lonely, lack companionship, or feel left out or isolated, and a recent Cigna survey revealed over half of Americans (54%) said they always or sometimes feel that no one knows them well. That&rsquo;s pretty sad.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_39.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>What&rsquo;s more, former US Surgeon General <strong>Dr. Vivek Murthy</strong> says that loneliness can lead to increased risks of a whole host of mental and physical diseases and is as damaging as smoking fifteen cigarettes a day. So although you might not find yourself wanting to rent a cat or a cuddle to cheer yourself up on those long winter nights (which is the new trend in Tokyo&rsquo;s <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/apr/07/loneliest-city-in-world\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">&lsquo;</a>affection industries<a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/apr/07/loneliest-city-in-world\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">&rsquo;</a>), you might be struck by the loneliness of your move to the next new city.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_50.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>So, where is this problem coming from? Urban loneliness has most often been linked to living alone. And Manhattan has one of the highest percentages of people living alone in the world, with two-thirds&shy; of people living by themselves (the national average in 1920 used to be 5%). The hard part&nbsp;is that if you live on your own, most people in big cities&nbsp;already have a group of friends which can be impossible&nbsp;to break into. The majority of New Yorkers seem to have pre-existing high school, college or work friends who they see and interact with almost exclusively. Sure, it would be great if you can find other people who are new to the city, but where do you find them? And wouldn\'t you benefit from the knowhow of people who have lived there longer?</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/press-release-downtown-brooklyn-house-2.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-3)\" />You can meet someone at an event or a bar and hit it off but then never hear from them again because in a big city, there&rsquo;s no accountability. We all know how easy it is to avoid someone with 8 million other people floating around. Roommates seem like the answer, but more and more often you&rsquo;ll find descriptions on apartment sharing websites that say the roommates \"keep to themselves\" or are \"always out\" and are looking for other people to live with who won&rsquo;t \"disturb\" them.</p>\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s the beautiful thing about coliving. At Outpost, we&rsquo;re upfront about our aim to build a community in our houses, and although members don&rsquo;t have to take part in anything if they don&rsquo;t feel like it, you know from the start that you&rsquo;re going to be living with other people who want to make new friends just like you.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/4th%20July-26.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Our range of events, communal spaces and co-working areas are all designed to tackle loneliness and get meaningful conversations flowing. Sociologist Eric Klinenberg <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/mar/30/the-rise-of-solo-living\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">wrote in 2012</a> that, &ldquo;research shows that it&rsquo;s the quality, not the quantity of social interactions that best predicts loneliness.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/Pride7.png\" alt=\"How coliving is combatting urban loneliness (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>So if you&rsquo;re barely home, busy or introverted, it doesn&rsquo;t mean you have to be lonely. Whether you hang out in one of our communal areas, cook a potluck dinner with your roommates in the kitchen or simply catch your roommate before you both go to sleep, the opportunity to get talking in coliving is always there if you want it. With coliving there&rsquo;s always someone to come home to, have a beer or a pizza with, and moan about your day.</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '2_10.jpg', 1, '2020-02-21 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(342, 'Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio', 1, 'destination-mr-tipples-recording-studio', '', 'Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio', 'Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio', 'Mr Tipple’s is our favorite place to kick back after a hard day’s work and escape the tourist traps to enjoy some simple, soulful music.', '<p>Mr Tipple&rsquo;s is our favorite place to kick back after a hard day&rsquo;s work and escape the tourist traps to enjoy some simple, soulful music. Serving up live jazz every single night of the week, it&rsquo;s ideal for your Sunday hair-of-the-dog as much as for your Friday night excitement.&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Mr Tipple&rsquo;s is our favorite place to kick back after a hard day&rsquo;s work and escape the tourist traps to enjoy some simple, soulful music. Serving up live jazz every single night of the week, it&rsquo;s ideal for your Sunday hair-of-the-dog as much as for your Friday-night excitement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_49.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Leslie C., Yelp</em></p>\r\n<p>This dark, moody bar is conveniently situated at 39 Fell Street between Van Ness and Polk. Set up as part bar, part recording studio by a mysterious British entrepreneur, this easy going hang out is always cover free and always buzzing.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_48.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio</em>, Yelp</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The music ranges from Miles to Coltrain to Django to Monk. This month, you can look forward to a range of Bop Jazz, soul, blues and Sunday Singer Sessions as well as a visiting jazz trio from Paris. And the food and drink isn&rsquo;t bad either! Take your seat at one of the small tables surrounding the intimate stage and order from an extensive menu of cocktails (all $13) or beer (starting at $6).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Our favorites are the &ldquo;Broken Record&rdquo;, made with reposado, campari, lemon and grapefruit and &ldquo;The House Jazz Built&rdquo;, a wonderful concoction of their house sazerac on draft rye, peychaud&rsquo;s, absinthe and lemon (and every time you buy this drink, $1 goes to help rebuild the SoundRoom in Oakland). Plus, there&rsquo;s a concise but on the mark food menu, which includes the legendary Mr T&rsquo;s Chicken &amp; Waffles (with bourbon maple, of course) priced at $16.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_38.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Mr Tipple\'s Recording Studio</em></p>\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s a $20 minimum spend for table service, but we think it&rsquo;s more than reasonable to enjoy some of SF&rsquo;s finest musicians in a cool, classy setting. It&rsquo;s the perfect place for date night, a catch up with friends or a solo evening of exploring the amazing live music scene that San Francisco has to offer.</p>', '2_9.jpg', 1, '2020-01-09 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(343, 'How coliving helps you build a home away from home', 1, 'how-coliving-helps-you-build-a-home-away-from-home', '', 'How coliving helps you build a home away from home', 'How coliving helps you build a home away from home', 'We talk a lot about the benefits of coliving for people who are new to a city. It’s the perfect way to meet new people, try new things and build a home away from home', '<p>We talk a lot about the benefits of coliving for people who are new to a city. It&rsquo;s the perfect way to meet new people, try new things and build a home away from home. But how exactly does coliving help you build this sense of home? What is it about coliving that&rsquo;s more homely than a regular apartment? Well, here are some&nbsp;of the facts behind&nbsp;our&nbsp;figurings...</p>', '<p>We talk a lot about the benefits of coliving for people who are new to a city. It&rsquo;s the perfect way to meet new people, try new things and build a home away from home. But how exactly does coliving help you build this sense of home? What is it about coliving that&rsquo;s more homely than a regular apartment? Well, here are some&nbsp;of the facts behind&nbsp;our&nbsp;figurings...</p>\r\n<h1><strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_44.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Meeting like-minded people makes you feel at home</strong></h1>\r\n<p>When you first come to a new city it can be difficult to adjust. When you&rsquo;re trying to get used to Metro cards, sidewalk etiquette and salty New Yorkers screaming at you for no apparent reason (you&rsquo;ll get used to it pretty quickly), the idea of home might feel literally miles away. But something as simple as being able to talk about your favorite TV shows with a roommate can instantly bring you back to earth with a dose of familiarity. Outpost is the perfect place for this, as our coliving model attracts like-minded people: people who want to explore, share with others and meet new people. And the free Netflix in our living rooms definitely helps start conversations too!</p>\r\n<h1><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_45.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Not being the only expat can combat homesickness</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Studies</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> have shown that interacting with other expatriates from both your own and from other countries is extremely productive in maintaining psychological balance when moving abroad, leading to &lsquo;success and healing&rsquo; in the new environment. Outpost is nothing if not a melting pot of cultures, nationalities and ideas, which allows newbies the opportunity to feel that their culture is still valued as one of many others when they&rsquo;re trying to get used to the new culture of&nbsp;their&nbsp;new home.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Feeling looked after keeps moving anxiety at bay</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_46.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One of the great things about Outpost is that you never feel like you&rsquo;re on your own when there&rsquo;s a problem. We have a robust community working to make your experience as great as possible, including our Community Manager and House Leaders who are easy to reach when you need them. You won&rsquo;t need to call the plumber or the electricity guy. You won&rsquo;t need to unclog your toilet. And if you need extra coffee or toilet paper, a friendly face will bring it round to your door.&nbsp;How great is that?</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Interior design that reminds you&nbsp;of home</strong></h1>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/12.jpg\" alt=\"How coliving helps you build a home away from home (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outpost apartments are designed with you in mind. There&rsquo;s a whole field of interior design related to how spaces make us feel and we&rsquo;re always innovating to find new ways to make you feel safe and at home in our coliving spaces. We always use welcoming colors with neutral, calming tones in our apartments. For instance, have you noticed how much yellow there is in Outpost houses? Color theory tells us that yellow is a calming color, as almost every culture associates yellow with sunshine, happiness and warmth. Yellow is also the most visible color of the spectrum and the first color which the human eye processes on sight. Yellow has a high light reflectance value, making it a secondary light source in any room which can combat the NYC winter blues and make you feel like you&rsquo;re back home if you&rsquo;re from the sunshine (or on vacation if you&rsquo;re not!).</span><br /><br /></p>', '1_15.jpg', 1, '2020-01-22 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(344, '3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter', 1, '3-brooklyn-museums-you-should-visit-this-winter', '', '3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter', '3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter', 'When you\'re new to NYC, you might want to head straight to the famous museums of Manhattan', '<p>When you\'re new to NYC, you might want to head straight to the famous museums of Manhattan. But Brooklyn is filled with&nbsp;a rich history that\'s worth exploring too. This borough is often overlooked by tourists, but it doesn\'t have to be that way. Here are our top 3 Brooklyn museums to visit this winter.</p>', '<p>When you\'re new to NYC, you might want to head straight to the famous museums of Manhattan. But Brooklyn is filled with&nbsp;a rich history that\'s worth exploring too. This borough is often overlooked by tourists, but it doesn\'t have to be that way. Here are our top 3 Brooklyn museums to visit this winter.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>1. Old Stone House of Brooklyn</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_52.jpg\" alt=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Old Stone House</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The </span><strong>Old Stone House</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is one of Brooklyn&rsquo;s hidden treasures. Built in 1699, this architectural relic first graced Brooklyn&rsquo;s streets in the Dutch colonial era. Since then, it&rsquo;s been the site of the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">the largest battle of the American Revolutionary War and the clubhouse of the Brooklyn Dodgers baseball team. Step into a piece of history in this small, tucked away museum in Park Slope, with its historically accurate interior and exterior. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_51.jpg\" alt=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo: <em>Old Stone House</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There&rsquo;s a permanent exhibit on the history of the house and the Battle of Brooklyn as well as a changing temporary exhibit. They&rsquo;re currently taking submissions for an upcoming art exhibit entitled &ldquo;Brooklyn Utopias: 2020&rdquo; which will showcase different artistic visions of the ideal Brooklyn of the present. The house also runs a variety of talks and activities to inspire community</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">336 3rd Street, Brooklyn, NY 11215</span></em></p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. Brooklyn Historical Society</strong></h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.brooklynhistory.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Brooklyn Historical Society</a>, founded in 1863, is a museum, library, and educational center preserving and encouraging the study of Brooklyn\'s 400-year history. With locations at Pierrepont Street in Brooklyn Heights and DUMBO, what we love most about this museum is its ever-changing program of events designed to educate and entertain.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_26.jpg\" alt=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Brooklyn Historical Society</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Head over to one of their workshops on your home neighborhood and undercover the hidden history of your block (and even your house) or enjoy a wide range of talks on everything from the city&rsquo;s architecture to civil rights.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_40.jpg\" alt=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Brooklyn Historical Society</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">They also have a range of exhibitions.&nbsp;Right now, you can see &ldquo;Waterfront&rdquo;, an interactive and multimedia experience on the history and future of Brooklyn&rsquo;s coastline, told from the perspectives of workers, artists, activists and families.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">128 Pierrepont Street Brooklyn, NY 11201; 55 Water Street Brooklyn, NY 11201</span></em></p>\r\n<h1><strong>3. Museum of Food and Drink (MOFAD) Lab</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_53.jpg\" alt=\"3 Brooklyn museums you should visit this winter (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></strong>Photo: <em>Museum of Food and Drink Lab</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>MOFAD</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is an exciting, interactive museum in the heart of Brooklyn. This educational non-profit and museum aims to change the way&nbsp;people think about food and drink, emphasizing its strong links to culture, politics, history and more. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">5,000-square-foot experimental space in Williamsburg is always unexpected and interesting with a program of temporary exhibitions. Right now, they&rsquo;re exhibiting </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Chow, </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">which celebrates the birth and history of Chinese American restaurants, featuring chef-designed tastings at the KitchenAid Culinary Studio and collection of historical menus.</span></p>\r\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">62 Bayard Street, Brooklyn, NY 11222.</span></em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '1_16.jpg', 1, '2020-02-20 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(345, 'Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen', 1, 'destination-katzs-delicatessen', '', 'Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen', 'Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen', 'If you’ve ever heard the phrase, “I’ll have what she’s having,” then you need to go to Katz’s Deli. In fact, if you’ve ever wanted to try a classic, meaty New York style sandwich, you need to go to Katz’s deli', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;ve ever heard the phrase, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll have what she&rsquo;s having,&rdquo; then you need to go to </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Katz&rsquo;s Deli</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. In fact, if you&rsquo;ve ever wanted to try a classic, meaty New York style sandwich, you need to go to Katz&rsquo;s deli. The iconic diner from </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Harry Met Sally </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">has since become New York&rsquo;s favorite place for a sandwich (which is really saying something) and it categorically does not disappoint.</span></p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you&rsquo;ve ever heard the phrase, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll have what she&rsquo;s having,&rdquo; then you need to go to </span><strong>Katz&rsquo;s Deli</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. In fact, if you&rsquo;ve ever wanted to try a classic, meaty New York style sandwich, you need to go to Katz&rsquo;s deli. The iconic diner from </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Harry Met Sally </span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">has since become New York&rsquo;s favorite place for a sandwich (which is really saying something) and it categorically does not disappoint.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_63.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />This popular diner first opened in 1888. In 1989 it rose to fame as the setting for the most (in)famous scene in </span><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Harry Met Sally</span></em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, but it&rsquo;s not just a tourist hub. The diner is widely considered to be one of the last traditional Jewish delis in Manhattan, serving the most delicious pastrami on rye sandwich we&rsquo;ve ever had in our lives (strike that, the best sandwich, period). Enter the glass doors to a retro dining hall with walls decked with celebrity photographs and memorabilia. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Simply pick up your ticket and line up behind one of the many cutting counters, where you can tell your cutter exactly what you want from the menu like in an old fashioned deli, including whether you want to eat in or take your sandwich to the city streets (we recommend taking it to nearby Tompkins Square Park, as it gets a bit crowded inside. Take a few snaps of the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\"Where Harry met Sally... hope you have what she had! Enjoy!\" sign and head out, if you ask us. The sandwich itself is what you&rsquo;re there for: the best pastrami or corned beef sandwich in New York (and it&rsquo;s not just us saying this, it&rsquo;s also been voted by </span><strong>Zagat</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">).</span></p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_64.jpg\" alt=\"Destination: Katz\'s Delicatessen (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /><br /><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How do they do it? Their corned beef and pastrami is cured using a slower method, which best flavors the meat, without injecting chemicals or any other additives into it. In fact, it takes up to 30 days to cure their meat, whereas commercially prepared products are often chemically altered to be cured in just 36 hours. Good things take time and love, and Katz understands that. At $22.95 a sandwich, they might be expensive but they&rsquo;re worth it (also, these sandwiches are truly huge and cut in half, so why not split one with a friend?) They&rsquo;ve even opened a pop-up stand at </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dekalb Market Hall in Brooklyn, although for us there&rsquo;s no beating the original (and still the best) on the site of Meg Ryan&rsquo;s acting high.</span></p>', '1_20.jpg', 1, '2020-01-23 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(346, '5 Winter Walks to try in NYC', 1, '5-winter-walks-to-try-in-nyc', '', '5 Winter Walks to try in NYC', '5 Winter Walks to try in NYC', 'Winter might seem like it’s all doom and gloom, but most winter days in NYC are actually bright and clear, which means that if you wrap up warmly there’s no reason why you can’t go out for that relaxing Sunday walk you’ve been dreaming about since summer. In fact, some parts of the city are even nicer to walk around in the winter. Here are our top 5 winter walks in NYC to get you moving.\r\n\r\n ', '<p>Winter might seem like it&rsquo;s all doom and gloom, but most winter days in NYC are actually bright and clear, which means that if you wrap up warmly there&rsquo;s no reason why you can&rsquo;t go out for that relaxing Sunday walk you&rsquo;ve been dreaming about since summer. In fact, some parts of the city are even nicer to walk around in the winter. Here are our top 5 winter walks in NYC to get you moving.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Winter might seem like it&rsquo;s all doom and gloom, but most winter days in NYC are actually bright and clear, which means that if you wrap up warmly there&rsquo;s no reason why you can&rsquo;t go out for that relaxing Sunday walk you&rsquo;ve been dreaming about since summer. In fact, some parts of the city are even nicer to walk around in the winter. Here are our top 5 winter walks in NYC to get you moving.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>1.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Riverside Park</strong></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img title=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_54.jpg\" alt=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />&nbsp;Photo: <em><a href=\"https://co.pinterest.com/pin/404479610256911733/?amp_client_id=CLIENT_ID(_)&amp;mweb_unauth_id=&amp;simplified=true\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Lucille Burns, Pinterest</a></em></p>\r\n<p>Riverside Park is a favorite with Columbia students, being located just a few blocks from the university&rsquo;s main campus. Cross the road and away from the buzzing Harlem streets and walk down the steps to a Mecca of green in the middle of the city. Because of its lowered ground level, Riverside Park is an instant breath of fresh air in its quiet serenity. The hill also acts as a wind blocker, so it barely feels like winter when you weave your way between the paths and the trees. As the name aptly suggests, Riverside Park is located along the side of the Hudson River, following the path of the river vertically down the side of Manhattan, which makes for the perfect winter river walk. The throngs of college students playing games on the grass and joggers running up and down the stretch of park gives this space a friendly, community feel which makes it one of our favorite winter walks in the city.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. The Little Red Lighthouse</strong></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_41.jpg\" alt=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/ataferner/19585444958\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Axel Taferner, Flickr&nbsp;</a></em></p>\r\n<p>Take a trip up to Fort Washington Park&nbsp;to see NYC&rsquo;s famed Little Red Lighthouse, the only lighthouse in New York City. Despite its acclaim, this little treasure is always blissfully tourist-free because it&rsquo;s actually pretty hard to get to. It&rsquo;s certainly worth the journey, though, as the lighthouse is a piece of history, built in 1921&nbsp;and it comes with amazing city views down the Hudson&nbsp;River. There&rsquo;s also plenty to see in the area around the lighthouse, so you can bring a picnic and make a day of it. Take a train to 190th Street or Dyckman Street&nbsp;and walk around Fort Tyron Park, a city park built around and through ancient walls and bridges. You can even pop in on the Met Cloisters just around the corner, a beautiful ancient monetary which has been restored into a museum as one of the branches of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The lighthouse is just a short underpass and walk away, so you can take in the not-so-city air and enjoy the sparkling riverside views while getting some culture (and warming up) on the same trip.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>3. East River State Park and Domino Park</strong></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_43.jpg\" alt=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em><a href=\"https://archpaper.com/2017/04/domino-sugar-factory-site-public-waterfront/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Archpaper</a></em></p>\r\n<p>Located at the beginning of Brooklyn, by the Williamsburg Bridge&nbsp;and the East River is a peaceful walk along East River State Park and Domino Park. The views of Manhattan from this side of the river are truly special and if you go at sunset you&rsquo;ll catch the reddest skies with a blissful shortage of other people around, making this the perfect afternoon walk to brighten up your winter. East River State Park has its own beach where you can walk up to the river water and pose for pictures on the (stable) rocks at the water&rsquo;s edge. It&rsquo;s a great place to sit and contemplate life, as it feels as though there&rsquo;s nothing but nature between you and the skyline. After soaking up the sandy air, you can walk south along Domino Park, a waterside promenade with unbeatable views. There are always people jogging and playing in this under the radar park, as features like public fountains, a dog park and bocce ball make it a communal, weekend-focused space.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>4. John V. Lindsay East River Park</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<img title=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_44.jpg\" alt=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em><a href=\"https://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/east-river-park\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">NYC Gov Parks</a></em></p>\r\n<p>We love this unsung park for a winter walk because you can just keep walking to your heart&rsquo;s desire. Beginning at the Williamsburg Bridge, this Manhattan waterside promenade allows you to walk north up the eastern side of Manhattan island for as long as your legs can take you. Our favorite part of this walk is the stretch beginning at the Williamsburg Bridge, because the paved walkway looks directly onto the river and there&rsquo;s barely anyone else around (except for a few joggers). Enjoy sprawling gardens and even a children&rsquo;s play area as you take in the feeling of being far outside of the city whilst still being just a few blocks from the bustling streets.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>5. Battery Park</strong></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_55.jpg\" alt=\"5 Winter Walks to try in NYC (Image-5)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><a href=\"https://www.nycgo.com/boroughs-neighborhoods/manhattan/battery-park-city\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">NYC Go&nbsp;</a></em></p>\r\n<p>Battery Park is hidden at the base of Manhattan island, between the offices of Wall Street and the hustle bustle of the city. Somehow, though, it&rsquo;s one of the most peaceful places in Manhattan, and one of our favorites for a chilly winter stroll. The park has amply green space as well as a riverside promenade where you can take in the sights of New Jersey and, amazingly, catch clear sight of the Statue of Liberty, which at night lights up to give the park a magical feel. There are park benches dotted along the path with enclaves for fountains and other monuments, as well as several cafes and the famous Brookfield Place mall, the perfect place to shelter for a hot chocolate, meal or shopping trip after your walk.</p>', '1_17.jpg', 1, '2020-01-25 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0);
