(347, 'Our top 5 things to do in SF this February', 1, 'our-top-5-things-to-do-in-sf-this-february', '', 'Our top 5 things to do in SF this February', 'Our top 5 things to do in SF this February', 'Just because it\'s chilly outside, doesn\'t mean February has to be boring! There are still plenty of activities going on in the Bay Area, from the cultural to the food-focused', '<p>Just because it\'s chilly outside, doesn\'t mean February has&nbsp;to be boring! There are still plenty of activities going on in the Bay Area, from the cultural to the food-focused. Here are our top 5 things to do this February in San Francisco.</p>', '<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Just because it\'s chilly outside, doesn\'t mean February has&nbsp;to be boring! There are still plenty of activities going on in the Bay Area, from the cultural to the food-focused. Here are our top 5 things to do this February in San Francisco.</p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Southwest Airlines Chinese New Year Parade 2020</strong><br /><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_56.jpg\" alt=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Do the Bay</em></p>\r\n<p>Sponsored by Southwest Airlines and held in the center of historic Chinatown, the SF<strong> Chinese New Year Parade</strong> is one of the best in the country, if not the world. It&rsquo;s one of the few remaining night illuminated parades in North America and the biggest parade for the occasion outside of Asia, dating all the way back to the 1860s. Over 100 floats, dancers and other units are taking part in this giant celebration of Chinese culture and the crowds are expected to be in the hundreds of thousands.</p>\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ll even get to see the newly crowned Miss Chinatown U.S.A take her pride of place and the spectacular 288&rsquo; Golden Dragon (carried by a team of 180 people). The parade, celebrating the incoming year of the rat, starts around 5pm on Saturday, February 8, stepping off at Second and Market Streets and finishing at 9pm. And the best part is, it&rsquo;s totally free to watch; although you can upgrade to bleacher seats, you can secure yourself a view by arriving early (and holding your camera above your head).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>San Francisco Independent Film Festival</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_47.jpg\" alt=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>SF Indie Fest</em></p>\r\n<p>Still going strong after 18 years, the <strong><a href=\"https://sfindie.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">San Francisco Independent Film Festival</a></strong> (SF IndieFest) is an annual festival showcasing the best in independent and alternative cinema from around the world. With a full line up of films on show, including full length, documentaries and much more, alongside parties and awards, it&rsquo;s the perfect introduction to the world of independent film. The festival is on from now until February 13, with comedies like \"39&frac12;&rdquo;, about a Mission District female filmmaker, and shorts like \"Alexa\", about a guy who enlists Amazon&rsquo;s Alexa in his dating life, topping our favorites list.</p>\r\n<h2>SF Beer Week&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<p>Taking place over 10 beer-packed days this February, SF Beer Week is the Bay Area&rsquo;s annual celebration of our brewing heritage and craft beer culture. Find hundreds of events hosted by breweries, venues and more and learn all about (and taste) the best craft beer that SF has.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_48.jpg\" alt=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />There will be beer tastings, community talks and educational beer classes as well as food pairings. Expect rare, cask, barrel-aged, experimental, new releases, seasonals and more. Many events are &ldquo;pay as you go,&rdquo; meaning free to attend and you only pay for any beer and/or food you order. Events like &ldquo;Wellness Saturday&rdquo; on February 8, which combines a bike ride with pop-up food, beer and bicycle repair services, are the perfect way to learn more about not just beer but SF as a whole.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Ezra Klein: Why We\'re Polarized by The Commonwealth Club</h2>\r\n<p>Offering a new perspective on modern American politics, <strong>&ldquo;Why We&rsquo;re Polarised&rdquo;</strong> is set to be an insightful talk by Editor-at-Large and Co-Founder of <em>Vox</em>, Ezra Klein. Klein will discuss his new book, which sets to analyse why American politics polarized around identity in the 20th century and what that polarization did to the way we see the world and each other. In Conversation with <strong>Anna Sale</strong>, host of WNYC\'s \"Death, Sex &amp; Money\", Klein will examine the gridlock of modern politics, adding a new perspective for a modern age. Doors open at 5:30pm with the talk beginning at 6:30pm on February 6.</p>\r\n<h2>Dumpling Down &ndash; Lunar New Year Food Festival</h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_49.jpg\" alt=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /><br />Photo: SoMa StrEat Food Park</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Last but not least, why not celebrate Chinese New Year with some good old-fashioned street food? We love SoMa StrEat Food Park, which is why we&rsquo;re more than excited about their February event, <strong>Dumpling Down</strong>, which will be serving up the best dumplings in town to the accompaniment of music, drinks and good vibes. Local vendors from all over the Bay Area will be serving dim sum, bottomless kumquat mimosas, and Chinese-themed beers at the biggest Lunar New Year food festival in San Francisco. And of course, there will be live entertainment on both Saturday 8 and Sunday 9 to really get your weekend going.</p>', '2_11.jpg', 1, '2020-02-05 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(348, 'How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC', 1, 'how-to-celebrate-chinese-new-year-in-nyc', '', 'How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC', 'How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC', 'NYC has one of the largest and diverse Chinese populations im America', '<p>NYC has one of the largest and diverse&nbsp;Chinese populations im America. Whether you want to catch&nbsp;the annual parade, explore Chinese history or sample some traditional cuisine, there\'s something going on in the city to fit the bill.</p>', '<p>NYC has one of the largest and diverse&nbsp;Chinese populations im America. Whether you want to catch&nbsp;the annual parade, explore Chinese history or sample some traditional cuisine, there\'s something going on in the city to fit the bill.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>See the parade</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_52.jpg\" alt=\"How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo: <em>Youtube</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">New York is famous for its Chinese New Year parade, and for good reason! Head down to Chinatown to catch amazing visuals, food stalls and cultural performances running through the afternoon for the <strong>21st Chinatown Lunar New Year Parade and Festival</strong>. The parade will begin at 1pm at Mott Street and Canal Street, moving on to Chatham Square to East Broadway towards the Manhattan Bridge and completing on Eldridge and Forsyth Streets towards Grand Street next to Sara D. Roosevelt Park. It&rsquo;s free to watch, just remember to get there early if you want a good space.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Try some puppet making</strong></h1>\r\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_58.jpg\" alt=\"How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"700\" height=\"490\" /></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Vecteezy</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Why not try some shadow puppetry at a workshop? Chinese shadow theater is over 2000 years old, consisting traditionally of carved and colored figures manipulated behind a cloth screen to tell stories of history, folk law and much more. Chinese Theatre Works, a non-profit cultural organization aiming to preserve and promote traditional Chinese performance, will teach you the background of this art form and even lead you in designing and building your own shadow figures! The </span><strong>Shadow Theater Workshops</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> take place on February 16 and 23</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Make traditional dumplings</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Have you ever wanted to make traditional Chinese dumplings? Well, here&rsquo;s your chance to learn. Essex Market vendor </span><strong>Eat Gai</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> will be conducting a hands-on dumpling making workshop to celebrate the new year, focusing on chicken-and-chive dumplings. Chef Mukda and co-owner Pei will explain why we eat dumplings and chicken during Chinese New Year while you make your own version of the dish and get to taste it, too.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Learn about history at The Golden Spike</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/3_27.jpg\" alt=\"How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Golden Spike, Eventbrite</span></em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This friday, catch </span><strong>The Golden Spike</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, an extraordinary play telling the epic love story of </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sun Wu and Jiao Zhou, spanning 13 years, from the completion of the First Transcontinental Railroad. San Yu, a Chinese railroad worker pursuing equal work rights, falls for a young Chinese laundress, combining to make a love story which is set heavily in this otherwise overlooked period of Chinese American history.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Brush up your herbology</strong>&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our top 5 things to do in SF this February (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_51.jpg\" alt=\"How to celebrate Chinese New Year in NYC (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Photo: <em>Kamwo, Eventbrite</em></p>\r\n<p>Traditional Chinese medicine is 2,000 years old and still as fascinating and powerful as ever. This workshop on February 7&nbsp; will take you into the history and science behind Chinese medicine, held in one of the country\'s most respected herbal dispensaries in Chinatown, <strong>Kamwo Meridian Herbs</strong>. Kamwo contains over 500 raw herbs, thousands of patent herbal products, and an extensive selection of acupuncture and natural wellness supplies. You can see, touch, smell and learn all about a wide variety of herbs, led by a knowledgeable staff member of Kamwo. <br /><br /></p>', '3_8.jpg', 1, '2020-02-03 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(360, '10 quarantine baking hacks', 1, '10-quarantine-baking-hacks', '', '10 quarantine baking hacks', '10 quarantine baking hacks', 'It seems like everyone is trying their hand at baking during quarantine. If you’re one of the many, many people in isolation getting doughy for the first time, you may have run into one of two problems: shortages of ingredients in your local grocery store or shortages in your ability to make your creations look the way they do in the recipe books—here are our baking hacks to fix both.', '<p>It seems like everyone is trying their hand at baking during quarantine. If you&rsquo;re one of the many, many people in isolation getting doughy for the first time, you may have run into one of two problems: shortages of ingredients in your local grocery store or shortages in your ability to make your creations look the way they do in the recipe books&mdash;here are our baking hacks to fix both.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It seems like everyone is trying their hand at baking during quarantine. If you&rsquo;re one of the many, many people in isolation getting doughy for the first time, you may have run into one of two problems: shortages of ingredients in your local grocery store or shortages in your ability to make your creations look the way they do in the recipe books&mdash;here are our baking hacks to fix both.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>1. Problem: The grocery store is out of flour</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Make your own</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Did you know that you can make your own (gluten-free!) oat flour using just oats and a blender?&nbsp; Simply blend gluten-free oats until they&rsquo;re powdered (it&rsquo;s that easy!)</p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. Problem: I don&rsquo;t have a rolling pin</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Use a wine bottle!</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You may not have a rolling pin at home, but we bet you have wine! Wine bottles are the perfect alternative to rolling pins. Just cover your dough in plastic wrap and hold either end of the bottle, rolling to your heart&rsquo;s content.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>3. Problem: The grocery store is out of buttermilk</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Make your own</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Many recipes use buttermilk for that extra flavor (especially pancakes!), but did you know you can make your own by adding 1 tablespoon of lemon juice or vinegar to every cup you use of regular milk. Let it sit for five minutes and you&rsquo;ve got buttermilk!</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>4. Problem: I can&rsquo;t mix in the butter properly</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Grate it</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It can be hard to get butter to soften and then to spread evenly throughout your mixture. For best results, grate the butter with a cheese grater to break it down into smaller chunks. This will mean the butter spreads, mixes and melts more easily.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>5. Problem: The grocery store is out of cookie dough</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Modify cake mix</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Did you know you can make cookie dough from almost any boxed cake mix? All you need to do is add &frac12; cup of oil and 2 eggs to the dry milk then simply bake as you would regular cookie dough. Craving solved!</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>6. Problem: There are air bubbles in my cookies and cakes</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Bang the mixture</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before you put your mixture in the oven, try dropping the pan of batter onto your countertop a few times. The force of the bang forces the air bubbles to the surface, meaning they won&rsquo;t get trapped in the batter and ruin the presentation of your creation. For cookies, it&rsquo;s best to do this after you take them out the oven to help them settle quicker.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>7. Problem: I don&rsquo;t have powdered sugar</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Make your own</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You can even make your own powdered sugar perfect for frosting or icing without a trip to the grocery store. Just add 1 cup of white sugar and 1 tablespoon of cornstarch and blend together until you reach a powdery texture.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>8. Problem: I dropped bits of eggshell in my batter</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Egg it out</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One of the most frustrating things is accidentally dropping a bit of eggshell in your batter. You don&rsquo;t want to stick your fingers in the mixture and it can be tricky to get it to stay in one place. Instead, use the rest of the eggshell to fish the broken pieces out. The parts will gel together, making it easier to get hold of those pesky flakes and leaving your batter crunch-free.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1><strong>9. Problem: I can\'t cut my baking treats in a solid line</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Floss them or heat things up</strong></h1>\r\n<p>It can be hard to cut the perfect slice of that cake or to get your cookie dough to divide where you want it to. We\'ve got two solutions for this. Either whip out the dental floss and use this to cut a fine line to separate your mixture without any stickiness, as dental floss cuts cleanly without leaving any residue. Or why not try simply heating up your knife under hot water for a few seconds? Simply wipe it dry and take the knife straight to your creation to create solid, professional cuts.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>10. Problem: The grocery store is out of brown sugar</strong></h1>\r\n<h1><strong>Solution: Make your own</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Because everyone is baking in quarantine you might find that your grocery store is out of brown sugar. Don&rsquo;t panic! You can make your own using white sugar and molasses (which are available in most baking aisles!). For light brown sugar, mix one cup of granulated sugar with one tablespoon of molasses. For dark brown sugar, add two tablespoons of molasses. It&rsquo;s that simple. Just mix the two ingredients together with a fork until completely mixed. Crisis averted!</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '2_15.jpg', 1, '2020-04-18 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(349, 'Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine’s Day', 1, 'unique-things-to-do-with-your-friends-on-valentines-day', '', 'Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine’s Day', 'Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine’s Day', 'Looking for something special to do with the ones you love on Valentines Day (by which we mean your friends)?', '<p>Looking for something special to do with the ones you love on Valentines Day (by which we mean your friends)? We&rsquo;ve got you covered with a selection of NYC&rsquo;s most empowering, mind-expanding events.</p>', '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Looking for something special to do with the ones you love on Valentines Day (by which we mean your friends)? We&rsquo;ve got you covered with a selection of NYC&rsquo;s most empowering, mind-expanding events.</span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Check out an art party&nbsp;</strong></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine&rsquo;s Day (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_53.jpg\" alt=\"Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine&rsquo;s Day (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: AnArtKey, Evensi&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">AnArtKey Collective is holding an exciting &ldquo;V Day Art Bash,&rdquo; an evening of art, music and live performances from 6pm to 12am on V Day itself. The gallery will be filled with incredible art to peruse, plus you can expect food, drinks, activities and much more to keep you entertained, all organized by this wonderful Queens-based artist guild. AnArtKey Collective was founded by Oriel Ceballos, an NYC artist and curator from Panama known for sensational city art events, and this is expected to be the best yet.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Indulge in a burlesque show&nbsp;</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Why not celebrate V Day with a good old fashioned feminist burlesque show? Bleecker Street\'s Le Poisson Rouge is holding their very own \"Filthy Gorgeous Burlesque Valentines Spectacular\" with live jazz music, saucy burlesque and circus performances. There will be drinks, there will be acrobatics, there will be feather boas. What\'s a better way to celebrate V day with your friends? Tickets start at $20 and you can find all the information on </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Eventbrite</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Engage in fem films&nbsp;</strong></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine&rsquo;s Day (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/2_54.jpg\" alt=\"Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine&rsquo;s Day (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: WeHeartAstoria</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Check out the </span><strong><a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/kaufman-arts-district-astoria-film-festival-galentines-day-film-event-tickets-92302163255\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Galentines Day Film Celebration</a></strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> by Astoria Film Festival for an evening of culture and feminist empowerment. On Saturday February 15 Kaufman Arts District and Astoria Film Festival will be celebrating local female and LGBTQIA+ filmmakers with screenings of short films, web series and a filmmaker panel event. All proceeds from the event go towards education and outreach activities with local public schools, so you can feel good about where your money\'s going this Valentines Day.</span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Get your brunch on</strong></h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Check out the Galentines Day event by \"Babes who Brunch\" on Sunday February 16 for a morning of makeup touchups, friendship bracelet making, drinks, snacks and much more. This event is all about celebrating friendship, providing the perfect combination of wellness, crafting, snacking and communication to really get your zen on this Valentines Day. </span></p>\r\n<h3><strong>Channel the power of the phoenix</strong></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine&rsquo;s Day (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/83898446_4043354385678429_8025253337261670400_o.jpg\" alt=\"Unique things to do with your friends on Valentine&rsquo;s Day (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: Bloc Art, Facebook</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Head to the Lower East Side to check out </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">\"The Phoenix\"</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> art show by BLOC Art. The Phoenix is known internationally as a symbol of rebirth and vitality. This exhibition will show the works of international artists interpreting the image of the Phoenix and what it means for them, exploring themes of resilience, hope and love. Fourteen artists from the US, Peru and Austria will be exhibiting, plus there will be artist talks, music and food tastings galore in celebration of the opening night. And did we mention it\'s all free? Definitely a great way to start off the night.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '1_18.jpg', 1, '2020-02-12 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(350, 'Our favourite jazz bars in NYC', 1, 'our-favourite-jazz-bars-in-nyc', '', 'Our favourite jazz bars in NYC', 'Our favourite jazz bars in NYC', 'You\'ve heard about iconic New York jazz, but how do you choose between the seemingly endless selection of jazz bars in the city to get a taste of the city\'s best cats? ', '<p>You\'ve heard about iconic New York jazz, but how do you choose between the seemingly endless selection of jazz bars in the city to get a taste of the city\'s best cats? We\'ve put together a list of our favorite jazz bars to get you inspired and toe-tapping in no time.</p>', '<p>You\'ve heard about iconic New York jazz, but how do you choose between the seemingly endless selection of jazz bars in the city to get a taste of the city\'s best cats? We\'ve put together a list of our favorite jazz bars to get you inspired and toe-tapping in no time.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Blue Note</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_59.jpg\" alt=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-1)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></strong><em>Photo: Blue Note Jazz, Facebook</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Blue note tops the list of our favorite jazz clubs in the city because it simply never disappoints. A New York institution of music since 1981, this old school jazz bar will take you back to that &ldquo;old New York&rdquo; Sarah Jessica Parker has been telling you about for so long. The decor is dark, slick and anything but try-hard and the signed pictures on the wall of numerous jazz greats tell a story all of their own. The line up is always exceptional, with jazz legends and promising newcomers all gracing the blue-lit stage every day of the week. Prices vary based on the show you choose to see, but you can splurge to sit at a table (old school style) near the front or you can get a cheaper ticket that allows you to sit at the bar. It&rsquo;s definitely worth the price, however, because this place is a real music gem.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Smalls</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_61.jpg\" alt=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-2)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" /></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Photo: Smalls</span></em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Smalls is probably one of the most famous jazz clubs in the city. Tucked away on West 10th Street, this underground cavern is always filled with the sweet rhythms of jazz and blues from some of the world&rsquo;s best musicians. It&rsquo;s the perfect place if quality is your only factor in a good night, because the vibe is slightly lacking for us (it&rsquo;s on the stuffier side of the jazz spectrum). The place is so small that patrons are often given a ticket to come back at a designated slot. The ticket gets you into </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mezzrow</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> across the street, which we argue is a destination in itself. Mezzrow is intimate and classy but without the high ticket prices of Smalls, and although you won&rsquo;t get the same consistent line-up of famous musicians, this is where many of the best cats come to practice and find their feet.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Fat Cat</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_60.jpg\" alt=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-3)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>Nez B., Yelp</em></p>\r\n<p>Fat Cat is a perfect introduction to jazz for those of you who don&rsquo;t want to jump in at the deep end. Sure, it&rsquo;s not as serious or high calibre as the other options here, but it&rsquo;s one of the most fun places to spend an evening in the city. Jazz plays in the background while you can enjoy a range of games, including ping pong and boardgames. The whole combination of music, beer and friendly vibes makes for a great Friday night hangout at a reasonable price while still being able to catch that iconic New York jazz.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>The Nest</strong></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/1_62.jpg\" alt=\"Our favourite jazz bars in NYC (Image-4)\" width=\"\" height=\"\" />Photo: <em>The Nest, Facebook&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Nest, Brooklyn, describes itself as &lsquo;an everything venue&rsquo;, but it&rsquo;s the jazz shows that really stand out at this hidden gem of a bar. Located in the heart of Flatbush, the music at the Nest is that old school, grimy jazz that feels authentic to the bone. The atmosphere of the basement show room is relaxed, with dark, moody lighting and cheap drinks. This is the epitome of where jazz is today, without the feel of commercialisation that some other jazz bars have.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', '1_19.jpg', 1, '2020-02-07 06:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(355, 'Ways to maintain social contact while social distancing', 1, 'ways-to-maintain-social-contact-while-social-distancing', '', 'Ways to maintain social contact while social distancing', 'Ways to maintain social contact while social distancing', 'Social distancing means we have to be more creative about how we socialize with our friends and family, but that doesn’t mean it’s impossible. With modern technology, there are plenty of ways you can stay in contact with loved ones and maintain social contact with the outside while staying safely indoors.', '<p>Social distancing means we have to be more creative about how we socialize with our friends and family, but that doesn&rsquo;t mean it&rsquo;s impossible. With modern technology, there are plenty of ways you can stay in contact with loved ones and maintain social contact with the outside while staying safely indoors.</p>', '<p>Social distancing means we have to be more creative about how we socialize with our friends and family, but that doesn&rsquo;t mean it&rsquo;s impossible. With modern technology, there are plenty of ways you can stay in contact with loved ones and maintain social contact with the outside while staying safely indoors.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>1.&nbsp;Use video chat or a phone call</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The most simple of these options is to pick up the phone, sharing either your audio or your audio and video with your loved ones via apps such as <a href=\"https://support.apple.com/en-gb/HT204380\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Facetime</a>, <a href=\"http://skype.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Skype</a> or <a href=\"zoom.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Zoom</a>. Just seeing a human face, even if not in person, can be enough to make you feel socially connected to the world again.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>2. Work on a creative project with others</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Usually, we socialize through activities. There&rsquo;s no reason that social distancing has to be any different. Working (remotely) on a creative project with friends, family or even likeminded strangers you connect with over the internet is the perfect way to stay socially connected, especially as collaboration is closely related to making us feel connected to others.</p>\r\n<p>So why not ask a friend if they want to write one line of a short story each a day, or write a song together on video chat where you play the guitar while they sing. The possibilities are endless and you&rsquo;ll have the added bonus of having a unique piece of art at the end of this all which will be a living diary to your struggles (or joy) in isolation.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>3. Go to a (virtual) social event with others</strong></h1>\r\n<p>The amount of online social events popping up on social media right now is astounding. Whether you pre-plan to attend virtually with a friend or tune in solo, you can enjoy concerts from home as well as video chat parties run by your regular NYC nightlife hangouts and much, much more. The app Houseparty takes video chat to the next level allows you to play games and interact with your friends in new and exciting ways, whilst online bar* has cropped up as a free space to grab a drink and meet new or existing friends in a virtual setting.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>4. Exercise with others</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Whether you normally engage in exercise classes or just want to try something new, video chat exercise classes are a great way to get your daily dose of social contact with others over the internet. Many local NYC fitness trainers are currently advertising live online exercise classes at varying times (check their <a href=\"http://instagram.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Instagram</a> and <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Facebook</a> pages; we love the daily 8am group workout by <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/BlinkFitness/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Blink Fitness</a>), or if you fancy a smaller group you can coordinate to watch the same fitness video with a group of friends and simply turn on your video chat to feel as though you&rsquo;re exercising together, despite being physically apart.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>5. Try co-working</strong></h1>\r\n<p>Many people won&rsquo;t have much free time during this period of social distancing, as working from home brings its own challenges. But that doesn&rsquo;t mean you have to miss out on social contact. Arrange a time to co-work with members of your household where you sit together in near-silence or have allotted times in which you can speak and where you can work; this will ensure that you get your work done while still getting social contact.</p>\r\n<p>The same activity can be replicated on video chat; pre-arrange to co-work with a friend and video chat them, putting the camera to one side while you both work and you&rsquo;ll see how much more social you feel when you trick your brain into thinking someone else is in the room. This can even help productivity, as miniature breaks to socialize while still getting on with work will help you maintain focus and positivity in these tricky times.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '9.jpg', 1, '2020-03-25 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(352, '5 Positive Ways to Pass the Time in Isolation', 1, '5-positive-ways-to-pass-the-time-in-isolation', '', '5 Positive Ways to Pass the Time in Isolation | Outpost Club blog', '5 Positive Ways to Pass the Time in Isolation', 'So, you’re stuck in quarantine and suddenly you seem to have a lot more free time on your hands. It’s easy in this situation to proclaim yourself bored and turn to Netflix or napping, but there are more positive ways to pass the time that are actually fun. Check out our recommendations below.', '<p>So, you&rsquo;re stuck in quarantine and suddenly you seem to have a lot more free time on your hands. It&rsquo;s easy in this situation to proclaim yourself bored and turn to Netflix or napping, but there are more positive ways to pass the time that are actually fun. Check out our recommendations below.</p>', '<p>So, you&rsquo;re stuck in quarantine and suddenly you seem to have a lot more free time on your hands. It&rsquo;s easy in this situation to proclaim yourself bored and turn to Netflix or napping, but there are more positive ways to pass the time that are actually fun. Check out our recommendations below.</p>\r\n<h3>1. Learn a language.</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now is a great opportunity to learn that language you&rsquo;ve been wanting to for years. The intense time at home will give you the chance to prepare and look forward to a time in future when you can visit this country (because this will be over one day!). There are plenty of free online sources and apps which teach language skills. We love </span><a href=\"http://www.babbel.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Babbel</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and </span><a href=\"http://www.duolingo.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Duolingo</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which can both be worked into your daily routine in small and regular doses.</span></p>\r\n<h3>2.&nbsp;Broaden your mind.</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are a whole host of online platforms offering free courses to educate yourself during this period of isolation. We love </span><a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Coursera</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a digital platform offering classes and qualifications at all levels, including </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Yale&rsquo;s </span><a href=\"https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-quarantine-yale-university-classes-free-online/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">most popular class</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, for free. Or why not take classes from leading figures in your chosen area with </span><a href=\"https://www.masterclass.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Masterclass</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">? New York&rsquo;s </span><a href=\"https://writingclasses.com/classes/video?fbclid=IwAR0fEt3RhenCNR1K5Wt_nuFVlBcEtBjgzPAnfYe-h054ASzmhwEIjZV-clo\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Gotham Writers</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> has also switched to online classes, teaching everything from novel writing to business writing.</span></p>\r\n<h3>3. Take up or develop a hobby.</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Again, this time can be used to develop or pick up a new skill. Don&rsquo;t have any hobbies? No problem, it&rsquo;s not too late to start.&nbsp; Ever wanted to play an instrument? Now&rsquo;s the perfect time, with online </span><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCP1ZfPYU0cjhXXnuxlLVhqQ\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">guitar lessons</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and many more available across the web.</span></p>\r\n<h3>4. Get some culture from home.</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Just because you&rsquo;re at home doesn&rsquo;t mean you can&rsquo;t get some culture in your spare time. In fact, the global lockdown is seeing many cultural institutions offering more services for free than ever before. The </span><a href=\"http://www.metopera.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Metropolitan Opera</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is streaming live performances </span><a href=\"https://www.metopera.org/user-information/coronavirus-updates/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">every day at 7:30 p.m. ET</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and local NYC institutions such as </span><a href=\"https://www.bowerypoetry.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Bowery Poetry</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> are holding regular live readings over social media platforms.</span></p>\r\n<h3>5. Catch up with friends (virtually).</h3>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For the first time in probably a long time, all your friends in many different countries are going to be at home with (probably) flexible schedules. Take this opportunity to reconnect (virtually) with your friends. This will both lift your mood and strengthen your friendships, making something positive out of this bad situation! Remember that you&rsquo;re not alone and everyone is struggling in their own way, so anything you can do to list the mood of others will be positive for all.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>At first look, it may appear difficult to find intriguing things to do at home, but there are so many interesting things in the world that all you need is a desire. Now is the perfect time to <a href=\"../philadelphia\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">rent a room</a> at Outpost Club, so seize the opportunity!</p>', 'joel-muniz-XqXJJhK-c08-unsplash.jpg', 1, '2020-03-19 05:00:00', '2022-11-01 07:36:40', NULL, 0, 0),
(353, 'Ways to stay healthy at home', 1, 'ways-to-stay-healthy-at-home', '', 'Ways to stay healthy at home', 'Ways to stay healthy at home', 'When you’re cooped up during quarantine, it’s easy to fall into unhealthy habits. But it doesn’t have to be this way. With a focus on your body, mind and soul, you can make sure you come out the other end of this even healthier than when you entered.', '<p>When you&rsquo;re cooped up during quarantine, it&rsquo;s easy to fall into unhealthy habits. But it doesn&rsquo;t have to be this way. With a focus on your body, mind and soul you can come out the other end of this even healthier than when you entered.</p>', '<p>When you&rsquo;re cooped up during quarantine, it&rsquo;s easy to fall into unhealthy habits. But it doesn&rsquo;t have to be this way. With a focus on your body, mind and soul you can come out the other end of this even healthier than when you entered.</p>\r\n<h1><strong>Your body</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With some forward planning, it&rsquo;s perfectly possible to keep your body healthy during quarantine. Of course, the combination of diet and exercise is the key here, but that doesn&rsquo;t mean you have to restrict yourself. In terms of diet, the key is getting your daily vitamins. Make sure you get at least 5 portions of fruit and vegetables a day and remember, the more colors on your plate, the better, because that means that you&rsquo;re getting a good spread across vitamins. You might also want to take a vitamin supplement during this period, as unfortunately your sun intake is likely to be limited by&nbsp;spending most of the day indoors. And don&rsquo;t worry about snacking left right and centre, that&rsquo;s totally normal in such anxious times, just be sure to snack on healthy foods like carrot sticks, nuts or other veggies if you can.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When it comes to exercise, some is always better than none at all. There are plenty of HIIT workouts, yoga classes and other videos available on Youtube. It can be difficult to motivate yourself in times such as this, which is why local NYC gyms such as <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/BlinkFitness/?ref=search&amp;s_tn__=%2Cd%2CP-R&amp;eid=ARAHcR3nnYfMIGOBqHjYREw_MhxUl4arRZfBxT03eqiujlGcGMKWJTZyY1dTojS9bvq_BkInm7P2n6Qt\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Blink Fitness</a>&nbsp;have started regular free group training sessions so you can feel connected to others from the comfort of your own home. If you&rsquo;re not a gym bunny, this can all seem a bit overwhelming, but simply throwing on your headphones and blaring Whitney Houston in your ears while you dance like crazy around the room is also exercise (and let&rsquo;s face it, it&rsquo;s pretty darn fun)--so get creative with your exercise and go easy on the self-judgment.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Your mind</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We need to both&nbsp;contract and relax your mind like a muscle to keep it healthy. To keep yourself thinking straight, it&rsquo;s important to have a focus, whether that&rsquo;s work or if you&rsquo;re not currently working, then some other way to stretch your mind, such as learning a new skill or reading. The <a href=\"http://nypl.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">New York Public Library</a>&nbsp;allows&nbsp;New Yorkers to sign up for a library card online and you can start borrowing ebooks right away. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But don&rsquo;t put too much pressure on yourself to be productive during quarantine. You&rsquo;ve also got to let your mind relax during this trying time. Try d</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">oing something fun which has been on your bucket list, like watching that list of best movies of all time or downloading The Sims in classic 90s nostalgia. Now more than ever is the time to indulge in your guilty pleasures--no one will ever know if you watch Disney on repeat or learn all the words to Eminem&rsquo;s &ldquo;Lose Yourself&rdquo; with this time! It&rsquo;s also good to keep in contact with at least a small number of friends or family during quarantine; although you can&rsquo;t spend your whole day replying to everyone, the human contact you get from video calling or simply texting others will give your mental health a boost&nbsp;in these trying times.</span></p>\r\n<h1><strong>Your soul</strong></h1>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It&rsquo;s also key to keep your soul healthy during quarantine. Self-care is an underrated part of keeping ourselves healthy and now is the perfect time to fix that. Self-care means looking after yourself just as you would a friend, instead of beating yourself up, setting unrealistically high expectations of yourself or just generally being mean to yourself. If you wouldn\'t do it to a friend, don\'t do it to yourself. Knowing your worth and that you are loved by others is easier said than done, of course, but you can take simple steps towards wellbeing through self-care practices such as engaging in a favorite hobby (even when you have a work deadline!), turning your phone off when you&rsquo;re stressed, treating yourself in whatever way works best for you (think facemasks, your favourite desserts, or buying that top on <a href=\"http://www.asos.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">ASOS</a> you&rsquo;ve been staring at since the beginning of quarantine!)</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For some people, spiritual activities such as yoga can be beneficial for your wellbeing, but that doesn&rsquo;t mean you have to do it that way if the \"traditional\" forms of self-care don\'t suit you. Self-care comes in many forms--even allowing yourself to cry can be healing. The important thing is to look inside yourself and think deeply about what you need to feel good during quarantine and to do it without feelings of guilt. And remember, being healthy on the outside comes from within.</span></p>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>', 'ways-to-stay-healthy-at-home.jpg', 1, '2020-03-23 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0);
