(405, 'Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown', 1, 'visit-these-beautiful-public-spaces-in-midtown', '', 'Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown', 'Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown', '', '<p>Some of our favorite places in Manhattan are easy to walk right past if you&rsquo;re not looking for them. These are the places that are reliable standbys when you&rsquo;ve been walking forever and need a break, want somewhere besides the subway to work on that book you just started, or are just looking for a relaxing space to chill for a few minutes.</p>', '<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/midtown-main-photo.jpg\" alt=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-1)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Some of our favorite places in Manhattan are easy to walk right past if you&rsquo;re not looking for them. These are the places that are reliable standbys when you&rsquo;ve been walking forever and need a break, want somewhere besides the subway to work on that book you just started, or are just looking for a relaxing space to chill for a few minutes.</p>\r\n<p>Spaces like these dot Manhattan, but are especially concentrated in Midtown, where the amount of high-rise buildings and skyscrapers have led to a wide array of public plazas being opened thanks to the city&rsquo;s Zoning Resolution of 1961. That resolution allowed developers to build out more area in exchange for creating adjacent space that&rsquo;s open to the public &mdash; and that&rsquo;s exactly why you&rsquo;re likely to stumble across at least one tiny park just by taking a walk.</p>\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re looking for a space to relax in Midtown Manhattan, start here:</p>\r\n<h2>Paley Park</h2>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/paley-park.jpg\" alt=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-2)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Paley Park is a delightful pocket park located on the site of the old Stork Club, which was considered one of the most prestigious nightclubs in the world until it closed in 1965. The park, <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1967/09/20/archives/paley-park-a-corner-of-quiet-delights-amid-citys-bustle-53d-st.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"> which opened in 1967</a>, features open seating and a 20-foot waterfall.</p>\r\n<p><em>3 East 53rd Street, between Madison and Fifth Avenues</em></p>\r\n<h2>Greenacre Park</h2>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/greenacre-park.jpg\" alt=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-3)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Greenacre Park is perhaps one of the most well-known pocket parks in New York City. The park is three levels and includes flexible seating, gorgeous greenery and a 25-foot waterfall, along with an outdoor cafe. Greenacre Park opened in 1971 and has since won a plethora of awards and been listed on the National Register of Historic Places.</p>\r\n<p>If you visit, please keep in mind that the park places a high priority on maintaining a serene space, and as the park is technically private property, park staff reserve the right to ask people to leave.</p>\r\n<p><em>217 East 51st Street, between 2nd and 3rd Avenues</em></p>\r\n<h2>Ford Foundation Atrium</h2>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/ford-foundations-atrium.jpg\" alt=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-4)\" /></p>\r\n<p>The Ford Foundation&rsquo;s atrium garden is a breathtaking surprise if you don&rsquo;t know what to expect when you walk inside. The open, airy atrium features floor-to-ceiling windows and is home to nearly 40 species of trees, vines and shrubs, <a href=\"https://www.fordfoundation.org/about/the-ford-foundation-center-for-social-justice/visitor-information/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"> according to the foundation</a>. Adding to the peaceful atmosphere are a reflecting pool and a reverberating fountain, as well as a sensory section that includes braille signage and audio interpretation.</p>\r\n<p>The garden is open to the public Monday&ndash;Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m.</p>\r\n<p><em>321 East 42nd Street, between 1st and 2nd Avenues</em></p>\r\n<h2>Dag Hammarskjold Plaza</h2>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-5), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/dag-plaza.jpg\" alt=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-5)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Dag Hammarskjold Plaza is a sweeping public plaza the width of an entire avenue block. In addition to plenty of greenery, the plaza boasts a cafe, greenmarket and public art exhibits, as well as the Katharine Hepburn Garden, shown above.</p>\r\n<p><em>E. 47 Street between 1st and 2nd Avenues</em></p>\r\n<h2>IBM Building</h2>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-6), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/ibm-building.jpg\" alt=\"Visit these beautiful public spaces in Midtown (Image-6)\" /></p>\r\n<p>The sprawling IBM atrium is home to 11 groves of bamboo trees, a sculpture garden, flexible seating and temporary art displays.<a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/15/realestate/public-realm-private-property-new-study-identifies-rates-hundreds-spaces-that.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\"> A review</a> of hundreds of New York&rsquo;s privately owned public spaces stated that the atrium is \"of such high quality that they draw visitors from around the city.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><em>590 Madison Avenue, at 57th Street</em></p>', 'midtown-main-photo.jpg', 0, '2022-04-01 05:00:00', NULL, NULL, 0, 0),
(406, '5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan', 1, '5-unique-cafes-to-check-out-in-manhattan', '', '5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan', '5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan', '', '<p>One of the great things about living in New York is the sheer variety of experiences that are available to you even while doing something as simple as grabbing a coffee. Below, find five of our favorite Manhattan cafes, all of which have put their own spin on the business.</p>', '<p>One of the great things about living in New York is the sheer variety of experiences that are available to you even while doing something as simple as grabbing a coffee. Below, find five of our favorite Manhattan cafes, all of which have put their own spin on the business.</p>\r\n<h3><a href=\"https://greatsofcraft.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Greats of Craft</a></h3>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-1), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/the-greats-of-craft.jpg\" alt=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image 1)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Aside from having a truly excellent literary name, The Greats of Craft excels at wearing multiple hats: it&rsquo;s a cafe that turns into a bar by night, so you can bring your laptop and order a pistachio milk latte in the afternoon and stick around to meet a friend for drinks.</p>\r\n<p>The Greats of Craft has live music on the weekends and trivia on Tuesdays.</p>\r\n<p><em>Midtown East | 983 1st Avenue, at 54th Street</em></p>\r\n<h3><a href=\"https://www.urbanbackyardnyc.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Urban Backyard</a></h3>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-2), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/urban-backyard.jpg\" alt=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-2)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Urban Backyard is a sustainability-focused cafe that is well-known for its specialty cupcakes and relaxing greenery-filled space. They make their own sauces and syrups, and also sell some merchandise.</p>\r\n<p><em>SoHo | 180 Mulberry Street, near Broome Street</em></p>\r\n<h3><a href=\"https://www.reminyc.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">REMI Flower and Coffee</a></h3>\r\n<p>REMI Flower and Coffee is exactly what it sounds like: a flower shop and cafe in one. You can grab a cappuccino, nestle in among the flora with a book and easily forget that you&rsquo;re sitting in the middle of Manhattan and not in a secret garden.</p>\r\n<p><em>Midtown East | 906 2nd Avenue, between 48th and 49th</em></p>\r\n<h3><a href=\"https://www.devocion.com/pages/devocion-cafe-flatiron-district-new-york-ny\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Devocion</a></h3>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-3), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/devocion.jpg\" alt=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-3)\" /></p>\r\n<p>Devoci&oacute;n is known for beautiful, airy interiors and dang good coffee. It&rsquo;s the perfect place to get creative work done &mdash; don&rsquo;t be surprised if you end up surrounded by people writing and drawing. In addition to a vibrant but peaceful environment, the company also says they&rsquo;re the only brand in the world that roasts &ldquo;true farm-fresh coffee only 10 days after leaving origin.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><em>Flatiron | 25 East 20th Street</em></p>\r\n<h3><a href=\"https://blackcatles.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Black Cat LES</a></h3>\r\n<p class=\"img\"><img title=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-4), outpost-club.com\" src=\"../files/uploads/blog/black-cat.jpg\" alt=\"5 Unique Cafes to Check Out in Manhattan (Image-4)\" /></p>\r\n<p>We say the city is our living room, and that&rsquo;s never more true than when you&rsquo;re at Black Cat. The spacious coffee house is filled with a variety of seating, from family-style benches to large poufy armchairs, and the vibe is welcoming. You can tell this is a neighborhood shop. Events include open-mic and comedy shows, themed movie and Netflix nights, academic lectures and tutoring.</p>\r\n<p><em>Lower East Side | 172 Rivington Street</em></p>', 'the-greats-of-craft.jpg', 0, '2022-04-06 05:00:00', '2022-07-06 02:07:25', NULL, 0, 0);
