(232, 231, NULL, 'event-process', '', 'Event Process', 'Event Process', '', 'Event Process', '', '', '<p><em>Good events do not just appear out of thin air. They are requested, funded, planned, and executed. Events take time, and therefore Outpost Club needs a process to hold interesting, professional, and fun events for our members. Here is how an event idea turns into reality at Outpost Club.</em></p>\r\n<h3>General Background Info</h3>\r\n<p>Events are worked into the position descriptions of many employees at Outpost Club. First is the House Leader and Outpost Club Support Team position: each house has a House Leader, and each house leader must hold two events per month. These house events can be for their house&rsquo;s member only, or they can invite people from all houses.</p>\r\n<p>The second position is the community manager: the community manager holds an additional two events per month that are company-wide events. This ideally allows each Outpost Club member to attend one event per-week. House leaders are also expected to be involved in company-wide events if/when the are available, and they should be prepared to help with promotion (inviting people to the events, putting up flyers) preparation (buying food, setting up decorations, etc.), and execution (meeting people at the door to greet them, directing people where to go, serving food, etc.).</p>\r\n<p>The last position affiliated with events is the Social Media and Marketing Manager, who will design the event poster beforehand, attend and take pictures during the event, make a blog or social post after the event, and distribute this post to the necessary channels. This person will also create the newsletter including the dates, times and descriptions of events, and links to last months events. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Event Request/Approval</h3>\r\n<p>Event&rsquo;s for each month are schedule, requested, and approved during the middle of the month before. So for example, events for the month of June are requested, and approved by the second to third week of May.</p>\r\n<p>To make a request, house leaders and community managers can go to the online to the current members portal and request to hold an event. Once all are submitted, Outpost Club management will approve the budget and send approvals to all house leader and community managers. The community manager is responsible for collecting the responses and getting approval from management.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Event Planning</h3>\r\n<p>Once events are approved, now it is time to start working on the specifics. All the information given in the event request form is subject to change. The time, date, budget, and even the event idea itself can change between when requested and when executed&hellip; And that&rsquo;s okay! However, this variability is why it is so important to plan as much as possible, as soon as possible.</p>\r\n<h4>Here are some essential questions House Leaders and Community Managers must answer.</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What can affect my events well-being?</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If it&rsquo;s an outdoor event, what\'s the weather?</li>\r\n<li>If it&rsquo;s a holiday event, who is going home for the holidays? Will people be around?</li>\r\n<li>If it had to be reschedule, when would it be rescheduled to?</li>\r\n<li>If its a ticketed event, when are tickets going to run out? What happens when they do? How do I notify members?</li>\r\n<li>How do I tell people who do not use facebook about my event?</li>\r\n<li>If the event is happening at your house, what happens if something else is going on in the space you want to hold your event in?</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><em>For this question, basically all you have to do is notify the house group chat that you will be using the space at a certain time</em>&gt;</li>\r\n<li>Who is coming to the event?</li>\r\n<li>What are you going to buy for the event and how are you going to buy it?</li>\r\n<li>What do I need from Outpost Club to complete this event successfully?</li>\r\n<li>Who will manage the event during the event? For example:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who&rsquo;s cooking?</li>\r\n<li>Who is making drinks?</li>\r\n<li>Who will organize the mini events within the event?</li>\r\n<li>Who will set up decorations?</li>\r\n<li>Who will do the music?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Answering these questions will help you plan the event so that there is nothing to worry about once the event starts.</h4>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Event Promotion</h3>\r\n<p>This is arguably the most important part of the event. You can&rsquo;t have an event if no one shows up. Additionally, the more people at an event, the better! The community manager will create all the events and post them in the private facebook group for all current members to see. The event will also be created on the website so members without a facebook can still attend.</p>\r\n<p><strong>When creating the event digitally, the community manager must include:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Date</li>\r\n<li>Time</li>\r\n<li>Location</li>\r\n<li>Description of the event</li>\r\n<li>An event picture, designed by the Social Media Manager</li>\r\n<li>Associated prices for members, friends, and alumni<em> and a link to purchasing page</em></li>\r\n<li>Link to the website event page (from facebook) link to the facebook event page (from the website)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Event Execution</h3>\r\n<p>This is the fun part! This part includes making sure all the party supplies are purchased and organized, things are prepared (the grill is hot, the movie is purchased, ect.) and that YOU ARE PRESENT! Don&rsquo;t forget, you get to decide when the event starts and when it ends. A couple other things to remember when holding events:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Outpost Club does not provide alcohol for events, but members who can legally drink are more than welcome to bring alcohol</li>\r\n<li>If an event is being held in the common of the house, make sure to be respectful of people in the rooms adjacent to the common space. If the event goes past quiet hours, make sure to get permission of the people in those rooms.</li>\r\n<li>Friends of members are welcome to come to events, they just need to buy a ticket, no matter the event. This is because Outpost Club members have already paid for the event through their membership fee, and if their friend shows up, they have not. Same goes for Alumni, however their payment is reduced in comparison to friends who have never stayed with Outpost.</li>\r\n<li>Have fun at events, but also remember that you are the host. Don&rsquo;t drink too much, but have a good time! Others will see this and have a good time as well.</li>\r\n<li>If an event goes overtime and members at the house want to sleep, take the event to a bar or a public place! Nothing is stopping people from continuing to hang out, just make sure to be respectful of members&rsquo; sleep schedules.</li>\r\n<li>Go knock on peoples doors if the event is at home, or you are leaving from the house, you are sure to get some more people this way!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Event Reporting</h3>\r\n<p>Once the event is over, it&rsquo;s not done! There are some final things you&rsquo;ll need to do to complete the responsibility of holding an event:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fill out the event report. This will ask you to:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Answer questions on how the event went: what went well and what could be improved</li>\r\n<li>Report attendance</li>\r\n<li>Report expenditures, as well as the need for a refund from Outpost (if applicable)</li>\r\n<li>To send pictures of the event</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Lastly, if it makes sense, the Social Media Manager will write a piece on the event and post it to the blog and facebook groups! That way others will be encouraged to come to future events.</strong></p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Company-Wide Events Versus House Events</h3>\r\n<p>At Out</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 12, '', '', '', '', 244, 1, 0, 0, 0, 'Event Process', 0, 0, 'a:0:{}', '', '', '', '', 0, '0.00000000', '0.00000000', 0, '', NULL),
(233, 231, NULL, 'event-ideas', '', 'Event Ideas', 'Event Ideas', '', 'Event Ideas', '', '', '<ul>\r\n<li>Comedy Nights</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>UCB Theaters NYC - has two comedy clubs in NYC</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"https://ucbtheatre.com/\">https://ucbtheatre.com</a> or <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/ucbtny\">https://www.facebook.com/ucbtny</a></li>\r\n<li>Best UCB event - WHIPLASH (free comedy show with famous people sometimes, 11pm monday nights) at UCB Hell\'s Kitchen</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Creek and the Cave - comedy club in Long Island City</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://creeklic.com/calendar/\">http://creeklic.com/calendar/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>The Laughing Budda - hosts comedy nights around the city</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Buddha Room at Klimat Lounge, 77 East 7th St.</li>\r\n<li>The Stand, 239 3rd Ave.</li>\r\n<li>Greenwich Village Comedy Club, 99 Macdougal St.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://laughingbuddhacomedy.com/schedule/\">http://laughingbuddhacomedy.com/schedule/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Gotham Comedy Club: <a href=\"http://gothamcomedyclub.com/showsCalendar.cfm\">http://gothamcomedyclub.com/showsCalendar.cfm</a></li>\r\n<li>The Comedy Cellar</li>\r\n<li>The Bell House</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Event Spaces just holding events</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Bell House: cool events of all types in Red Hook: <a href=\"https://www.thebellhouseny.com/\">https://www.thebellhouseny.com</a></li>\r\n<li>Nowadays</li>\r\n<li>House of Yes</li>\r\n<li>Braven Brewing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Sporting events</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Knicks, Nets, Jets, Giants, Rangers, Islanders, Red Bulls, NYCFC, Yankees, Mets, Tennis (Arthur Ashe Stadium)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Beach day: Rockaway Beach</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Go by Subway or Ferry</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Movie nights</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>At the house - movie or new show premieres</li>\r\n<li>Out of the house - Movie theaters</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Great inexpensive movie experience: Syndicated BK</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://syndicatedbk.com/events/\">http://syndicatedbk.com/events/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Late-night shows - wait in line and you might be able to see these shows! Instructions in the link below</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.freetoursbyfoot.com/new-york-tv-show-tickets/\">http://www.freetoursbyfoot.com/new-york-tv-show-tickets/</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Plays and Musicals:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Buy same-day matinee tickets for cheap showings! Tips and tricks below: <a href=\"http://www.freetoursbyfoot.com/new-york-tv-show-tickets/\">http://www.freetoursbyfoot.com/new-york-tv-show-tickets/</a> &nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Poker Night</li>\r\n<li>Class based athletics: yoga, cross fit, martial arts, meditation</li>\r\n<li>Speaker nights</li>\r\n<li>Bar crawls</li>\r\n<li>Game Night</li>\r\n<li>Physical activities (running, soccer games, yoga, boxing etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Concerts/Music Festivals</li>\r\n<li>Art Exhibits/Museums</li>\r\n<li>Barbeques/Communal dinners/Potlucks</li>\r\n<li>Community/Neighborhood Initiatives</li>\r\n<li>Local events already taking place</li>\r\n<li>Community Service events</li>\r\n<li>Protests, marches, etc.</li>\r\n<li>Get in contact with local community leaders, groups</li>\r\n<li>activities etc.</li>\r\n<li>Karaoke</li>\r\n<li>&ldquo;Who&rsquo;s shit is this???&rdquo; event - buy food and beer, then clean out the fridge, cabinets, and bathrooms (lotions, body washes, shampoos etc.) while listening to music and hanging out</li>\r\n<li>Outings -</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ski Trips</li>\r\n<li>Hiking Trips</li>\r\n<li>Cruises</li>\r\n<li>Sightseeing</li>\r\n<li>Going to Governors Island</li>\r\n<li>Going to Fire Island</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Escape Rooms/Quest rooms</li>\r\n<li>Pizza making, nacho making, or taco night</li>\r\n<li>Geeks who drink - <a href=\"https://www.geekswhodrink.com/schedule/NY\">https://www.geekswhodrink.com/schedule/NY</a></li>\r\n<li>Salsa nights - https://www.clubcachenyc.com/</li>\r\n<li>Karaoke Night: &n